<1ST_LINE>u i AM-CentralAmerica-Peace 1stLd-Writethru a0841 06-22 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Central America-Peace, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0841,0427</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honduras Rejects Nicaraguan Demand For Border Inspection</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with Honduras and Nicaragua rejecting each other's
demands, meeting breaking up without communique, details. No
pickup. ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Honduras on Wednesday rejected a
Nicaraguan demand that it allow inspection of its border region by
an international team for U.S.-supported rebel bases, a foreign
ministry spokesman said.
   Spokesman Eugenio Castro told The Associated Press in an
interview that Nicaragua's foreign minister, Miguel D'Escoto, made
the request at a seven-hour meeting that also included the foreign
ministers from Honduras, Guatemala, Costa Rica and El Salvador.
   The request, in the form of a draft treaty, called for
inspection of Honduras' border region with Nicaragua by an
international team made up of Canadian and East German observers,
Castro said.
   The foreign ministers met privately first at a hotel and later
at the Foreign Ministry to discuss progress of a regional peace
plan signed in August last year.
   The five countries' presidents signed the peace plan to
negotiate an end to the U.S.-supported insurgency against
Nicaragua's Sandinista regime and leftist guerrilla wars in
U.S.-backed El Salvador and Guatemala.
   Officials at the meeting Wednesday said they would issue a joint
communique when they ended their discussions. But the meeting broke
up suddenly and no communique was issued when Honduras rejected the
Nicaraguan demand.
   Hondura's foreign minister, Carlos Lopez Contreras, demanded at
the meeting that Nicaragua withdraw complaints filed against
Honduras and Costa Rica at the World Court in The Hague, Holland,
claiming the two countries harbored anti-Nicaraguan rebels, Castro
said.
   Castro said D'Escoto rejected the Honduran demand.
   Honduras claims it has none of the rebels, known as Contras,
inside its territory and the Contras claim they operate inside
Nicaragua. But there have been numerous reports the rebels have
maintained supply and staging camps along the southern border since
they started fighting to overthrow Nicaragua's Sandinista regime in
1982.
   A lesser number of such camps were also reported at one time
along Costa Rica's northeastern border with Nicaragua, but the
reports ceased since one rebel group stopped operating in the area
three years ago.
   The regional peace plan calls for cease-fires, reconciliation
talks between governments and opposition groups, an end to military
aid to insurgents in the region, and reforms to bring greater
democracy to Central America.
   So far, a tenuous cease-fire has been in force since March 23 in
Nicaragua. The conflicts continue in Guatemala and El Salvador.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
