<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FairHousing     06-22 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fair Housing,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Compromise Expected to Speed Approval of Fair Housing Measure</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: No House action likely until midafternoon EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress is expected to act quickly to enact
legislation to strengthen the enforcement of the nation's fair
housing law now that Democrats and the Reagan administration have
worked out a compromise.
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., one of the measure's strongest
supporters, called the compromise ``a giant step toward enacting
legislation that will make the promise of fair housing a reality.''
   President Reagan and Vice President George Bush gave their
approval Tuesday to an agreement reached by Democrats and civil
rights groups with Republicans and realtors, permitting someone
charged with housing discrimination to have the accusation
considered in federal court.
   Currently, the Department of Housing and Urban Development can
offer to mediate disputes only if both parties agree to
participate. If they don't, individuals must bring private
lawsuits. The Justice Department can intervene only if government
lawyers detect a pattern of discrimination against a particular
group.
   The bill that came out of the Democratic-controlled House
Judiciary Committee earlier this month would allow those who
believe they have been discriminated against in the sale or rental
of housing to bring complaints before an administrative law judge.
The judge would have the power to levy fines and issue injunctions,
and the decision could then be appealed through the courts.
   Administration officials opposed the measure because, they said,
monetary damages should be assessed only by the courts.
   Rep. Hamilton Fish Jr., R-N.Y., crafted an amendment to the bill
that received support from the opposing parties _ giving the
accused party the opportunity to go into federal court first to
have his case heard.
   ``The fair housing law, enacted two decades ago at a time of
national mourning and strife, stands as a symbol of our national
commitment to the goals of equal housing opportunity for all
Americans,'' Fish said at a news conference. ``Unfortunately,
however, the reality confronting victims of housing discrimination
falls far short of our lofty legal goal.
   ``The proposed bill, together with my amendment, provides
victims a quick and effective means of seeking redress,'' he said.
``Passage of this legislation will boost confidence in the
effectiveness of our fair housing law.''
   Rep. Robert H. Michel, R-Ill., the House minority leader, said
that Reagan, in Toronto for the economic summit, told Michel that
he believes the compromise ``preserves the constitutional right to
jury trials and hopes the Congress will move quickly on the
legislation to strengthen fair housing laws.''
   Bush, the Republican presidential nominee-to-be, said the Fish
amendment will strengthen the fair housing law by giving HUD
Secretary Samuel Pierce ``the necessary enforcement powers to more
effectively combat housing discrimination.''
   A similar measure is pending in the Senate, which is expected to
act as soon as the House approves the measure.
   The bill also extends anti-discrimination provisions to families
with children and to the disabled, and requires that all new
apartment buildings be constructed to permit access by the
handicapped to some units. It also requires landlords to permit
disabled individuals, at their own expense, to adapt homes to suit
their needs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
