<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 0342EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-S&LLosses     06-22 0694</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-S&L Losses,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gap Between Healthy and Sick S&Ls Widens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The gulf between the haves and have-nots in
the savings and loan industry is yawning wider as institutions in
Texas continue to bleed red ink.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board said Tuesday that the 3,118
federally insured savings institutions lost a staggering $3.78
billion in the first three months of this year, down only slightly
from the $3.81 billion post-Depression record set in the last
quarter of 1987.
   Bank board economist James Barth said 2,164 institutions, 69
percent of the industry, posted a $1.3 billion profit in the first
quarter. But that was overwhelmed by the $5.1 billion lost by the
remaining 954 money-losing institutions.
   Barth said three states plagued by moribund oil industries and
depressed real estate prices _ Texas, Oklahoma and Louisiana _
accounted for 80 percent of the first-quarter loss.
   Texas alone, where nearly half of the S&Ls _ 133 of 279 _ are
considered insolvent, racked up losses of $3.48 billion.
   The 20 weakest S&Ls accounted for $3 billion of the loss, up
from $2.4 billion in the fourth quarter, and the weakest 50
accounted for $3.7 billion. A single institution, Sun Belt Savings
Association in Dallas, lost $1.2 billion.
   ``We do have a bifurcated industry,'' Barth said.
   Last year, savings associations had their worst year since the
Great Depression, losing $7.6 billion. If the first three months
are any indication, 1988 is likely to set another record.
   By comparison, the nation's 13,541 commercial banks earned $3.6
billion in 1987, the smallest profit since the Depression, but
recovered with a $5 billion gain in the first quarter of 1988.
   Still, Barth noted some hopeful signs for the savings industry.
   The number of insolvent S&Ls under generally accepted accounting
rules fell for the first time in two years from 518 to 504.
   Also, earnings at thrifts considered solvent under less-strict
regulatory rules _ about 90 percent of the industry _ totaled $600
million, compared with a $200 million loss in the fourth quarter of
1987.
   And, preliminary data for April indicate the industry as a whole
could turn an operating profit in the second quarter.
   ``There are a lot of things in these numbers to suggest that
while the problem is terrible, it is not getting worse,'' said
Martin A. Regalia, chief economist of the National Council of
Savings Institutions.
   ``It is bottoming out somewhat. I don't mean to put a favorable
light on a $3.8 billion loss, but there are some glimmers out
there,'' he said.
   The question is how many more soured loans, as yet unrecognized
on S&Ls' books, are there. Loan losses accounted for $3.9 billion
of the first quarter loss versus $4 billion the previous quarter.
   ``I would expect they would start tapering off in Texas. We've
had a massive amount of losses ... over the past few years,'' said
William C. Ferguson, an Irving, Texas, S&L consultant. ``I
fervently hope it will taper off soon.''
   But other private analysts say billions more in bad loans are
likely to surface. And they say rising interest rates could cut
into the operating profits of healthy thrifts.
   ``A lot of people would say that losses in the industry total
$55 billion. We're still a long way from recognizing that, plus
there is some risk of short-term interest rates going up and losses
increasing,'' said Richard L. Peterson, professor of finance at
Texas Tech University in Lubbock.
   The question is becoming increasingly critical as regulators and
Congress try to determine how long the Federal Savings and Loan
Insurance Corp., which insures savings deposits up to $100,000, can
continue operating without an infusion of more money.
   Bank board Chairman M. Danny Wall said the $20 billion the FSLIC
will have over the next three years is as much as the agency can
efficiently spend and it is too soon to tell if more will be needed
later.
   However, the General Accounting Office, Congress' auditing
agency, estimates it will cost $26 billion to $36 billion to clean
up the industry. Private analysts put the price tag at $50 billion
or more.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
