<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 0343EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BudgetDeficit     06-22 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Budget Deficit,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prospect of Meeting Deficit Target Grows Dimmer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prospects that the Reagan administration
will be able to meet its $146.7 billion budget deficit goal for the
fiscal year are growing dimmer.
   The Treasury Department said Tuesday that personal income-tax
collections picked up in May after the April revenue flow lagged.
But the cumulative deficit of $127.5 billion for the first eight
months of the 1988 fiscal year is still running 6.3 percent higher
than last year.
   ``If we continue the pace we have right now it will come in at
about $159 billion,'' said Samuel D. Kahan, chief financial
economist of Kleinwort Benson Government Securities Inc. in Chicago.
   ``Unless they do some funny accounting, they're not going to be
able to hit their goal for the year,'' or even the Congressional
Budget Office's projection of $157 billion, he said.
   The deficit last year totaled $150.2 billion after soaring to a
record $221.1 billion in 1986. The target for the 1989 fiscal year,
beginning Oct. 1, is set at $136 billion by the Gramm-Rudman budget
balancing law.
   The persistent imbalance between what the government spends and
what it takes in is blamed by economists for weakening the dollar,
encouraging a high trade deficit and pressuring interest rates
upward.
   In May, the deficit totaled $22.5 billion, about $5 billion less
than expected by most analysts and down 36.9 percent from $35.6
billion a year ago.
   Personal income tax collection was off by 25.8 percent in April,
$51.3 billion against $71.8 billion a year earlier. But May
collections were nearly double those of last year. They rose from
$9.3 billion in 1987 to $18.0 billion, the Treasury Department said.
   ``Basically the IRS (Internal Revenue Service) got money in May
this year, rather than in April,'' Kahan said.
   Economists trying to determine the 1988 number will be closely
watching quarterly corporate tax collections, which were due June
15.
   ``The question is if corporations, with their sharp pencils, can
reduce some of the bite of the new tax law,'' Kahan said.
   In May, government revenues totaled $59.7 billion, 25.2 percent
stronger than in May 1987. Spending totaled $82.2 billion, down 1.3
percent from a year ago.
   For the first eight months, revenue totaled $581.8 billion, up
4.9 percent over 1987, while spending was $709.3 billion, up 5.2
percent from a year ago.
   As usual, the largest spending categories in March were the
military, followed by Social Security, interest on the national
debt and other programs in the Department of Health and Human
Services.
   Military spending totaled $20.3 billion last month and $188.7
billion for the fiscal year so far, up 4.1 percent from the same
period a year ago.
   Spending for Social Security totaled $18.1 billion last month
and $139.4 billion for the past eight months, up 5.4 percent from
the same period in fiscal 1987.
   The other HHS programs, including Medicare and Medicaid, spent
$11.9 billion in May and $105.1 billion so far this budget year, a
5.5 percent increase over 1987.
   Interest on the $2.5 trillion national debt totaled $17.4
billion last month and $137.5 billion so far this fiscal year, an
increase of 9.5 percent over the same period last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
