<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SpaceStation     06-22 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Space Station,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Ups Financing For NASA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Senate panel has cleared the way for an $800
million appropriation for the planned U.S. space station, up from a
$200 million package approved last week that officials said was so
small it would derail the project.
   The Senate appropriations defense subcommittee voted Tuesday to
shift $600 million from unspent defense funds to the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration budget. The money is intended
for the space station, said Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, who helped
arrange the transfer.
   ``The big hurdle was the subcommittee,'' Bentsen said. ``We've
crossed the big hurdle.''
   Another Senate appropriations subcommittee, which has
jurisdiction over NASA's budget, voted last week to appropriate
$200 million for the space station. Bentsen said at the time that
amount ``provides only enough for the slow strangulation'' of the
project.
   Bentsen said an $800 million appropriation would be enough to
``reach the level of support that is needed and get it moving ahead
as it should.''
   President Reagan had asked for a $967 million appropriation for
the space station in the next fiscal year's budget, and NASA
officials said $900 million is needed to keep it on schedule.
   Construction of the space station could begin next year if it
stays on schedule, and it is planned to be in orbit around Earth
and occupied by astronauts by the end of 1996, officials say.
   Bentsen said he is optimistic the $800 million will clear the
appropriations committee and the full Senate.
   The House Appropriations Committee, however, says the future of
the project should depend on the next president. The committee
voted last week to appropriate $902 million for the space station,
but the next president would have to agree to go ahead with the
project before the project could receive about half of that amount.
</TEXT>
