<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 0200EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-OperainPark     06-22 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Opera in Park,0578</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tens of Thousands Enjoy Picnic and Pavarotti</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs separate planned.</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shortly before 10 a.m., Toni Kurasch spread her
blanket on the Great Lawn in Central Park and plopped a
hand-lettered sign on it reading ``Beware of Dog.''
   Nine hours later, no dog had appeared, but Ms. Kurasch's sign
had served its purpose _ safeguarding her spot in front of an
estimated 150,000 other picnicking music lovers who thronged to
Tuesday night's free concert by the Metropolitan Opera.
   The work being performed, Donizetti's ``Elixir of Love,'' seemed
incidental for most of the crowd to the main attraction, a chance
to hear tenor Luciano Pavarotti and soprano Kathleen Battle.
   Luckily, both were in top form, which means they sang about as
well as any two singers alive are capable of singing.
   ``It's great they've managed to assemble such an array of
talent,'' said Jane Sternsnyder, who came from Philadelphia for the
event. ``One doesn't sit in this heat for no reason.''
   That was at noon, nearly three hours before the temperature
peaked at a withering 97 degrees. At performance time, the sun was
still blazing enough for Parks Commissioner Henry Stern to joke
that the audience could get ``both an opera and a suntan.''
   But as the sun went down, the music took hold of the crowd,
which spread back the length of several football fields from the
portable stage and two 40-foot amplifiers. Even from the far edge
of the lawn, the singers came through clearly, though they looked
no bigger than ants.
   Up close, Pavarotti & Co. were almost as much fun to watch as to
hear, using broad gestures and facial expressions to get across the
comic action. Outstanding in this respect was baritone Giuseppe
Taddei, whose infectious enthusiasm brought Dr. Dulcamara, the love
potion peddler, vividly to life.
   Pavarotti has always had a special fondness for the part of the
bumbling, lovestruck Nemorino, and he sang with more ease and
elegance than he sometimes musters these days. His rendition of the
famous aria ``Una furtiva lagrima'' brought such an ovation that he
responded with an encore, something that's strictly taboo at the
indoor Met.
   As for Miss Battle in the role of Adina, she poured out delicate
tones of unmatched beauty all night, earning an encore of her own
near the finale.
   Paolo Coni, a baritone who will make his official debut with the
Met next season, displayed a vibrant, powerful sound as Sergeant
Belcore, and soprano Dawn Kotoski was excellent in the small part
of Giannetta. Conductor Marcello Panni led a spirited performance
in his American debut.
   Crowd estimates are notoriously unreliable, but Met spokeswoman
Johanna Fiedler said she figured the attendance at about 150,000,
compared with the previous record of 100,000 for an opera in the
park.
   The performance kicked off the Met's 22nd season of free opera
in the park, a nearly $2 million endeavor whose major sponsor is
Chemical Bank. The opera company visits each of New York City's
five boroughs, Long Island and New Jersey, though the all-star cast
sang only on opening night.
   Opera lovers who missed Pavarotti and Miss Battle can catch them
in ``Elixir'' at the Met next season. The acoustics will be better,
but you'll pay for it _ up to $90 for the best orchestra seats.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880622-0026 </DOCNO>
