<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PACMoney     06-22 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PAC Money,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PACs Building Up Warchests For Fall Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Political action committees bankrolled by
members of special interest groups are building up their war chests
for the fall elections, with the Teamsters' and Realtors' PACs each
contributing close to $1 million to federal candidates so far.
   Five of the more than 4,000 PACs registered with the Federal
Election Commission each had more than $2 million in cash on hand
at the beginning of April, an FEC summary released Tuesday showed.
   Together, the registered PACs raised more than $213 million in
the 15 months ending March 31, up 7 percent from the same period in
1986. They had spent $162 million, up 8.4 percent from spending at
that point in the last election cycle, the FEC said.
   Labor unions and corporations are prohibited by law from giving
money to federal campaigns, so many set up PACs to which their
employees and others can give money voluntarily. Politicians and
interest groups also form PACs to promote their own interests.
   The Teamsters PAC, called Democratic Republican Independent
Voter Education Committee, raised the most during the 15-month
period, $5.5 million, followed by the American Medical Association
PAC at just under $4 million, and the Realtors Political Action
Committee at $3.7 million.
   Federal law allows PACs to give no more than $5,000 to each
candidate per election, compared to the $1,000 limit on
contributions by individuals.
   The Teamsters and Realtors PACs each reported giving close to $1
million to federal candidates, but the AMA PAC was 10th on the list
of most contributions, giving $585,946, the summary said.
   In cash on hand, the Teamster PAC had the most, $4.5 million,
followed by: the International Longshoremen's Association AFL-CIO
PAC, $2.7 million; the National Education Association PAC, at $2.3
million; the Auto Dealers and Drivers For Free Trade PAC, $2.3
million; and the Realtors PAC, $2.1 million.
   The PACs that raise the most do not necessarily give the most
donations to candidates, with money often going to a variety of
fund-raising and overhead costs.
   The FEC summary did not reflect any money the PACs might have
spent on so-called independent expenditures. Such expenditures do
not come under the $5,000 limit as long as the money is spent to
support or oppose a candidate but without coordination with the
candidate's campaign.
   Besides the Teamsters, AMA and Realtors PACs, those that raised
the most through March 31, followed by the sums they have
contributed to candidates were:
   _The National Congressional Club, founded by supporters of
Republican Sen. Jesse Helms in North Carolina, $2.7 million raised,
$47,032 in contributions.
   _Auto Dealers and Drivers For Free Trade PAC, a Jamaica,
N.Y.-based committee funded significantly with money from imported
and domestic car dealers, $2.7 million, $377,650.
   _Campaign America, founded by Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., $2.6
million, $59,350.
   _American Citizens for Political Action, a committee founded by
former Young Americans For Freedom chairman Robert Dolan which has
given to a variety of conservative candidates, $2.4 million,
$35,650.
   _League of Conservation Voters, an environmentally oriented
group, $2.4 million, less than $30,000.
   _National Education Association Political Action Committee, $2.3
million, $697,587.
   _Association of Trial Lawyers Political Action Committee, $2.2
million, $722,658.
   The PAC founded by Vice President George Bush, Fund For
America's Future, raised $1.7 million, and spent a total of $1.5
million, but less than $20,000 of that went to federal campaigns.
   Critics of the PAC system contend that PAC spending allows for
too much special interest influence in politics. The Center For
Responsive Politics conducted a survey that found PACs give money
expecting that it will buy them access to politicians.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
