<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Glance     06-22 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Glance,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Reagan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are the highlights comments made by and
about President Reagan in Toronto as he concluded his eighth and
final economic summit of industrialized democracies:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>REAGAN NEWS CONFERENCE</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In a prepared statement, Reagan retraced the eight summits, said
he was satisfied with the economic prosperity and revitalization
that has been achieved through cooperation in the Western states.
He said however, some ``items are still in needs of attention.''
   Answering questions from reporters, primarily on domestic issues:
   He said he was ``very upset'' about alleged widespread bribery
and fraud in the Defense Department's procurement process but said
it would be ``understandable'' considering the size of the
government. He praised former Secretary of Defense Caspar
Weinberger as ``one of the finest secretaries of defense this
country has had'' who ``was doing all that he cold to bring our
national security out of the kind of chaos that we inherited.''
   On the Iran-Contra situation and possible pardons for former
administration officials he said, ``Of course the case has to go
forward.'' He also defended his management style and the
administration's handling of the situation.
   On gun control he said he had taught everyone in his family to
how to use a gun ``in case they need to.'' He also proposed state
governments conduct background checks on all gun purchasers.
   On the drought plaguing much of the country, he said ``Outside
of praying for rain, there isn't anything I can do.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>SUMMIT FAREWELL TO REAGAN</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Western leaders praised Reagan throughout the 3-day meeting.
   Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney, speaking on behalf of
the leaders said, ``Ronald Reagan has been for all of us at this
table a gracious friend and a trusted ally. We shall all miss his
warmth and his wisdom.''
   Mulroney said the Reagan's ``leadership has been strong, his
accomplishments substantial and his place in history secure.''
   The summit host said the leaders wished ``for good health and
every happiness for Nancy and himself.''
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher declared she had only
``kind words'' for Reagan, adding, ``He's been marvelous.''
   She echoed Mulroney's tribute saying each of the leaders had
``the whole-hearted support and affection for President Reagan and
what he has done.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>___</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>REAGAN'S FAREWELL SPEECH TO SUMMIT</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Reagan's farewell to the leaders of the Western democracies came
in a speech to a group of Canadian businessmen.
   He warned them that ``protectionist storms'' are brewing around
the world.
   He told them they had a choice ``between moving toward freer
trade, or backward toward the protection and isolation that are
relics of another age'' and urged them to follow the example set by
the United States and Canada. ``We North Americans never have. We
have always risen to meet a challenge. Our hearts quicken to the
call, our eyes brighten, our pace picks up,'' he said.
   Reagan praised the economic progress he had seen take place in
the Western states during his tenure. ``Inflation, stagnation,
decline and despair characterized, in one measure or another, the
economies of nearly all the summit nations. Today, we live in a
time of hope.''
   He also said there was hope for the reform going on in the
Soviet Union, calling Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev ``a
serious man seeking serious reform.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
</DOC>
