<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 0247EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Drought-Politics     06-22 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Politics,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dry Weather Adds to Bush's Midwest Woes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Likely Republican presidential nominee
George Bush faces a ``political dust bowl'' in the Midwest that is
worsening with this year's drought, some Democratic and GOP
observers say.
   ``It's true that farmers, when they're out of sorts for any
reason, vote against the party in power,'' said Lawrence Pope, a
Drake University law professor and GOP strategist.
   ``I think that what Republican legislative and congressional
candidates are worried about right now is that does begin to affect
those other races,'' Pope said Tuesday. ``Republicans are going to
be nervous about a Bush candidacy in Iowa right now.''
   Phil Roeder, spokesman for the Iowa Democratic Party, pointed to
growing Democratic strength in the region, demonstrated by the
party's capture of Senate seats in Iowa and Illinois in 1984 and in
the Dakotas in 1986.
   ``There's clearly a Democratic seed growing out here,'' Roeder
said. ``With that on top of drought, it's not only going to be a
literal dust bowl, it's going to be a political dust bowl for
Bush.''
   Republican politicians have been nervous about the impact Bush
will have on other races, and their confidence wasn't helped by a
poll in Sunday's Des Moines Register showing him trailing likely
Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis by a 60 percent to 28 percent
margin.
   ``When you're down that bad, you don't need more bad news,''
Pope said.
   Also reflecting the GOP nervousness was David Roederer, a
political aide to Republican Gov. Terry Branstad.
   ``If you have weak candidates at the presidential level, it's
bound to hurt,'' Roederer said. ``We're a long way from writing the
final chapter but this doesn't help.''
   Iowa Republican Chairman Michael Mahaffey put a better face on
the issue.
   ``I think Iowans are smart enough to realize that those are
things beyond a politician's control,'' he said. ``You can make an
argument that it's going to make people nervous.''
   Mahaffey said the GOP can recover even if the drought worsens if
the Reagan administration moves quickly with emergency aid programs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880622-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 0249EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis-Jackson     06-22 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Jackson,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says He Has No Short, Long or Medium List For Vice
Presidency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis came away from a private
discussion with Jesse Jackson saying he has no short, medium or
long list of potential running mates but that the search is on for
someone ``first-rate.''
   Neither of the Democratic rivals would say whether Jackson asked
for the vice presidential slot during the 40-minute meeting Tuesday.
   Dukakis said he wouldn't discuss his private conversation with
Jackson, but added that ``there's no understanding'' with Jackson
over the selection of a running mate.
   ``The process has now begun. But it's open,'' Dukakis said.
``There's no short list, or medium list or long list.''
   Meanwhile, sources in Washington who spoke on condition of
anonymity said Tuesday that Dukakis' campaign has requested
background information from Jackson and at least one other possible
running-mate, Sen. Bob Graham of Florida.
   Dukakis also is conducting public polling to assess the strength
of potential Democratic vice presidential candidates, the sources
said.
   Dukakis, who has more than enough delegates to clinch the
presidential nomination at the Democratic National Convention next
month, replied indirectly when asked if he were using polling to
help him pick a running mate.
   ``I don't think this is a decision that is helped particularly
by a lot of polling,'' he said.
   ``This is one where you're looking for presidential qualities,
for a person to be a first-rate president, who can bring real
strength not only to the ticket but to government and the nation.
And those are things you really don't poll for,'' he added.
   At a news conference following the Dukakis-Jackson meeting,
Jackson repeated his assertion that his ``constituency deserves
consideration'' in the selection of the Democratic vice
presidential nominee.
   ``Our constituency represents hope for our party. It represents
a commitment to make room for all Democrats,'' Jackson said.
   But asked whether he told Dukakis that he wanted to be on the
ticket, Jackson said, ``I'm not going to characterize exactly what
we discussed.''
   Jackson said that during the meeting, the two discussed the vice
presidency ``more than we have talked about it (before) person to
person.''
   Dukakis and Jackson met following Dukakis' address to more than
3,500 members of the American Federation of State, County and
Municipal Employees. Jackson was to address the same group today.
   Dukakis used his appearance before the group to renew his call
for a national health insurance program, patterned after
legislation he signed in Massachusetts.
   Affordable health care ``is the birthright of every family and
every citizen of the United States of America,'' Dukakis said.
   ``Two months ago, ... I became the first governor in America to
sign a bill that will guarantee health insurance for every single
citizen in my state,'' Dukakis said. ``And I look forward to the
day I can sign the same kind of bill into law for all Americans _
as president of the United States.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
