<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 0049EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ContraLayoffs     06-22 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contra Layoffs,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras To Lay Off Staff, Cut Expenses, Spokeswoman Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Contras will lay off administrative staff and
sharply cut expenses at the end of June, a spokeswoman for the
Nicaraguan rebels said late Tuesday.
   But the budget squeeze will not affect troops in the field or
support received by their families, said spokeswoman Marta Sacasa.
   ``We are not closing _ it's just a matter of trying to function
with less cost,'' she said.
   Deep cuts are expected in the staff at the Miami headquarters
and other Contra political offices around the world, although some
employees may continue as unpaid volunteers.
   ``By the 30th, I understand nobody is sure who will continue
working,'' Ms. Sacasa said, adding that the directors have not
announced the extent of the layoffs or the ``restructuring'' that
will accompany them.
   The New York Times in Wednesday's editions quoted Silvio
Arguello Cardenal, vice president of the Contra legislative
assembly, as saying layoff notices have already been mailed to 350
to 400 employees in the Contra offices in Miami, Washington, Latin
America and Europe.
   Ms. Sacasa said that to her knowledge none of the employees had
received the official notice by Tuesday. She said directors would
do their best to ensure none of the employees would be ``out on the
street.''
   The layoffs are part of a top-to-bottom reorganization, she said.
   ``We're giving the directors the freedom to do what has to be
done to be more productive,'' she said.
   She denied the cutbacks were directly related to Congress'
refusal to back the administration's full budget request for the
Contras this year.
   The rebel political staff has had exceptionally high expenses so
far this year, in part because of trips back and forth to Central
America to negotiate a truce with Nicaragua's Sandinista government.
   In March, Congress approved $47.9 million in Contra aid but
limited it to humanitarian applications, and although the Reagan
administration is expected to ask for more money, legislative
leaders give new funding little chance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
