<DOCNO> AP880622-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 0305EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Summit-Reagan'sFinale Bjt   06-22 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Reagan's Finale, Bjt,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON WIRE: Summit Brings Reagan to Twilight of His
Presidency</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, his last economic summit not
quite the success he had hoped for, heads into the twilight of his
administration with only the slim prospect of another session with
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev to keep him on center stage in
the international arena.
   There was considerable praise for Reagan in Toronto, most of it
in the form of a personal tribute. In his best aw-shucks manner,
Reagan admitted he would miss the glitter and ceremony ``in a way.''
   With only seven months to go, and a long summer vacation ahead,
Reagan is entering lame-duck status and his foreign policy
objectives are nearing a dead end.
   Negotiations with the Soviet Union to sharply reduce long-range
nuclear weapons have encountered problems with verification and the
Kremlin's continued objections to his search for a space-based
defense against ballistic missiles.
   But talks are continuing in Geneva, and neither Reagan nor
Gorbachev has ruled out the possibility of a fifth superpower
summit if a deal is struck. Most analysts, however, believe the
chances of that happening are remote.
   In the Middle East, where Reagan's economic summit partners
called for a peace conference, his envoy, Secretary of State George
P. Shultz, has been unable to nudge Jordan's King Hussein and
Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir to the negotiating table.
   On Reagan's agenda in the coming months are vacations at his
California ranch in both July and August and campaign forays on
behalf of his vice president, George Bush.
   And so for Reagan, the three-day Toronto meeting might just be
his last hurrah.
   ``The summit punctuated the success of the president's economic
program over the last seven years,'' Marlin Fitzwater, the White
House spokesman, enthused in a windup statement.
   The facts, however, suggested a more mixed performance.
   For instance, Reagan's proposal to end all agricultural
subsidies by the year 2000 fell on deaf ears.
   France's Socialist President Francois Mitterrand challenged
Reagan's unfettered faith in the free market. And on helping
debt-ridden countries, the best Reagan could manage was a
compromise formula that really was no decision at all.
   And then there were those persistent Washington reporters who
peppered Reagan with questions at a pre-departure news conference
about a spreading Pentagon bribery investigation and the
Iran-Contra affair.
   These are not the kind of topics Reagan likes to discuss _ at
home or away.
   In fact, Reagan fielded only a few questions about the economic
meeting.
   He did receive a rousing tribute from the summit host, Canadian
Prime Minister Brian Mulroney, and Reagan's closest ally, Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher of Britain. But even that was tempered
by Mitterrand.
   ``For someone who played a great role in contemporary history,
it's normal to salute him and wish that his retirement be happy and
long,'' the French president said. ``It's a courtesy. It has
nothing to do, I suppose, with politics.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Barry Schweid is head of the AP's State
Department staff.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
