<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 0421EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-US-USSRHotline     06-22 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-USSR Hotline,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Washington-to-Moscow Hotline Celebrates 25th Birthday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREDERICK, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Washington-to-Moscow hotline has
helped cool tensions between the superpowers since its creation 25
years ago this week after the Cuban missile crisis put the United
States and Soviet Union on the brink of nuclear war.
   ``The best quote I've seen about it called it `an insurance
policy for peace,''' Norm Covert, a spokesman for Fort Detrick,
said Tuesday. ``I think it's the best description of the system and
why we have it.''
   Fort Detrick, an Army installation just north of Washington, was
made part of the hotline system in 1978. The communications line
was established June 20, 1963.
   The president has access to other forms of communication with
the Soviet Union, but the hotline provides a direct link between
the two heads of state, Covert said. The hotline, often used when
either country is planning military action in some part of the
world, provides a way for the leaders to communicate without going
through diplomatic channels.
   The hotline was established less than a year after tensions
mounted between the superpowers during the Cuban missile crisis.
   After learning the Soviet Union had missiles in Cuba capable of
striking U.S. cities, President John F. Kennedy set up a blockade
and ordered Navy ships to turn back all vessels delivering Soviet
missiles to Cuba. War seemed imminent for about a week, but the
Soviets eventually ordered offensive missiles removed and Kennedy
lifted the blockade.
   Soon after, Jess Gorkin, a senior editor for Parade Magazine,
wrote an open letter to Kennedy, suggesting that a communication
line be opened, allowing the two leaders to communicate directly,
without the chance for misinterpretation, Covert said. Kennedy
embraced the idea and the hotline was established in 1963.
   ``We don't know that he (President Reagan) uses it unless he
tells us,'' Covert said. ``I believe he said he used it just before
we invaded Grenada.''
   Unlike fictional descriptions of the hotline, a red telephone is
not part of the system. ``The only telephone there is the one the
technicians use,'' Covert said.
   Fort Detrick is one of two independent satellite stations in the
hotline network. The other is in Etam, W.Va., he said, adding that
communications technicians check the line with Moscow every hour.
The Soviet Union's satellite earth station is just south of Moscow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880622-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 0241EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Nielsens     06-22 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nielsens,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS Wins Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS slam-dunked two NBA finals games into the
top 10 in the A.C. Nielsen Co. rankings last week and broke NBC's
six-week winning streak.
   But ``NBC Nightly News'' got out of third place in the news
ratings by eking out a tie for second in a dead heat that saw only
a tenth of a rating point separate the three network newscasts.
   For the week that ended Friday, the ``CBS Evening News'' had an
average rating of 8.5, ABC's ``World News Tonight'' and NBC had 8.4
each. Each had a 19 share.
   The rating is a percentage of the nation's estimated 88.6
million households with televisions. The share is a percentage of
sets in use.
   Game five Thursday night in the National Basketball Association
championship series between the Los Angeles Lakers and the Detroit
Pistons was the week's fourth highest-ranked prime-time program,
with a rating of 16.0. Game four last Tuesday ranked ninth with a
14.8.
   CBS' rerun Sunday night of ``Intimate Strangers,'' starring Teri
Garr as a a female prisoner of war who returns home, won the night
and ranked seventh, even though it was up against an original
made-for-TV movie, ``A Father's Homecoming,'' on NBC.
   CBS' cult hit ``Wiseguy,'' was off to a good start in summer
reruns. The two-hour introductory episode ranked 20th.
   ABC's ``20-20'' tied for 20th with an installment that featured
Jane Fonda apologizing to Vietnam veterans for her trip to Hanoi to
protest the war.
   For the week that ended Sunday, CBS had an average, prime-time
rating of 11.8, NBC 11.0, and ABC 8.7. CBS pulled into a tie with
ABC for second place in season-to-date ratings, which stand at: NBC
15.4, CBS and ABC 13.0 each.
   The last time CBS won a week was the first week of May, when the
``Magnum, P.I.'' finale was the No. 1 show. CBS has also tied with
NBC for first one week.
   The top 10 prime-time shows of the week were: ``Night Court,''
``A Different World'' and ``Cheers,'' NBC; game five of the NBA
finals, CBS; ``Golden Girls,'' ``The Cosby Show,'' NBC; ``Intimate
Strangers,'' ``60 Minutes,'' game four of the NBA finals, CBS;
``L.A. Law,'' NBC.
   The lowest-rated shows were: ``TV's Bloopers and Practical
Jokes,'' ``West 57th,'' ``Charlie Brown Special,'' ``Highway to
Heaven,'' ``The Days and Nights of Molly Dodd,'' ``Ohara,''
``Sledge Hammer!'' ``Our House,'' ``Double Agent, Part 1'' and
``Probe.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
