<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Dance     06-22 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dance,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paris Opera Ballet Opens in NY</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rudolf Nureyev's version of ``Swan Lake,'' which
opened the Paris Opera Ballet's three-week season at the
Metropolitan Opera, is not the finest production of the well-known
ballet. Nor was Tuesday night's performance the best presentation.
   The two stars danced very well but didn't dazzle with
personality. Laurent Hilaire was the most impassive prince we've
seen. Isabelle Guerin rippled her arms and looked appropriately
swan-like, but did not convey the aspects of the woman she was
before evil sorcerer Rothbart changed her into a swan.
   When she danced the black swan, Miss Guerin switched on
vitality, which the ballet needed badly.
   Hilaire has impressive height to his jumps and beats in air. The
prince and black swan, when they traded variations, did build
excitement, though not as much as usual in that scene.
   We recall both dancers putting more oomph into their
performances when the company presented the same ballet here two
years ago. Maybe the June 14 to 19 season in Costa Mesa, Calif.,
was exhausting.
   Nureyev, whose choreography is ``after'' the early work of
Marius Petipa and Lev Ivanov, emphasizes the men more than those
choreographers did. He has one dance for four groups of four men,
one group of which couldn't stay together on Tuesday.
   John Lanchbery conducted the Tchaikovsky music with elegance.
Franca Squarciapino designed costumes and unusually effective swan
headdresses.
   From July 12 to 14, the company will dance in Vienna, Va.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
