<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Summit-NextYear Bjt   06-22 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Next Year, Bjt,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bicentennial Fireworks, New U.S. President At Next Summit in
France</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Next year's summit of the seven most powerful
democracies will feature a new U.S. president on the world stage
and a backdrop of fireworks marking the bicentennial of the French
Revolution.
   The meeting may also show whether Socialist President Francois
Mitterrand of France, who will become the first leader ever to
repeat as summit host, can shift the theme of the gathering away
from the free-market philosophy so dear to President Reagan and
British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
   Reagan will be gone _ replaced most likely by George Bush or
Michael Dukakis _ but most of the other leaders who finished their
three-day meeting Tuesday in Canada's largest city probably will be
on hand again next year.
   Reagan's retirement is sure to shine the spotlight all the more
brightly on Mrs. Thatcher, a vigorous proponent of the policy that
less government is good government.
   Like Mrs. Thatcher and Mitterrand, West German Chancellor Helmut
Kohl has won re-election in the past 18 months and can expect to be
in office next year. Prime Ministers Noboru Takeshita of Japan and
Ciriaco De Mita of Italy are new in office, but the Italian cannot
count on staying around long enough to see his second summit.
   The leader in the shakiest position is this year's host,
Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney, whose Progressive
Conservative party is trailing well behind the opposition Liberals
in public opinion polls with an election expected within the next
year.
   But Mitterrand may well be the only Socialist in the next group,
as he was this year. His views, eccentric in a group of free-market
conservatives, brought him into repeated clashes with Reagan over
contents of the final communique.
   The host leader has a strong role in shaping the summit agenda,
and the 71-year-old Mitterrand is known as a wily strategist. But
he will have a difficult task if he wants to stamp the meeting with
his leftist policies.
   He told a news conference on Tuesday that he was sure that farm
subsidies and Third World debt _ the two biggest issues at the
Toronto summit _ will still be major items for the leaders to
attack next year.
   When Mitterrand convenes the economic summit on July 14, 1989,
France will be marking exactly 200 years since a Parisian throng
stormed the Bastille prison, launching the French Revolution and _
in a sense _ the modern era.
   Preparing the bicentennial was one of Mitterrand's priorities in
his first term, and his re-election last month to another seven
years in office assures that he will be able to preside over the
fireworks displays, concerts and other events planned for the
occasion.
   Mitterrand said Tuesday that it was fitting that the seven
leaders would be on hand ``for the celebration of one of the great
events of our history, which is also theirs.''
   He said the date chosen for the summit ``will have an undeniable
symbolic force.''
   Next year's meeting will start a third ``cycle,'' now that each
of the seven countries has been host twice since the summits
started in 1975, when President Valery Giscard d'Estaing of France
invited his peers to the Renaissance chateau at Rambouillet.
   When Mitterrand started the second cycle in 1982, he chose
another grand palace _ the chateau of Louis XIV at Versailles _ but
officials said next year's site would more likely be a modern
office complex in Paris.
   In their closing statement Tuesday, the leaders said their
meetings ``have helped to sustain the values of democracy that
underlie our economic and political system,'' and were worth
continuing for the next seven years, ending with another meeting in
Canada in 1995.
   ``We believe that the mutual understanding engendered in our
meetings has benefited both our own countries and the wider world
community,'' they said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880622-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 0138EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Summit-Leaders Bjt   06-22 0749</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Summit-Leaders, Bjt,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>America's Summit Allies Leave With Much of What They Wanted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States' summit allies left Toronto
with much of what they wanted. They won more debt relief for the
world's poorest countries and fought off an American attempt to
eliminate agricultural subsidies.
   From French President Francois Mitterrand to Japanese Prime
Minister Noboru Takeshita, the allies expressed satisfaction with
the outcome of the 14th annual economic summit of seven leading
industrialized nations.
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher called the summit,
which wound up Tuesday, ``highly successful,'' and Takeshita said
through a spokesman that he was ``finishing this summit meeting
with a sense of fulfillment.''
   With the economies of the major industrialized nations on track,
the leaders turned their attention to the sticky question of
agricultural subsidies and the desperate plight of the world's
poorest countries.
   In advance of the summit, Mitterrand proposed that the leaders
fashion a plan to ease the foreign debt burdens of the poorest of
the poor countries, those in vast sub-Saharan Africa.
   At the end of the meeting, Mitterrand said his suggestions were
adopted in the leaders' final communique.
   ``So,'' he told reporters, ``I'm satisfied.''
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl also praised the plan, which
offers a variety of options, including slashing interest rates and
forgiving some loans, for easing the poor countries' debt burden.
   Willy De Clercq, commissioner for external relations of the
European Community, called the measure ``a big step forward.'' The
12-nation trading bloc is represented at the summit.
   The United States earlier this month backed off from its
previous refusal to go along with concessions, paving the way for
the agreement.
   Japan's finance minister, Kiichi Miyazawa, offered a sweeping
proposal that would help such big-debt countries as Brazil and
Mexico. The two Latin American countries are the developing world's
largest debtors, with a combined foreign debt of $220 billion. The
total for all the developing world is an estimated $1 trillion.
   Summiteers complained the Japanese plan was so complicated and
offered on such short notice that they did not have time to study
it.
   They renewed their support, instead, for the current
case-by-case approach drawn up in recent years to handle
individually the money woes of the large debtors.
   The Japanese seem unfazed by the cool response to their plan,
which will no doubt be discussed at future international meetings.
   Takeshita was ``particularly pleased at the great deal of
attention that was paid to the problems of developing countries,''
according to Michihiko Kunihiro, chief Cabinet counselor for
external affairs.
   The Europeans and the Japanese tangled with the Americans and
Canadians over what has become a bitterly disputed issue, that of
agricultural subsidies.
   Reagan has proposed, as part of his free-market philosophy, that
farm subsidies be scrapped by the year 2000.
   American officials argue that European subsidies have made the
European Community a major agricultural supplier at a time of
excess world capacity.
   The Europeans respond that they have begun the politically
sensitive process of limiting European Community subsidies to
farmers but don't want to be pushed to meet a deadline.
   The final statement offers vaguely worded language that called
for a ``framework approach, including short as well as long-term
elements'' to promote reforms, relieve strains in agricultural
markets and which would be in line with goals ``concerning the
reduction of all direct and indirect subsidies and other measures
affecting ... agricultural trade.''
   De Clercq expressed satisfaction with what he said was a
compromise among the leaders.
   ``Agriculture is a bone of contention ... We succeeded in
avoiding a row,'' he told reporters.
   The final wording, he said, ``underlines the reality ... the
diversity of agriculture situations in the world, a fact we had to
take into account.'' Small family farms, not large agribusinesses,
are common in Europe.
   Kohl said the leaders were ``moving completely on a similar
track.''
   ``The long-term goal must be a strong market-orientation of
agriculture production,'' he said. ``For this, realism and
perspective are necessary.
   Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney, who had hoped for firm
action to end the global subsidy war, said, ``It is not a perfect
statement but it represents progress.''
   Mrs. Thatcher, who has fought in the European Community for
curbing the subsidies, said, ``There is a specific commitment to
try first to freeze and then to roll back the subsidies and various
other kinds of support for agriculture in an ordered and
substantial way.''
   ``We have made a start,'' she said..
</TEXT>
