<HEAD>Duarte Released From Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salvadoran President Jose Napoleon Duarte,
suffering from terminal cancer, has been released from Walter Reed
Army Medical Center but is staying in residential quarters on
hospital grounds, a spokesman for the Salvadoran Embassy says.
   Duarte, one of the United States' closes allies in Latin
America, was released from the hospital on Monday and moved to
nearby quarters, said Alfredo Milian, El Salvador's deputy
ambassador to the United States.
   Duarte, who was admitted to Walter Reed on May 31, underwent
three hours of cancer surgery on June 7. During the surgery,
doctors removed a portion of his stomach but left his cancerous
liver alone.
   A spokesman for Walter Reed, Peter Esker, said late Tuesday that
Duarte, 62, had been released from the hospital because ``he's
recovered from his abdominal surgery.'' Esker said he expected
Duarte would be ``back (in the hospital) in about a week for
re-evaluation of his condition.''
   Following Duarte's surgery, his personal physician, Dr. Benjamin
Interiano, said the average life expectancy of someone in Duarte's
condition is six months.
   Duarte's son, Alejandro Duarte, said Monday that chemotherapy
could extend his father's life well into next year. Alejandro
Duarte said his father probably would return to El Salvador between
July 5 and July 8 and would resume the presidency immediately.
   Duarte's five-year term expires June 1, 1989. Serving as acting
president in Duarte's absence is Vice President Rodolfo Castillo
Claramount.
</TEXT>
