<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua     06-22 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ortega Says Shultz Will Seek Regional Unity Against Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega charged that
Secretary of State George P. Shultz plans to seek support for U.S.
aggression against Nicaragua when he visits Central America next
week.
   Shultz will visit El Salvador, Honduras, Guatemala and Costa
Rica from June 29 to July 1 to discuss the collapse of Nicaraguan
peace talks.
   Ortega on Tuesday noted that Shultz would not visit Nicaragua.
   ``What does this mean?'' he said. ``The United States doesn't
have any interest in a negotiated solution to the problems with
Nicaragua.''
   Negotiations between Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government
and the U.S.-supported Contra rebels broke off June 9.
   On Monday, rebel leaders rejected a government proposal to
resume the talks, saying the offer was aimed at discouraging a
renewal of U.S. military aid.
   Ortega told a group of more than 100 Americans, representatives
of sister cities programs, that while President Reagan recently
visited the Soviet Union, ``he doesn't have the desire to negotiate
with Nicaragua.''
   He said the purpose of the Shultz visit was to seek regional
support for American ``war policies against Nicaragua.''
   The United States has supported the Contra rebels since they
began their war to topple the Sandinistas in 1981.
   Managua and Washington maintain diplomatic relations. But the
United States cut off all aid in 1981 and imposed an economic
boycott in 1985.
   Bilateral talks between the Sandinistas and the Reagan
administration broke off in 1985.
   In other developments, a group of Atlantic Coast Indian rebels
declared they were renewing their warfare against the leftist
Sandinista government, according to a statement published Tuesday
night in the opposition newspaper La Prensa.
   The communique of the Yatama Indian rebel organization rejected
peace negotiations with the Sandinistas and said the government
would have ``to revise its dictatorial policies to implant the
conditions for a true democracy in our country.''
   Yatama seeks a form of self-government for the indigenous tribes
along the so-called Mosquito Coast of the Atlantic. The Sandinistas
have reached agreements with other Indian rebel groups to lay down
their arms.
   Yatama organizers claim to have 2,000 combatants. At least 1,000
have surrendered since last year and the Indian war had stopped for
the most part.
   The statement, signed by Yatama general coordinator Wicliff
Diego, said the Sandinistas refused to accede to their demands for
autonomous rule.
   Cease-fire talks with the Indians began in May, little more than
a month after the mainstream Contras reached a temporary truce with
the Sandinistas. The Indians received a small part of the millions
of dollars in military and economic aid supplied by the U.S.
government.
</TEXT>
