<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Unrest     06-22 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Unrest,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disputed Region's Legislature Asks Temporary Independence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The legislature of Nagorno-Karabakh has asked that
the disputed region be declared independent until Moscow decides
whether to transfer its control from the Azerbaijan republic to
Armenia, a dissident said.
   The body also asked the federal parliament, or Supreme Soviet,
to disregard an earlier decision by Azerbaijan's legislature to
oppose the region's transfer to Armenia, added Koryun Nahabidyan, a
Moscow-based Armenian activist.
   He said he had spoken with Nagorno-Karabakh residents familiar
with the regional legislature's Tuesday decision.
   Nagorno-Karabakh has a population of about 160,000 people. Most
are ethnic Armenians, a mainly Christian ethnic group, but the
region was assigned in 1923 to the predominantly Moslem neighboring
republic of Azerbaijan.
   Nagorno-Karabakh's legislature voted Feb. 20 to request
annexation to Armenia and the legislature of that southern republic
supported it.
   But Azerbaijan has refused to cede the territory and Moscow has
not said whether it will decide the question.
   Nahabidyan, who has led several Armenian demonstrations in
Moscow, said Nagorno-Karabakh's legislature also asked the federal
Supreme Court to take over legal action against rioters responsible
for killing 32 people, most of them Armenians, on Feb. 28 in the
Azerbaijan city of Sumgait.
   Armenians have said the Supreme Court of Azerbaijan, which is
handling the case, is not dealing harshly enough with those
responsible.
   A resident of Stepanakert, the territorial capital, said the
``whole city'' of 60,000 people had gathered outside government
buildings to await the legislature's decision.
   The resident, speaking by telephone on condition of anonymity,
said the members rejected a proposal to secede outright from
Azerbaijan.
   The legislature also reportedly asked residents to return to
their jobs. They have been striking since May 23, stopping nearly
all commercial activity in the region except for retailing and
agriculture, according to reports from the area.
</TEXT>
