<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     06-22 0599</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Ruling May Force Disclosure Of Financial Inducements</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court says investment tip
sheets can be forced to tell readers that financial inducements
were given by a company to write a favorable article.
   The ruling by the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals here on Tuesday
revived a lawsuit by the Securities and Exchange Commission to make
Stock Market Magazine tell readers that features about companies
were carried as a result of financial inducements
   But the court rejected the SEC's contention such publications
must tell readers that a featured company provided the article or
paid the writer who composed it.
   Deciding whether the text of a particular article was
``substantially provided'' by the company would be an intrusion in
the editorial process that is prohibited by the First Amendment,
the court said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Safety Commission Warns of Fireworks Danger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal safety officials spread the word about
the dangers of the Fourth of July by filling two dressed turkeys
with an explosive stuffing.
   The Consumer Products Safety Commission blew the turkeys to bits
with M-100s _ small, finger-type firecrackers that are illegal yet
readily available in many areas, agency officials said on Tuesday.
   A pair of watermelons also met their end as the CPSC simulated
what could happen to a human being in a holiday accident.
   ``This July 4th marks Uncle Sam's 212th birthday. What better
way to celebrate than to make sure that fireworks do not spoil the
occasion,'' commission Chairman Terrence M. Scanlon said at the
base of the Washington Monument.
   The commission said approximately 9,000 injuries involving
fireworks were treated at hospital emergency rooms last year, down
from 12,600 in 1986.
</TEXT>
