<HEAD>NPR Receives Record $1.5 Million Grant</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Bennet, 2nd graf, is cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Public Radio is getting a $1.5
million grant from the John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur
Foundation, the largest single private-sector grant in NPR's
history.
   The grant will ``enhance NPR's ability to create new services,
search for better ways to do what we do, and serve better a
national audience growing in numbers,'' Douglas J. Bennet,
president of the non-profit radio network, said Tuesday.
   About 30 percent of NPR's operating revenues comes from grants
and program underwriting, with the rest generated by its 350 member
stations.
   Since 1978, the MacArthur Foundation has awarded more than $550
million in grants to various organizations for programs in mental
health, tropical medicine, conservation, education, peace and
international cooperation.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Approves Final Purchase Of Bird Refuge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Conservationists hoping to preserve Texas'
Matagorda Island, habitat for wintering whooping cranes and other
endangered bird species, got a boost from a Senate panel that
approved plans to buy the last parcel of privately held land on the
barrier island.
   A Senate appropriations subcommittee approved late Monday
legislation to spend $5.5 million to purchase 5,017 acres at the
southern tip of the Texas Gulf Coast island.
   The U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service will buy the land from the
Texas Nature Conservancy, putting all the land on the island under
either federal or state ownership, according to the office of Sen.
Phil Gramm, R-Texas.
   ``This is important not only for whooping cranes, but for water
fowl, shore birds, and herons, egrets and song birds,'' Brent
Giezentanner, manager of the nearby Aransas Pass National Wildlife
Refuge, said Tuesday.
   ``This is going to preserve and protect their habitat from
development,'' said Giezentanner. ``There are only two barrier
islands in Texas that are not developed to some degree _ Matagorda
and (adjacent) San Jose.''
</TEXT>
