<DOCNO> AP880622-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 0724EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-JapanTrade     06-22 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Japan Trade,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Negotiator Looks to Europe After Japan `Bites the Bullet''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An agreement on boosting sales of American
beef and oranges in Japan could set the stage for settling similar
agricultural issues with European nations, says the chief U.S.
trade negotiator.
   ``Now that we've been able to strike a deal with the Japanese on
beef and citrus, it puts some additional pressure on the Europeans
to be somewhat more accommodating than they have in the past,''
U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter said on Tuesday.
   Yeutter told reporters the accord signed this week in Tokyo
after prolonged dispute was the result of a fundamental change in
the attitude of Japanese leaders who showed new willingness to
settle the issue.
   The agreement calls for Japan to phase out quotas on imported
beef and fresh oranges within three years and orange juice in four
years, with the blow to Japanese domestic producers cushioned by
declining tariffs.
   The settlement was ``obviously very attractive'' for the United
States and its exporters and shows Japan has ``bitten the bullet''
and decided to begin to open its markets, Yeutter said.
   Yeutter conceded to reporters Tuesday that the original U.S.
demand for total and immediate removal of the quotas last March was
a negotiating tactic impossible for the Japanese government to
agree to.
   ``It would have been impossible for the (Japanese) government to
make that agreement and survive. So we had to work out a way to
achieve full market liberalization as quickly as possible,''
Yeutter said.
   Yeutter said the next step for the U.S. will be to press
European leaders to eliminate agricultural trade barriers there
within the next decade.
   ``It doesn't seem to us that a 10-year phase-out is unrealistic
or irrational,'' he said.
   ``It ought to be faster,'' he said. ``The world would be better
off and the European community would be better off if it were,
because the community just as much as the rest of the world'' is
hurt by farm trade barriers.
   There was no agreement over the agricultural issue at this
week's summit in Toronto between the leaders of the world's seven
leading industrialized nations, but Yeutter said the U.S. will
press for an end to barriers at the next round global trade talks
next December in Montreal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
