<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Saudi-Water     06-22 0176</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Saudi-Water,0179</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>King Fahd Inaugurates Vital Water Supply Project for Mecca</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JIDDAH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   King Fahd inaugurated a major Red
Sea desalination project that will daily pump 35 million gallons of
water into Mecca, greatly increasing the kingdom's water supply for
the annual pilgrimage.
   The $400 million plant, inaugurated Tuesday 70 miles south of
the port city of Jiddah, also will produce 15 million gallons of
water daily for the summer resort city of Taif. It will generate
325,000 kilowatts of electricity.
   The project is part of a massive development plan to better
accomodate the estimated two million Moslems who converge on Mecca
and neighboring Medina during July for the annual hajj to Islam's
holiest shrines.
   The kingdom, which claims to be the world's largest producer of
desalinated water, currently has 22 plants with a total capacity of
550 million gallons of water per day.
   Four projects, including a $640 million plant in the mountainous
Asir region, are under construction. They will supply the desert
kingdom with 30 million gallons of water daily.
</TEXT>
