<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CaptiveWomen     06-22 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Captive Women,0571</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Victims Tell of Torture, Death in Heidnik Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Contents may be offensive.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE LLOYD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A self-styled minister who enslaved four
women and killed two others in his basement torture chamber
believed society owed him a wife and a family, one of the survivors
testified at his murder trial.
   The four women spoke Tuesday about the horrors they encountered
while chained to pipes, some for months, and said Gary Heidnik
tortured and raped them repeatedly and fed them dog food mixed with
the human remains of one of his victims.
   Two survivors testified that they saw Heidnik hang Sandra
Lindsay, 24, from a pipe until she died Feb. 7, 1987, and
electrocute Deborah Dudley, 23, also known as Debbie Johnson, in a
water-filled pit in the basement.
   Heidnik's attorney describes the 44-year-old Army veteran and
financial whiz as ``very, very guilty'' but insane. He could face
the death penalty if convicted.
   During the grisly testimony, Heidnik seemed to pay no attention.
He sat in the courtroom staring straight ahead and wearing the same
flowered black Hawaiian shirt and baggy trousers he has worn to
court appearances for months.
   Josefina Rivera, who was held four months before she escaped,
told jurors that the black comedy film ``Eating Raoul,'' in which a
couple disposes of a body by mixing the flesh with food, gave
Heidnik the idea to chop up Ms. Lindsay's body, grinding parts in a
food processor and mixing it with dog food he fed his captives.
   ``He was mixing the body parts in with the dog food, because
that's the only way he could get rid of Sandra,'' Ms. Rivera said.
Heidnik first tried to dispose of the body by cooking it but
stopped after neighbors complained of the odor, she said.
   Heidnik once took a protesting Ms. Dudley upstairs and when she
was brought down, ``I asked Debbie what Gary had done,'' Ms. Rivera
testified.
   ``She said he had taken her upstairs and shown her Sandra's head
in a pot and her ribs in a roasting pan on the stove and her legs
and arms in the freezer, and that if she kept it up that's what was
going to happen to her,'' Ms. Rivera testified.
   Heidnik wanted his captives to have his children, the women
testified.
   Heidnik, who spent four years in jail for kidnapping and raping
a woman, ``felt as though society had owed him a wife and a
family,'' Ms. Rivera said.
   Lisa Thomas, who was 19 when police freed her from Heidnik's
north Philadelphia house, said she was abducted when she accepted a
ride from Heidnik and returned to his house to have sex.
   When she wanted to leave, he tried to strangle her, she
testified.
   She was taken to the basement, where Ms. Thomas said two other
women, naked from the waist down, were chained.
   Heidnik once pretended to be a police officer coming to the
women's rescue, then beat his captives when they screamed for help,
Ms. Thomas said.
   Jacquelyn Askins testified that she once heard what sounded like
a chain saw upstairs after Heidnik removed Ms. Lindsay's body from
the basement. She said she smelled the burning odor later.
   ``It was in his hair,'' Ms. Askins said of the smell. ``It was
all over him.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
