<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Refuseniks     06-22 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Refuseniks,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Refusenik Family Told by U.S. Official They Can Leave Soon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. State Department told a refusenik family
that waited in vain for a presidential visit last month that Soviet
officials will let them emigrate after 11 years of denials, a
family member said today.
   Tanya Zieman said her daughter, who was permitted to leave the
Soviet Union last year and now lives in Boston, was informed of the
decision by Richard Schifter, assistant secretary of state for
human rights and humanitarian affairs.
   The daughter, Galina Khatutsky, telephoned early today to tell
her family the news, Mrs. Zieman said. The word reportedly was
conveyed to Secretary of State George P. Shultz by Soviet
Ambassador Yuri Dubynin.
   Mrs. Zieman said she was told it would take about two weeks for
the Soviet Union to formally notify her that she, her husband,
Yuri, and their 12-year-old daughter, Vera, may leave the Soviet
Union.
   The family spent much of the previous two days seeing off best
friends who received permission to emigrate to Israel just before
the Moscow summit.
   The first indications the matter was about to be resolved came
Tuesday, when Soviet officials informally notified U.S. and other
Western diplomats that the Ziemans would soon be granted exit visas.
   Last week, the Ziemans were officially informed that their
latest appeal had been rejected by a special review commission of
the Supreme Soviet, the nominal parliament.
   Vera Zieman had written President and Mrs. Reagan appealing for
their help and the Reagans considered going to her home when they
arrived in Moscow May 29 for the U.S.-Soviet summit.
   But sources said they passed up the visit after U.S. officials
were warned such a presidential stop would doom the family's
chances to emigrate.
   The Ziemans did attend a tea the Reagans gave for people
Washington considers victims of Soviet human rights abuses and
Vera, a pianist, recently received a gift of several classical
music tapes from the first family.
   The gift wrapping from the present, with the gold presidential
seal, was on Vera's piano today in the family's tiny three-room
apartment in southwest Moscow. In a note the Ziemans received after
the summit, Reagan said he hoped one day to be able to visit them
in Boston.
   Yuri Zieman, a computer specialist who lost his job when he
applied to emigrate in 1977, worked as a plumber until stricken
several months ago by a mysterious brain ailment that left him with
double vision and a loss of balance.
   The condition, diagnosed by some Soviet physicians as a
potentially deadly aneurysm, or bulge in a cerebral artery, made
the family's quest more urgent because Zieman was warned by his
doctors not to undergo the delicate corrective surgery in the
Soviet Union.
   Zieman has been told he is not permitted to leave the country
for security reasons, though he contends he never had access to
state secrets and has no information that could threaten Soviet
security.
</TEXT>
