<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     06-22 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Reaches 127-Yen Level, Stocks Dip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar moved back to the 127-yen level today in
Tokyo for the first time in nearly three months, while share prices
declined slightly.
   After opening at 126.70, up 0.37 yen from Tuesday's finish, the
dollar continued to climb against the Japanese currency and closed
the day's trading at 127.60 yen, up a sharp 1.27 yen.
   ``Active dollar buying by Japanese institutional investors
boosted the dollar,'' said a foreign exchange dealer at a major
commercial bank, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Traders said the dollar's rise was fueled in part by a statement
by President Reagan that he thought the currency had stabilized.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, a big 213.46-point loser Tuesday, shed another
64.79 points, or 0.23 percent, and ended the day at 27,860.78.
   It was the Nikkei's third consecutive decline since the
beginning of the week.
   ``A sense that the market was rising too high prompted selling
among large-capital issues during the afternoon session, which
pulled back share prices,'' said a stock analyst with a major Tokyo
securities house, who also demanded anonymity.
   Mirroring the overnight advance on Wall Street, the Tokyo stock
market's main barometer reached 28,056.40, up 130.83 points, at the
end of the morning session, then fell back later in the day.
   Trading was moderate with volume on the first section trade
standing at 1.2 billion shares, up from 1.1 billion shares Tuesday.
   Losers included non-ferrous metals, shipbuildings, and
chemicals. Among the gainers were heavy electricals and precision
machineries.
</TEXT>
