<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Pope     06-22 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pope,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope To Use Austrian Trip To Speak To East</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II's second trip to
Austria will provide the pontiff with a platform from which he can
address the faithful in bordering Communist-ruled countries he has
been kept from visiting.
   Tens of thousands of Hungarian Catholics are expected for a Mass
on Friday at Trausdorf, less than 10 miles from the frontier.
   And Catholics from Yugoslavia's northern republics of Slovenia
and Croatia will probably flock to a Mass on Saturday at Gurk,
about 90 minutes by car from the border.
   About 60 percent of the 15.5 million Czechoslovaks are
Catholics, according to Vatican estimates, but their government's
travel restrictions are much tougher and they probably will have to
rely on television.
   The pope's tour begins Thursday and ends Monday. Austrian
television will broadcast 40 hours of the trip.
   A native of Poland, John Paul has been allowed to visit his
homeland three times since being elected in 1978 to head the
church. He has not, however, been welcome in the rest of the Soviet
bloc or non-aligned Yugoslavia.
   Cardinal Franz Koenig of Austria, who built relationships with
the Catholics of Eastern Europe in the 1960s and 1970s, predicted
the pope will reach out to the Soviet-bloc and Yugoslavia during
his Masses in Austria.
   In recent months, the Vatican has been pressuring Prague to
liberalize its treatment of the church. Catholic activists recently
got 600,000 signatures on a petition for religious freedom there.
And this month, Czechoslovakia held its first consecrations of
bishops since 1973.
   The Prague government, perhaps influenced by recent official
overtures by the Kremlin to the Russian Orthodox Church, also
allowed brief excerpts of the ceremonies to be shown on television.
Names of bishops barred from performing their duties for decades
suddenly appeared in the state-run media.
   Vatican efforts against restrictions on religion appear even
more successful in Hungary and the Soviet Union.
   Cardinal Agostino Casaroli, Vatican secretary of state, this
month attended celebrations of 1,000 years of Christianity in
Russia and gave Mikhail S. Gorbachev the first letter ever sent by
a pope to a Kremlin leader.
   Gorbachev said the Soviet Union and the Vatican have a basis for
further talks in the common struggle for peace, and did not exclude
eventual diplomatic relations.
   In Hungary, where an estimated 5 million of the 10.6 million
people are Roman Catholics, the church may be able to improve its
legal standing in a current revision of religious laws.
   Cardinal Laszlo Paskai, who has criticized predecessors for not
standing up to curbs on religion, is said to have a good
relationship with Imre Miklos, head of the government office on
church affairs.
   In Yugoslavia, relations between the Communists of Slovenia and
Croatia and their Catholic churches are far from easy.
   One major obstacles to a papal visit there is a reported wish by
John Paul to visit the grave of Cardinal Aloisius Stepanac in
Zagreb Cathedral. The Communists call Stepanac a war criminal who
collaborated with the Nazi puppet regime in Croatia during World
War II.
</TEXT>
