<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Costly Insult,0168</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former High Official Gets Jail For Insulting The Monarchy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today sentenced a
former deputy interior minister to four years in prison for
insulting the monarchy, a provincial court official said today.
   The Supreme Court agreed with a lower court decision that
remarks made by former minister Veera Musikapong during a political
campaign were intended to insult King Bhumibol Adulyadej,
Thailand's constitutional ruler.
   But the court reduced the original sentence of six years because
of Veera's past services to the country, said Chamnong
Kerdsoongneon, the court official.
   Veera, 40, was accused of making the allegedly insulting remarks
on July 13, 1986 while campaigning for a seat in the lower house of
Parliament.
   Veera's remarks contrasted the life of the peasant to life in
the Royal Palace. Media directly reproducing remarks deemed
insulting to the monarchy may face the same lese majeste charges.
   Lese majeste in Thailand carries a maximum pealty of 15 years
imprisonment.
</TEXT>
