<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea-Labor,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor Protests Spread To Foreign Firms, Banks, Embassies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korean workers at the French
Embassy in Seoul said today they would strike unless the embassy
allows them to form a union and changes what they call an unfair
pay system.
   The threat comes during a wave of strikes at Korean companies in
recent months by workers who demand better pay and working
conditions. Strikes also have hit some foreign firms.
   On Tuesday, Korean workers at the French Embassy began a sit-in
inside the embassy compound, shouting slogans, during their lunch
hour. They worked normally during office hours.
   The workers said the job action would begin on June 30.
   They said French Embassy officials refused to allow them to form
a union on the grounds foreign embassies have extraterritorial
rights. They also accused the embassy of basing pay on an unfair
system of rating worker performance.
   Foreign Ministry officials said they were studying international
practices to see whether the formation of labor unions would be
possible at foreign legations, which don't come under South Korean
jurisdiction.
   ``We are afraid it would cause diplomatic disputes,'' said a
ministry official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Korean workers at other embassies, including those of Canada,
West Germany, Denmark and the Netherlands, are also seeking to form
labor unions.
   Meanwhile, about 400 union leaders at 37 foreign bank branches
in Seoul held a peaceful joint rally Tuesday night at a downtown
park to support striking workers at the Seoul branch of Australia's
Westpac Banking Corp.
   ``Respect our national pride'' and ``Expel white supremacy,''
they shouted as a Korean union leader from Bank of America accused
some foreign firms of suppressing union activity. The union leaders
vowed to take collective action, contending that Westpac had
unfairly treated 17 Korean workers who began a wildcat strike May
27 for more money.
   Speakers at the rally maintained that foreign firms, banks and
embassies have ignored demands by Korean workers.
   At the Seoul branch of Japan's Mitsui and Co., 82 Korean workers
began an indefinite strike Monday, demanding an end to what they
called unfavorable regulations and suppression of union activities.
   The strikers drove Japanese employees out of their office and
barricaded the office doors with tables.
</TEXT>
