<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ContraLayoffs     06-22 0313</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contra Layoffs,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contra Expense Cuts Won't Affect Troops, Spokeswoman Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaraguan Contra troops in the field will not be
affected by deep cuts in administrative staff and expenses planned
for the end of the month, a spokeswoman for the U.S.-backed rebels
says.
   ``We are not closing _ it's just a matter of trying to function
with less cost,'' spokeswoman Marta Sacasa said late Tuesday.
   Layoffs are expected at the Miami headquarters and at other
Contra political offices, although some employees may continue as
unpaid volunteers.
   ``By the 30th (of June), I understand nobody is sure who will
continue working,'' Ms. Sacasa said, adding that the Contra
directors have not announced the extent of the layoffs or the
top-to-bottom ``restructuring'' that will accompany them.
   She denied cutbacks were directly related to Congress' refusal
to back the Reagan administration's full budget request for the
Contras this year.
   In March, Congress adopted a limited $47.9 million budget
limited to humanitarian aid, and although the administration is
expected to ask for more money, legislative leaders give new
funding little chance.
   The rebel political staff also has had exceptionally high
expenses so far this year, in part because of trips to and from
Central America to negotiate a truce with Nicaragua's leftist
government.
   The New York Times today quoted Silvio Arguello Cardenal, vice
president of the Contra legislative assembly, as saying layoff
notices have been mailed to 350 to 400 employees in Contra offices
in Miami, Washington, Latin America and Europe.
   Ms. Sacasa said that as far as she knew no employees had
received the official notice by Tuesday. She added that directors
would do their best to ensure that no employees would be ``out on
the street.''
   ``We're giving the directors the freedom to do what has to be
done to be more productive,'' she said.
</TEXT>
