<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NBANewspage     06-22 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NBA Newspage,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Los Angeles Lakers Repeat As National Basketball Champs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INGLEWOOD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James Worthy's 36 points led Los
Angeles as the Lakers held off the Detroit Pistons 108-105 to
become the first team in 19 years to win back-to-back NBA
championships.
   Tuesday night's victory in the deciding game of the
best-of-seven series also gave the Lakers their fifth National
Basketball Association title in this decade and 11th overall.
   The Lakers, who trailed 52-47 at halftime, hit their first 10
shots of the third quarter on the way to a 15-point lead, then held
off a furious rally by the Pistons in the final 12 minutes.
   Led by Worthy, the series' Most Valuable Player, the Lakers
became the first repeat champions in the NBA since the Boston
Celtics did it in 1969.
   By successfully defending last year's crown in the seven-game
championship, the Lakers fulfilled a guarantee by Coach Pat Riley.
They did so despite just four points and three rebounds from Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar, the NBA's all-time leading scorer.
   ``I'm going to guarantee everyone we're going to repeat,'' Riley
said minutes after the Lakers beat the Celtics a year ago.
   The sellout Forum crowd of 17,505 screamed ``Repeat, repeat''
during every timeout and swarmed the court after the game.
   The Pistons, making their first appearance in the championship
series since moving to Detroit 31 years ago, became the first team
since Seattle in 1978 to lose the finals after taking a 3-2 lead.
</TEXT>
