<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RubySlippers     06-22 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ruby Slippers,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retansmits a0526 to delete editors note</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dorothy's Ruby Slippers Fetch $165,000; Monroe Photos $53,955</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY11</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A house had to drop on a witch before Dorothy
could get the magic ruby slippers, but $165,000 did the trick for a
man bidding on the shimmering shoes that Judy Garland wore skipping
down the Yellow Brick Road.
   The auction room at Christie's East, which seats about 400
people, was standing-room-only Tuesday as a bidding war drove up
the price to more than eight times the presale estimate of $15,000
to $20,000.
   ``When our expert asked him (the anonymous buyer) what he'd do
with them, he said, `Treasure them,''' said Lee Anne Fahey,
spokeswoman for Christie's East.
   Later in the auction of movie memorabilia and other
collectibles, $53,955 was paid for 96 unpublished color slides of a
young Marilyn Monroe taken in Los Angeles in 1945 by William
Carroll.
   The slides were sold in 16 lots, all to anonymous buyers. The
most expensive, for $6,380, featured eight color studies of Miss
Monroe, seated on a seaside boulder and wearing white suspender
shorts and a red and white T-shirt.
   Carroll, who owned a film processing laboratory, hired the
19-year-old model, then known as Norma Jean Dougherty, to pose for
advertising cards that he displayed on counter tops at photo
stores. None of the counter cards are known to remain in existence,
Christie's said.
   The size 6B ``Wizard of Oz'' slippers _ topped with 2,300
crimson-dyed sequins and soled with orange felt to muffle footsteps
on the sound stage _ were among seven or eight pairs worn by Miss
Garland while filming the 1939 MGM classic. Only five sets are
known to exist today. Roberta Jeffries Bauman of Memphis, Tenn.,
had won this pair in a contest in February 1940 when she was 16.
   ``They are considered the `purest' by those who believe in their
magic, and are the best known to Oz fanciers, having been in
private hands 30 years longer than any other pair,'' the auction
catalog said.
   The price, which included a 10 percent commission to Christie's,
was a record for any type of shoes sold at auction and for a single
movie property, Ms. Fahey said.
   Other big sellers included:
   _An Elvis Presley Army uniform from the 1960 movie, ``GI
Blues,'' which eclipsed its presale estimate of $1,000 to $1,500 to
command $12,100;
   _A set of 14 lithographs by John Lennon, depicting his marriage
and honeymoon with Yoko Ono, $6,600;
   _A portrait by Richard Bernstein of the late actor Harris Glenn
Milstead, better known as Divine, $2,200;
   _A Cecil Beaton photographic study of Marilyn Monroe, $2,090;
   _A pair of black, western boots, appliqued with a grand piano
motif for Liberace, $1,045.
</TEXT>
