<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Terrorists-Vermont     06-22 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Terrorists-Vermont,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Men Convicted of Smuggling Bomb Set to Be Sentenced</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANICA KIRKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BURLINGTON, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Canadians who smuggled a bomb into
the United States were bunglers who got caught, not members of a
Syrian terrorist group that assassinated Bashir Gemayel in Lebanon,
a defense attorney says.
   Georges Younan, Walid Mourad and Walid Kabbani faced sentencing
today in U.S. District Court. Younan faces up to 35 years in
prison, Kabbani faces 30 years and six months and Mourad faces 10
years.
   ``I think the government's attempt to say they're part of a
terrorist group is greatly exaggerated,'' said Art Anderson,
Younan's attorney. ``I think it should be kept in perspective.''
   The men, who were born in Lebanon, were arrested last Oct. 23
after crossing the border at Richford.
   Mourad pleaded guilty Jan. 26 to conspiring to transport
explosives and an immigration violation. A jury convicted Younan
and Kabbani on several charges of explosives violations and an
immigration violation.
   U.S. Attorney George Terwilliger III and the FBI said the men
are members of the Syrian Social Nationalist Party. The party was
founded in the fascist era of the 1930s and devoted to the
formation of ``Greater Syria,'' would have united Lebanon and what
was then Palestine under Syrian hegemony.
   Members of the group have claimed responsibility for the 1982
assasination of Lebanese President-elect Gemayel, according to
Floyd Clarke, an assistant director of the FBI's criminal
investigative division.
   The trio's offenses represent ``an attempt to import those
techniques (of violence) into the United States,'' Terwilliger said.
   The three were arrested in Richford after the police chief
spotted them behaving suspiciously near the international border. A
search of their van turned up explosives, authorities said.
   Since their arrest, the three have been held at the Northwest
State Correctional Facility in St. Albans.
</TEXT>
