<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--JusticeResigns     06-22 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Justice Resigns,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Justice Becomes Third to Resign in Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state Supreme Court justice says he will
step down to look for a better-paying job, making him the third
justice to resign in less than a year.
   ``I'm tired of being the lowest-paid lawyer in the courtroom,''
Justice James Wallace said Tuesday. Justices are paid $79,000 a
year.
   Wallace said he would resign Sept. 1, a move that would put the
seat on the November ballot and allow Democratic and Republican
officials to pick candidates. Republican Gov. Bill Clements will
appoint an interim justice to serve until the November election
results are certified.
   Wallace was elected to the court in 1980 and re-elected in 1986.
His current term ends in 1993. He said he would practice law in
Austin or Houston.
   Chief Justice John L. Hill and Justice Robert Campbell, both
Democrats, submitted their resignations late last year. Hill quit
to devote time to his push for appointed, instead of elected, state
judges. Campbell quit to campaign in favor of keeping the elected
system.
</TEXT>
