<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heat Bakes Central United States; Thunderstorms Sweep South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A persistent heat wave baked several spots around the country
today while thunderstorms struck the central Plains and South after
whipping up destructive winds in Arkansas and Alabama.
   Tuesday's high temperatures in the central United States were
the hottest in some spots that have been observed during the month
of June. Afternoon highs soared to 109 at Huron, S.D., 108 at Sioux
City, Iowa, 103 at Des Moines, Iowa, 102 at Fort Wayne, Ind., and
101 at South Bend, Ind.
   The high temperature of 110 degrees at Sioux Falls, S.D.,
equaled its all-time record.
   A cold front in the north central United States offered some
relief from the heat but not much hope for rain.
   A thunderstorm Tuesday night in Arkansas produced high winds at
Black Oak that damaged four homes and a trailer home, injuring two
people. A thunderstorm in Alabama stirred high winds north of
Hamilton, destroying a house, ripping the roofs off three barns and
downing many trees and power lines.
   Widely scattered showers and thunderstorms swept through the
central Plains and the Great Lakes region early this morning.
Strong thunderstorms also hit parts of Wisconsin and Michigan. A
cold front brought showers to the northern Pacific coast. Dry
weather prevailed across the rest of the nation, with clear skies
in the south central nation.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms scattered
from northern New England across the Great Lakes region to Iowa, as
well as from southeast Texas to the southern half of the Atlantic
coast; and afternoon thunderstorms widely scattered from the
Plateau region and the Rockies.
   Temperatures were forecast in the upper 80s or 90s across much
of the nation; in the 70s along the Pacific coast; in the 70s to
mid-80s from Minnesota into upper Michigan and from the eastern
Great Lakes into northern New England; reaching 100 to 110 degrees
across the desert Southwest; and around 100 degrees from Kansas to
Indiana and over the northern High Plains.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 53
degrees at Arcata, Calif., to 94 degrees at Phoenix, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 77 partly cloudy; Boston 68 partly cloudy;
Buffalo 66 cloudy; Charleston, S.C. 73 fair; Cincinnati 71 fair;
Cleveland 77 partly cloudy; Detroit 82 fair; Miami 80 fair; New
York 69 foggy; Philadelphia 74 hazy; Pittsburgh 77 hazy; Portland,
Maine 61 partly cloudy; Washington 79 hazy.
   _Central: Bismarck 66 fair; Chicago 81 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
77 fair; Denver 66 fair; Des Moines 86 fair; Indianapolis 73 fair;
Kansas City 81 windy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 77 fair; Nashville 73
fair; New Orleans 72 fair; St. Louis 81 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 79 fair; Anchorage 59 cloudy; Las Vegas 82
thunderstorms; Los Angeles 59 partly cloudy; Phoenix 93 fair; Salt
Lake City 76 partly cloudy; San Diego 63 fair; San Francisco 58
fair; Seattle 65 cloudy.
   _Canada: Montreal 63 fair; Toronto 66 showers.
</TEXT>
