<HEAD>Dollar Up, Gold Prices Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar rose in early European trading today
with the piercing of two significant chart levels spurring on a
bullish, moderately active market.
   Gold prices were lower.
   Foreign exchange dealers said large institutional investors in
the Far East were heavy buyers of dollars after the U.S. currency
rose above a significant chart level of 126.50 yen.
   Although the dollar was stable in early European trading,
dealers said it spurted higher once it pierced the technical
resistance level of around 1.7625 deutsche marks.
   ``The story is still the same; the market is buying dollars''
because of strong underlying bullish sentiments, said one senior
trader with an Italian bank in Rome. ``The market is all on one
side.''
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar rose 1.27 yen to a closing 127.60 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted higher at 128.15 yen.
   In London, the dollar edged up against the British pound, which
was quoted at $1.7770, compared with $1.7855 on Tuesday.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday:
   _ 1.7627 West German marks, up from 1.7548
   _ 1.4645 Swiss francs, up from 1.4623
   _ 5.9395 French francs, up from 5.9245
   _ 1.9822 Dutch guilders, up from 1.9755
   _ 1,307.75 Italian lire, up from 1,304.00
   _ 1.2075 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2079
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $449.50 a troy ounce,
down from late Tuesday's $451.00. At mid-morning Tuesday, the
city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of
$449.80.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $449.95 down from $451.50 late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.29 to close at a bid $451.46.
   Silver bullion was quoted in London today at a bid price of
$7.12 a troy ounce, down from Tuesday's $7.19.
</TEXT>
