<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 0713EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Poland-Radio     06-22 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland-Radio,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spokesman Offers To Confront Radio Free Europe Staff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban has
offered to travel to Munich, West Germany, to confront the staff of
U.S.-funded Radio Free Europe about what he calls distortions in
its Polish-language broadcasts.
   The president of Radio Free Europe, Gene Pell, said the station
accepts Urban's challenge and will accept an invitation to send
members of its staff to Poland.
   ``I am hereby announcing a proposal which I am addressing to ..
. the head of Radio Free Europe in Munich,'' Urban told a news
conference Tuesday.
   ``If you are not afraid of discussion about the role of Radio
Free Europe against the backdrop of the situation in Poland, then I
declare my readiness to come to Munich.''
   Urban added that staff members of the station could also come to
Poland.
   Pell issued a statement Tuesday night saying he welcomed Urban's
offer and planned to forward a formal invitation to Urban today.
   Pell said the station also would accept the offer to send staff
members to Warsaw.
   A secretary to Urban said today that he was not in the office so
could not comment immediately on Pell's reply.
   Jamming of Polish-language broadcasts of Radio Free Europe,
Voice of America and the British Broadcasting Corp. ended Jan. 1.
The end of jamming was accompanied by a stepped-up Polish media
campaign against the stations, particularly Radio Free Europe.
   The station broadcasts uncensored news and commentary to Poland.
   Urban and the official press have accused it of inaccuracies and
waging psychological warfare against Poland. Specifically attacked
have been the station's reports after the 1986 Chernobyl nuclear
disaster, its coverage of price increases earlier this year and its
reports on strikes in Poland in April and May.
   In general, the station is accused of exaggerating Poland's
problems and inciting unrest.
   ``As a relic of the Cold War, Radio Free Europe is an obvious
anachronism,'' said a commentary today on the state-run news
service PAP. It ``misses the spirit of our times, new political ..
. thinking and the current trend in East-West relations.''
   In addition to direct attacks on the station, the government has
taken steps to demonstrate that it does not fear the broadcasts.
   For instance, Polish state radio has a weekly program in which
it repeats without comment excerpts of Western broadcasts. And the
communist party newspaper Trybuna Ludu has a new column in which it
reprints three or four quotes from government critics interviewed
on Western stations, followed by a pithy response in italics.
   Two emigre Poles employed by Radio Free Europe who moved back to
Poland were given highly publicized television interviews last week
in which they described the station's work.
   Estimates for the number of listeners vary. The government says
16 percent of Poles listen to Radio Free Europe at least
occasionally. Radio Free Europe puts the number at 59 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
