<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 0716EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater 1stLd-Writethru a0902 06-22 0678</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0902,0689</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Revival of `Juno and the Paycock' Opens on Broadway</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 4 grafs with other reviews.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than six decades after it was written, Sean
O'Casey's ``Juno and the Paycock'' still has the power to move an
audience to laughter and tears.
   Both are present in the extraordinary yet remarkably
unsentimental revival which opened Tuesday at Broadway's Golden
Theater as part of the First New York International Festival of the
Arts.
   This straightforward production, from the Gate Theater in
Dublin, is tough and unrelenting as it tells the sad tale of the
bibulous Capt. Jack Boyle and his long-suffering wife Juno, who eke
out their lives in a Dublin tenement.
   The Boyle home _ a wonderful decrepit design by Frank Hallinan
Flood _ doesn't radiate warmth. It's a dismal place where shatterx ty.
He's a
foolish Everyman, evading employment and responsibility for his
wife and children.
   The florid-faced Donal McCann beautifully captures Boyle's
childish dreams, particularly after the character learns he has
inherited a great deal of money from a distant relative. It's the
salvation Boyle has been dreaming about but unwilling to work for.
Only after the inheritance has turned to dust does his foolishness
take on a poignant quality that turns to despair by the end of the
play.
   Boyle spends much of his time in the company of Joxer Daly, a
spectral figure who, in the Gate revival, resembles one of
Beckett's alienated creatures. The Beckett analogy is particularly
apt because of the startling performance by John Kavanagh, a crone
of a man who's as much of a scavanger as he is a lost soul.
   Still, there is a lot of humor in these characters' daily lives.
Boyle and Joxer have a long breakfast reverie in Act 1 that is one
of the comic highlights of the play. They rail against the world's
problems without coming up with any solutions.
   The captain stands in contrast to Juno, a sad, sensible woman
who worries about her daughter Mary, on strike from her job, and
son Johnny, a morose homebody whose arm was blown off during the
war for independence.
   Geraldine Plunkett has the resilience needed to convey Juno's
sense of survival and duty, while Rosemary Fine and Joe Savino
capture the unhappy, defeated lives of the Boyle children. Another
standout in the large cast is Maureen Potter as the boisterous
neighbor Maisie Madigan.
   Director Joe Dowling keeps the high spirits under control and
avoids the maudlin as the play builds toward its inevitable tragic
finale.
   ``Th' whole worl's in a terrible state o' chassis!'' says a
sodden Boyle who never could pronounce the word `chaos.' It's one
of his favorite refrains and reappears often during the play.
   Boyle mutters it as the curtain falls on the final act. It's to
the credit of this production that audiences can see the statement
not just as a metaphor for Ireland, but for a family whose center
no longer holds.
   In other reviews:
   Frank Rich of The New York Times called the production ``alive
at every level _ as boisterous comedy, as wrenching tragedy, as
blistering social commentary.''
   In the Daily News, Howard Kissel writes that ``few plays capture
the soul of a nation as powerfully as `Juno and the Paycock.''' He
praises McCann as ``memorable'' and Kavanaugh as ``masterly,'' but
writes that ``the women are less strong.''
   Clive Barnes in the New York Post said the production is ``one
of the greatest nights the New York theater has seen in years. ...
the ironic mingling of tragedy and comedy _ and here O'Casey
demands comparison with Shakespeare _ has never been so much to the
life before.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
