<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NoriegaWitness     06-22 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Noriega Witness,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sentenced Pilot Key Witness Against Noriega, Prosecutors Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pilot sentenced to nine years in prison on
drug-smuggling charges would be the major witness against Manuel
Antonio Noriega if the Panamanian general ever comes here to face a
federal drug indictment.
   Floyd Carlton Caceres was sentenced after pleading guilty to one
count of conspiracy to import cocaine, Chief Assistant U.S.
Attorney Richard Gregorie said Tuesday.
   ``If Gen. Noriega comes to trial at some future time, this
defendant will be the key witness against him,'' Gregorie said.
   U.S. District Judge Sidney Aronovitz sentenced Carlton late
Monday to the 9-year term, but Carlton could be released on parole
after serving three years.
   The prosecutor reviewed for the judge Carlton's role in the
Noriega indictment. Carlton has been held at the federal
Metropolitan Correctional Center south of Miami since his
extradition from Costa Rica.
   Carlton's testimony before a Miami grand jury was crucial in
indicting Noriega in February, and he even donned a black hood to
tell a U.S. Senate panel how Noriega protected Colombian drug lords.
   Carlton told authorities he personally flew arms to Central
American leftists for Noriega and brought cocaine shipments into
Panama.
   In February, the Panamanian-born Carlton told the Senate
committee that Noriega contracted in 1982 to protect drug flights
of the notorious Colombia-based Medellin cartel, responsible for up
to 80 percent of U.S. cocaine imports.
   ``We did nothing without his approval,'' Carlton said of Noriega
during the hearing.
   Carlton said he acted as a go-between for the cartel and
Noriega, even recounting how the general laughed off the smugglers'
original $30,000 offer for landing rights in Panama.
   ``He told me that if these people thought he was begging, they
were wrong,'' the Spanish-speaking Carlton testified through a
translator.
   Noriega eventually received up to $200,000 a flight, said the
pilot, who said he personally flew several flights from Colombia to
Panama.
   Carlton also told Congress that Noriega personally authorized
air shipments of weapons to leftist guerrillas in El Salvador and
the rebel Sandinistas in Nicaragua before they overthrew the
government of Anastasio Somoza Debayle in 1979. Carlton said he
also made some of those flights.
   The pilot was eventually accused by the cartel of stealing a
cocaine shipment; at the same time drug agents in Florida
intercepted a flight by an associate, who named him as a fellow
smuggler.
   Carlton tried to make a deal with U.S. authorities without
surrendering, but was eventually lured to Costa Rica, where he was
arrested and extradited.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880622-0095 </DOCNO>
