<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Infiltration 1stLd-Writethru   06-22 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Infiltration, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0556,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: Israeli Troops Capture Four Palestinian Guerrillas</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with army attribution. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops captured four Palestinian
guerrillas trying to sneak into Israel before dawn today to attack
a northern civilian settlement, the army said.
   It was the 15th infiltration or attempted infiltration since an
Arab uprising began in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip on Dec.8.
   Three of the Palestinians were wounded in a brief firefight
before the squad surrendered, but the Israeli troops suffered no
casualties, an army spokesman said.
   The guerrillas belonged to the pro-Syrian Popular Front for the
Liberation of Palestine headed by George Habash, Israel radio said.
   They were captured in southern Lebanon, north of Israel's
self-declared ``security zone'' and opposite the Israeli border
settlement of Kfar Yuval, three miles northeast of Kiryat Shmona,
the army said.
   In a brief communique, the army said its troops ``foiled an
attempt by a guerrilla squad which tried to infiltrate Israel and
launch a terror attack against one of the civilian settlements in
the north.''
   The attempted penetration came on a day of general strikes in
the occupied territories and a call by Palestinian underground
leaders to set fires to Israeli factories and farmlands.
   The guerrillas were armed with machine guns, rocket-propelled
grenades, hand grenades and explosives, the army spokesman said,
adding that they also carried food supplies.
   Israel established the ``security zone'' in southern Lebanon in
the summer of 1985. About 1,000 Israeli troops currently patrol the
mostly Moslem area along with Israel's Lebanese ally, the
predominantly Christian South Lebanon Army.
</TEXT>
