<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 0947EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Egypt-Fire 3rdLd-Writethru   06-22 0596</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Egypt-Fire, 3rd Ld - Writethru,a0562,0612</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Near Coptic Monastery Kills 47 Pilgrims, Mostly Children</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to RECAST and edit. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ASSIUT, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fire set off by sparks from a cooking
booth swept through a city of tents housing thousands of Coptic
Christians attending a religious festival, police said. Forty-seven
people were killed.
   The victims, most of them children, either died in the blaze or
were trampled to death in the rush to escape, a senior police
official said.
   The fire broke out late Tuesday in the tent city at the foot of
the al-Muharraq Monastery in al-Qusiyyah, north of this southern
provincial capital, authorities said.
   The fire began when sparks from a makeshift food booth touched
some tents, igniting them and setting off a chain reaction in which
about three dozen butane lamps exploded, the police official said,
speaking on condition of anonymity. He said the booth's two owners,
both Copts, were arrested.
   Witnesses said monks quickly closed the monastery's massive door
when the fire broke out. This caused panic-stricken pilgrims, who
initially dashed to the building for refuge, to turn back and rush
to the gate of the fenced tent city.
   ``There was was a big rush from the pilgrims towards the main
gate of the camp. Some children fell and were trampled to death,''
the police official said.
   The police official said 26 children, 15 men and six women died
in the blaze. He said 15 people were injured trying to escape.
   The monastery, a 10-acre compound with 70 to 80 monks in
residence, was not damaged.
   Foul play was not suspected in the fire.
   The police official said authorities had authorized burial of
the dead, which in Egypt is allowed only when the cause of death is
not in question and a corpse is not required for criminal
investigation.
   ``The fire caught us by surprise,'' said a survivor, one of the
pilgrims. The man appeared dazed and refused to give his name.
   ``There wasn't enough water in the tent city to extinguish the
fire. Apparently there was no fire-fighting equipment at the
monastery,'' said the survivor.
   Fire engines were summoned from nearby villages and eight of
them arrived on the scene ``a full hour after the fire started,''
he said.
   A preliminary police report estimated damage at $420,000.
   The monastery is built at the site of a cave where tradition
says Joseph, Mary and the infant Jesus took shelter on their flight
into Egypt. The Holy Family left Palestine after King Herod ordered
all male children killed.
   The church, inside the monastery, is among the oldest in Egypt,
although its exact origins are unknown. The name of the monastery
means ``The Burnt Monastery.''
   The pilgrims were at an annual festival dedicated to the Virgin
Mary.
   About 50,000 people customarily celebrate the Feast of the
Consecration of the Church of the Virgin held every June 21-28. But
Tuesday, only about 5,000 pilgrims were inside the tent city near
the monastery.
   Formerly a Christian stronghold, the Assiut area has become in
recent years a hotbed of Moslem fundamentalist militancy. Several
times, Moslem extremists have attacked Coptic Christian shops.
   Unlike many early Coptic monasteries built in desert isolation,
al-Muharraq is along a relatively well-traveled route near the Nile
River about 35 miles north of Assiut. The provincial capital is 240
miles south of Cairo.
   The Coptic Orthodox church is reputed to be the oldest community
in Christendom. It traces its origins to the disciple St. Mark, who
tradition says founded a congregation in Alexandria in the first
century.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880622-0099 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 0950EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TelevisionTimber     06-22 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Television Timber,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Neighbor Arrested In Tree Chopping To Clear Up Satellite Reception</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REDDING, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An admitted television addict has been
charged with cutting down a neighbor's tree that apparently stood
between his satellite dish and clear reception of the Disney
Channel.
   Arthur Anderson, a 59-year-old construction worker, has been
charged with second-degree criminal mischief and third-degree
criminal trespassing in the June 12 incident, according to Redding
police officer Brian T. Jones.
   He's scheduled to appear in court July 1.
   Charles Marriner, a 62-year-old financial analyst, awoke that
Sunday morning to discover the 50-foot tall oak tree lying on its
side on his wooded property.
   ``It's very unfortunate to think that someone can walk on your
property and cut something down that took 80 or 90 years to grow,''
Marriner said.
   ``I've heard of people who have satellite dishes around here but
cutting down somebody's tree for better reception goes a little
above and beyond,'' said Patrolman John Leonard.
   Anderson claimed that the tree felling, spotted by several
children playing nearby, was a mistake.
   ``I didn't know whose property I was on,'' Anderson said.
   He also said the lure of distant television signals via the
satellite dish is all-consuming.
   ``That dish has caused me more problems. We're TV addicts. Me
and my wife watch it all the time. Disney, baseball, the Yankees,
we pick it all up. I got bicycle races on now. You've never seen
anything like it,'' Anderson said.
   He said he has gotten telephone calls from supporters who have
asked him to cut down trees that are blocking their satellite
signals.
   ``I got one from a girl who said she wanted to be able to get
the Disney Channel, too,'' he said.
   Anderson said he has offered to pay Marriner $500 in damages and
to haul away the dead tree in exchange for his neighbor dropping
the charges. Marriner has refused.
   ``The scoundrel. He knew what he was doing. We're all just lucky
it didn't fall on somebody,'' Marriner said.
</TEXT>
