<1ST_LINE>r p PM-NewJersey-Jackson     06-22 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-New Jersey-Jackson,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Gets Eight More New Jersey Delegates in Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JO ASTRID GLADING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAMILTON TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New Jersey Democrats defused a
growing party dispute by increasing Jesse Jackson's delegation at
the Democratic National Convention next month in Atlanta.
   The compromise reached Tuesday night between supporters of
Jackson and Michael Dukakis gives Jackson eight more delegates, in
addition to the nine delegates he won in the June 7 primary.
   Jackson's supporters felt he deserved more than nine delegates
because he won 33 percent of the popular vote.
   Newark Mayor Sharpe James, who was elected as one of the Jackson
delegates, said he was confident his candidate's voice will be
heard at the convention.
   ``Those of us who support and worked hard for Jesse Jackson go
to the Democratic Convention in Atlanta next month are optimistic
that many of the goals and principles of the Jackson campaign will
be embodied within the Democratic party platform,'' James said.
   He said state Democrats must work after the convention to change
New Jersey's winner-take-all delegate system that left Jackson with
33 percent of the popular vote but only 12 percent of the delegates.
   ``We need to restructure our delegate districts more fairly so
that the strength of urban voters is not diluted,'' James said.
   State Democratic leaders also voted to send Acadamy
Award-winning actress Olympia Dukakis to the convention next month
in Atlanta as an at-large delegate for Dukakis, her cousin.
</TEXT>
