<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FuneralHome     06-22 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Funeral Home,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Funeral Director Blames Lack Of Payments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A funeral home director said customers
who didn't pay for funerals they ordered were to blame for his
failure to bury 44 bodies found in his funeral home earlier this
month.
   Investigators discovered the decomposing remains stashed in
closets, hearses and storage rooms at the closed Howell Morning
Glory Chapel.
   Lewis J. Howell was charged Tuesday with 42 criminal counts,
including six felony counts alleging he accepted money from
individuals for burial services that were never performed.
   He was also charged with 36 misdemeanor counts alleging fraud
and failure to perform the duties of a licensed funeral home
director. Virgil Green, city Welfare Division chief, said officials
have evidence that Howell billed the city $100 each for four
cremations that he didn't perform.
   Howell wasn't charged in some cases because they fell outside
the statute of limitations. At least two of the people died as long
ago as 1978.
   If convicted of all charges, Howell faces up to 30 years in
prison.
   ``People came in and made arrangements and never came back
again,'' Howell said in an interview broadcast Tuesday by
Jacksonville radio station WOKV.
   Howell's wife, Margaret, said her husband was too proud to admit
he had a problem and even hid what was going on from her. She said
her husband buried the bodies of indigents covered under a city
contract.
</TEXT>
