<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Bear     06-22 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bear,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bear Ties Up Downtown; Authorities Wait It Out</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LITTLETON, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 300-pound black bear who stumped police
and entranced onlookers by spending the day in a downtown tree
headed back to the woods early today.
   ``That poor bear wasn't going to come down in the day,''
firefighter Bill Sargent said. ``It was just waiting for night and
for everyone to get away.''
   The police had planned to wait until today to decide what to do
about the bear; they hoped it would leave by itself. They found the
tree empty when they cruised by at about 1:30 a.m.
   ``I don't know what the townspeople will do for excitement
today, though,'' Sargent said. The tree was about 500 feet from
town hall in this northern New Hampshire community of about 6,000
residents.
   The treed bear drew a crowd of spectators on Tuesday, including
children on their first day out of school.
   While officers made sure no one got close enough to get into
trouble if the bear decided to come down during daylight, the
dispatcher at headquarters was busy with calls from people who had
ideas on how to get the bear down.
   ``My phone has been ringing off the hook with suggestions,''
said the dispatcher, who declined to give her name. ``One person
said to get a long pole, tie a rag on the end and dip it in honey''
to coax the animal down.
   ``Another said `Use ice cream. Bears love ice cream.'
   ``And one suggested climbing the tree, and believe it or not,
just talking the bear down like you would a child or your pet,''
she said.
   Chief Louis Babin said it's likely the bear had visited the tree
before and had not been noticed.
   This time, one of his officers saw the animal on the street
early Tuesday, and Babin said the cruiser's light may have spooked
it and sent it up the tree.
</TEXT>
