<HEAD>Cable Car Fares May Go Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For tourists and others who plan to leave
their hearts in San Francisco, it soon could cost a dollar more to
climb halfway to the stars.
   In what the song calls ``the city's little cable cars,'' cost of
public transport is due for a hike.
   The five-member San Francisco Public Utilities Commission voted
unanimously Tuesday night to raise fares from $1.50 to $2.50.
   If approved by the Board of Supervisors, the new fares will go
into effect on August 1, according to Municipal Railway General
Manager William Stead.
   The increase is part of a plan to improve Muni revenues without
boosting fares for the elderly or youngsters.
