<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Blast, 4th Ld - Writethru,a0523,a0542,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Explosion In East Beirut Kills One Person, Wounds 18</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with fatality, guerrilla fighting;
no pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb exploded in Christian east
Beirut today, killing one person and wounding 18 and setting six
shops on fire, police reported.
   A police spokesman, who cannot be named under standing
regulations, said the car bomb blew up at 11 a.m. in the Karantina
district.
   The explosion, the sixth car bombing in Lebanon this year, also
damaged six cars, the spokesman said.
   Fire engines and ambulances raced to the scene as police experts
examined the remains of the car that contained the explosives.
   The Voice of Lebanon radio said black smoke billowed from the
site of the explosion.
   By police count, 93 people have been killed and 233 wounded in
the five earlier car bombings this year. There have been no claims
of responsibility for any of the bombings.
   Also in Beirut today, Yasser Arafat's guerrillas said they beat
back attacks by Col. Saeed Mousa's Fatah-Uprising in Beirut's
devastated refugee camps of Chatilla and Bourj el-Barajneh, as
fighting raged with howitzers and rockets.
   Police said at least five people were killed and 16 wounded in
the battles between Arafat's Fatah faction, the main component of
the Palestine Liberation Organization, and the radical,
Syrian-backed Fatah-Uprising.
   That raised the known casualty toll since fighting flared 13
days ago to 51 killed and 204 wounded.
   The rival Palestinian factions are fighting for control of south
Beirut's shantytowns.
   Lebanon has been torn for 13 years by a civil war that has mosty
pitted Moslem against Christian militias.
</TEXT>
