<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0431 06-22 0781</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0431,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Vows He Won't Be `Out-Hustled' By Dukakis</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: TOP 7 grafs new with Bush comment; picks up 4th graf pvs,
bgng, `We're ready.'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush today denied he was
engaging in name-calling in his attacks on rival Michael Dukakis
and said he will continue to set the record straight on the
differences between the two presidential contenders.
   ``It's the record _ what he favors and what I favor. It's not
name-calling,'' Bush said aboard Air Force Two en route to
Louisville, Ky., where he was scheduled to address the National
Sheriffs Association.
   Bush said he hasn't seen much emphasis in news reports or
Democratic statements on the differences between himself and the
Massachusetts governor.
   ``Yet they are there. If people like that kind of thing, they'll
vote for him,'' he said referring to Dukakis' vagueness.
   Bush added that he will continue to ``spell it (the differences)
out and then get surrogates, those other people who believe as I
do, to spell it out.''
   On Tuesday, Senate Republicans, concerned about recent polls
showing Bush trailing Dukakis by 10 or 12 points, promised the vice
president they would campaign on his behalf.
   ``We're all politicians. We see a poll that shows that kind of
thing, we get excited and say, `Hey, what can we do?''' Sen. Alan
Simpson, Wyo., said after a meeting between Bush and the Senate GOP
in the Capitol.
   ``We're ready to go like a bunch of trout ready to jump out of
the water. We're going to get out our assignments and spread out
across the country,'' said Simpson, deputy Senate Republican leader
and a close friend of Bush's.
   The Bush campaign, which has curtailed sharply the vice
president's travel plans because it is nearing the federal limit on
pre-convention spending, is relying heavily on ``surrogate
speakers,'' including Republican senators.
   On Tuesday, Bush renewed his attack on Dukakis for supporting a
prison furlough system under which the vice president claimed
convicted murderers were released on weekend passes, and he accused
Dukakis of seeking to confuse the issue.
   Asked by reporters about statements by Dukakis that many other
states had such programs, including California while Ronald Reagan
was governor, Bush said: ``It's my understanding that none, except
Massachusetts, had furlough programs for first-degree murderers.''
   ``He can obfuscate it, confuse it all he wants. But the facts
are as I stated them. And I'm very interested in his response,''
Bush said.
   Reacting to Bush's statemement, Dukakis spokesman Leslie Dach
said there are ``a number of other states that grant furloughs for
first-degree murderers'' and that Massachusetts is no longer among
them.
   ``George Bush is using the furlough issue as a smokescreen to
hide the fact that he has no record on crime and drugs,'' Dach said.
   At Tuesday's GOP luncheon, Bush declared to a standing ovation:
``I'm convinced we can carry the day. I am not going to be
out-hustled by Michael Dukakis, I can guarantee you.''
   He was presented a letter signed by all 46 Senate Republicans
expressing their confidence in his victory in November but stating,
``we take nothing for granted.''
   The letter was inside a large white mailbox, with ``G & B Bush,
1600 Pennsylvania Avenue'' emblazoned on it. The `G & B' stands for
George and Barbara and the address is that of the White House.
   The letter from Republicans said, ``We realize it will be a
tough fight on the 1988 campaign trail. But there are some heavy
hitters in this room who wanted to let you know they'll be with you
every step of the way.''
   Speaking with reporters afterward, Bush said, ``I came out of
there feeling 20 feet high.''
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas, who pulled out of
the GOP race in late March and endorsed Bush, told reporters:
``This wasn't just an endorsement, it was a willingness to say
we're available, send us where he wants. We're ready to go.''
   Earlier, Bush met in his office at the Old Executive Office
Building with a presidential task force on drug interdiction and
called for greater emphasis on intelligence resources in the war on
drugs, claiming that the intelligence currently available was ``not
totally satisfactory.''
   Bush also issued a statement Tuesday in which he praised _ and
sought to take credit for _ the vow by the industrial democracies
at the economic summit in Toronto to set up a seven-country task
force on drugs and money-laundering.
   ``This is an idea that I proposed following (Canadian) Prime
Minister (Brian) Mulroney's most recent visit to Washington,'' Bush
said. ``I am pleased these ideas have been implemented.''
</TEXT>
