<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Misconduct     06-22 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Misconduct,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rules on Issue of Misconduct by Prosecutors in Denver Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today ruled that federal
judges may not throw out indictments because of misconduct by
prosecutors unless the defendants can show they would not have been
indicted were it not for such misconduct.
   The 8-1 ruling upheld the reinstatment of an indictment in a
Denver case against the Bank of Nova Scotia and others accused of
setting up and taking part in phony tax shelters.
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, writing for the court, said the
judge who originally dismissed the indictment lacked such authority
``absent a finding that (defendants) were prejudiced by
(prosecutorial) misconduct.''
   Kennedy said the dismissal of an indictment must be based on
evidence that the grand jury would have voted against indictment
were it not for the misconduct. Otherwise, he said, any violations
by prosecutors must be ``deemed harmless.''
   The case stems from a 20-month federal investigation that led to
a 27-count indictment in 1982 against seven individuals and the
Bank of Nova Scotia. The indictment alleged conspiracy, mail fraud
and tax fraud.
   There also was one count of obstruction of justice against
Denver businessman William A. Kilpatrick, accused of being
instrumental in setting up the tax shelters.
   U.S. District Judge John L. Kane Jr. in Denver dismissed 26 of
the counts of the indictment on Feb. 21, 1983, and threw out the
remaining obstruction of justice charge against Kilpatrick after he
was convicted.
   Kane said the indictment was defective for several reasons,
including extensive misconduct by federal prosecutors and Internal
Revenue Service officials.
   For example, Kane said IRS agents made frequent appearances
before the grand jury when they were unsupervised by government
attorneys. The agents also appeared together to read testimony in
violation of grand jury rules.
   Also, the attorneys allowed the IRS to disclose confidential
grand jury material to other IRS agents who were investigating
civil charges in the case.
   There also was evidence that a tax expert who testified for the
defendants was ``browbeaten and ridiculed'' in testifying before
the grand jury, Kane said. The judge also noted that a prosecutor's
heated argument with the tax expert was overheard by other
witnesses waiting to testify.
   And, the judge said, prosecutors impermissibly interrogated
high-level bank employees outside the grand jury without notifying
lawyers for the Nova Scotia bank.
   The 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reinstated the indictment
in 1987.
   The Supreme Court, in upholding that ruling, agreed with the
appeals court that there is a lack of conclusive evidence the grand
jury would have voted against indictment were it not for the
alleged misconduct.
   Justice Thurgood Marshall was the lone dissenter.
   The case is Bank of Nova Scotia vs. U.S., 87-578.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880622-0119 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 1158EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Martinez-Drugs     06-22 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Martinez-Drugs,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governor Plans Drug Task Force, Drug Czar</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT KALLESTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Bob Martinez said today he would
name a ``drug czar'' and create a drug policy task force to wage
war on narcotics in the Sunshine State.
   Martinez, who just returned from a trip to Washington where he
met with Vice President George Bush and Defense Secretary Frank
Carlucci, said the top-level policy adviser would serve as chairman
of the task force.
   ``Florida's drug problem won't get any better unless we develop
tougher and more creative policies and penalties,'' Martinez said.
``We must make the cost of drug trafficking and drug abuse so high
that individuals won't risk getting involved.''
   Martinez said he wanted the new chairman and 15-member task
force to consider such options as using the Florida National Guard,
including its air unit, to help locate illicit drug shipments into
the state. The National Guard is now used in a minor role in
surveillance.
   About 70 percent of the cocaine shipped to the United States is
believed to come through Florida, which has more than 1,350 miles
of coastline.
   He also recommended that a task force look at random drug tests
for most state employees, especially those who work in the state's
schools, in the prisons and on the highways.
   He also said the task force would consider extending the death
penalty statute to major traffickers and drug dealers.
</TEXT>
