<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AbandonedChildren     06-22 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Abandoned Children,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Who Left Five Children At Hospital Charged With Abandonment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 31-year-old mother charged with abandoning her
five children at a hospital emergency room faced similar charges
two years ago.
   Brenda Shed was arrested early Tuesday after being interviewed
by police and caseworkers for the state Department of Children and
Family Services, said Police Youth Division Officer Terry Belinski.
   The five children ranged in age from a 2-year-old girl to
9-year-old twin boys. The three youngest children were placed in
foster homes by Tuesday night, but the 9-year-olds remained in an
emergency shelter, said Dave Schneidman, a family services
spokesman.
   The agency, he said, would seek to win temporary custody of the
children.
   Schneidman said the child-welfare agency cited Ms. Shed for
neglect in 1986 and that her four children were placed in foster
care for seven months.
   The citation, he said, came after the children were found living
alone for four days with only ``minimal food,'' and a neighbor
looking in on them once a day.
   But a Juvenile Court judge ordered the family reunited in
November 1986, Schneidman said.
   ``There was no follow-up investigation since then,'' he said.
   Following her arrest Tuesday, police said Ms. Shed told them she
was ``financially stressed,'' and had been evicted from an
apartment into which she moved three months earlier from public
housing.
   According to Ms. Shed's account, her older sister, Dorothy, 40,
came to the family's apartment as they were being evicted Monday
and said she would drive them to a public-aid shelter.
   Instead, Dorothy Shed drove to Cook County Hospital and while
the children's mother waited in the car, took the youngsters to the
emergency room. There, she left Brenda Shed's name and told a
security guard, ``I'll pick these children up Thursday.''
   Youth Division officers picked up Dorothy Shed late Monday and
charged her with contributing to the dependency of a child, a
misdemeanor, said Belinski.
   The children were examined Monday and found to be healthy. They
also were well-dressed and the three school-aged children had their
schoolbooks with them, said Belinski.
</TEXT>
