<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Simpson-Veep     06-22 0627</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Simpson-Veep,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wyoming's Simpson Not Promoting Himself As Running Mate For Bush</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: One of a series of occasional stories about vice presidential
prospects</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alan Simpson of Wyoming has climbed toward the
peak of the Senate's Republican ranks with a determined lawmaking
style that's spiced with a rangeland wit and outspoken irreverence.
   ``I've punched the lights out of every sacred cow in this
city,'' he says.
   Despite his blunt independence, the 56-year-old attorney from
Cody, Wyo., is being mentioned as a possible running mate for
George Bush. Not surprisingly, he's less than enthusiastic.
   ``I just can't imagine myself in the capacity of a vice
presidential running mate,'' he said, citing the loss of privacy
and freedom he'd have to endure. ``It would be a very difficult
thing for me to do.
   ``I can't get out of a plane in Detroit and have somebody hand
me a speech and tell me what I have to say. I have an aversion to
that _ it's almost physical,'' he said in an interview.
   Simpson has been writing his own speeches since he entered the
Senate a decade ago after serving in his state legislature,
including majority leader of the Wyoming House of Representatives.
   In 1984, after only a single six-year term, he was named by his
GOP colleagues as deputy majority leader. Had Republican leader Bob
Dole's campaign for the party's presidential nomination succeeded,
Simpson would have been hard to beat for the top job.
   His is a distinctive presence on the Senate floor.
Six-foot-seven, stoop shouldered, thin and balding, he stares
menacingly over his half-frame glasses like a vulture and surveys
the Senate floor for prey.
   Then he smiles, and compares passing a tough bill to ``giving
dry birth to a porcupine.''
   Simpson is known as one who fights to win his arguments, not
just go for the easy compromise. He arms himself by studying at
home late into the night.
   He's been critical of some of the most popular programs in
Washington, including veterans benefits for non-combatants,
cost-of-living increases for entitlements and rural electric
cooperatives.
   He has sometimes shown impatience with colleagues _ even GOP
colleagues _ who use the Senate's arcane rules to make things
difficult. But his ability to soothe and work with opponents while
maintaining his priorities has earned him respect from both parties.
   Simpson's credentials as a conservative are unquestioned, but
he's not aligned with the New Right.
   His father, Milward Simpson, was a governor and a senator. His
leap from the statehouse to Washington's most exclusive club, and
his re-election in 1984, were made with ease.
   The marathon and ultimately successful effort to overhaul the
nation's immigration laws has been Simpson's most noted
accomplishment. It was, he said, one of those porcupine bills.
   Simpson teamed up with Rep. Romano Mazzoli, D-Ky., and spent six
years crafting and pushing the immigration bill to final approval.
Along the way, the measure became known simply as
``Simpson-Mazzoli,'' and it was signed into law by President Reagan
in November 1986.
   Along with the successes have come frustrations _ especially
with the inability of Washington to resist special interest
lobbying and attack federal deficits.
   He's not shy about making those feelings known, and his humor
can take an edge when he's on the attack. His jokes are ``my sword
and my shield,'' he says.
   Simpson says his friend George Bush will find many who are
qualified to be his running mate. He says whoever is chosen, he's
confident the Republicans will hold the White House.
   On their fishing trips, Simpson has learned that Bush is ``good
at anything, because he's highly competitive.''
   And, he adds: ``Michael Dukakis is going to find that out.''
</TEXT>
