<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Strike     06-22 0276</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Strike,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brief Strike to Reinstate Fired Bus Drivers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bus drivers in the northwestern city of
Szczecin staged a brief strike Wednesday and won reinstatement of
two fired worker leaders, according to opposition spokesmen and the
state-run news service PAP.
   Spokesmen of the banned Solidarity trade union in Warsaw said
drivers at three bus depots struck from 4:30 a.m. to 8 a.m. The
depots employ nearly 4,000 workers. A brief report by PAP said the
disruption ended at 7 a.m.
   Ryszard Anczykowski, director of the transport company for the
city of 390,000, refused comment.
   The drivers demanded reinstatement of Jozef Ignor, chairman of
the workers' council and co-chairman of the strike committee formed
when the drivers went on strike for one day May 5, and Romuald
Ziolowski, also co-chairman of the strike committee and a workers'
council member, the spokesmen said.
   Ignor and Ziolowski were fired May 18 and Wednesday's strike was
called after the dismissals were upheld by a labor court Monday,
said Henryk Wujec, a Solidarity leader in Warsaw.
   Management signed an agreement at 7:30 a.m. restoring their jobs
and promising no further punishment for the strike, and drivers
went back to work soon afterward, said Solidarity national
spokesman Janusz Onyszkiewicz.
   ``What is interesting is the fact that it wasn't a strike
demanding higher pay, but a typical Solidarity strike,'' said
Onyszkiewicz.
   The stoppage was the second reported among bus drivers since a
wave of strikes between April 25 and May 10 in Poland, the worst
labor unrest since the 1981 imposition of martial law.
   Drivers in Lomza in northeast Poland struck briefly June 15 in a
pay dispute.
</TEXT>
