<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UgandaTrial     06-22 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Uganda Trial,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Ambassador on Trial For Kidnapping</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Uganda's new ambassador to Egypt, a
former aide to dictator Idi Amin, will go on trial on charges of
kidnapping with intent to murder for the disappearance of two
businessmen in 1972.
   Lt. Col. John Onah appeared in Kampala magistrate's court
Tuesday, two days after his appointment was announced.
   Onah, 44, denied charges that he kidnapped businessmen Gregory
Kabera and Matthew Kandore in the western town of Fort Portal on
Sept. 2, 1972, and planned to kill them. He was commanding a
paratroop battalion at the time, when soldiers indiscriminately
arrested civilians they accused of supporting rebels.
   Onah was Amin's minister of tourism and wildlife when the
dictator was overthrown in 1979 and civilian President Milton Obote
was returned to power. Onah fled Uganda, returning after Obote was
ousted in a 1985 coup and replaced by a military junta.
   Five months later, President Yoweri Museveni chased the junta
from power, ending a five-year insurgency. He set up a broad-based
government and a commission to investigate deaths and
disappearances of thousands of Ugandan civilians under previous
governments.
   Like many, Kabera and Kandore have not been seen since they
disappeared.
   Onah was remanded in custody until a trial date is set.
</TEXT>
