<HEAD>At Least 10 Injured in Johannesburg Explosion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An bomb blast destroyed a
video game and pinball arcade in downtown Johannesburg, injuring at
least 10 people, police said.
   The facade of the Winning Games Center was blown out by the
explosion at 2:06 p.m. and a fire flared briefly before it was put
out, they said.
   Police Col. Frans Malherbe said the injured included six blacks,
one white and three people of Indian descent, including the
pregnant woman, her husband and their daughter.
   Malherbe said four of the victims were seriously hurt.
   Witnesses said one woman was knocked off her feet by the blast
and appeared seriously injured. Police said the blast was caused by
an explosive device known as a limpet mine.
   The arcade is located on the ground floor of an apartment
building. Residents were ordered to evacuate as police investigated.
   More than two dozen bombing and hand grenade attacks in South
Africa this year have killed 14 people.
   The government has blamed the attacks on the outlawed African
National Congress, the only guerrilla movement fighting the white
South African government. The ANC has not claimed responsibility
for the various attacks, but has said it plans to intensify its
guerrilla operations.
