<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Manuscript     06-22 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Manuscript,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Autographed Manuscript of O'Casey Play Auctioned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The autographed manuscript of ``The Plough and the
Stars'' by Irish playwright Sean O'Casey was sold on Wednesday for
about $68,000, auctioneers Christie's said.
   The buyer was Bernard Quaritch, leading London book dealers. The
seller was not identified.
   The manuscript on lined paper stapled to make a school exercise
book was of the type that O'Casey used for the two earlier plays in
the trilogy on which his fame rests: ``The Shadow of a Gunman'' and
``Juno and the Paycock.''
   Kate Hedworth, head of Christie's manuscripts department, said
O'Casey used the cheap books for the manuscript because he was very
poor at the time he wrote them.
   ``The Plough and the Stars'' is about the effects on the people
of a Dublin tenement of the violent Easter Rising in the city in
1916 against British rule.
   When staged at Dublin's Abbey Theater in 1926, the play provoked
riots as O'Casey was accused of distorting Irish life.
   On the fourth night, the poet William Butler Yeats jumped on the
stage and told the audience to calm down. He said they had failed
to recognize O'Casey's ``genius'' and they were bringing disgrace
on Ireland.
   But the uproar and the Abbey's rejection in 1928 of his next
play, ``The Silver Tassie,'' led O'Casey to quit Ireland for good.
He made his home in England where he died in 1964 at age 84.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880622-0130 </DOCNO>
