<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--Atlantic-Climate     06-22 0124</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Atlantic-Climate,120</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>Scientists To Study Atlantic-Climate Effects</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists from three nations will spend July
and August cruising the Atlantic Ocean to learn how that body of
water affects climate.
   The research vessel Mt. Mitchell will begin the cruise from
Norfolk, Va., in July, traveling to Bermuda, Iceland, the Azores
and Barbados during the research effort, which ends in September.
   Aboard will be meteorologists from the United States, Canada and
the United Kingdom, according to the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration, which is sponsoring the cruise.
   The aim is to measure the interaction of the ocean and
atmosphere, particularly effects on chemicals which may affect
weather or climate, including carbon dioxide, sulfur and nitrogen
compounds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880622-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 1235EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China     06-22 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deng Says Market-Style Economic Reforms Face Serious Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senior leader Deng Xiaoping confidently assessed
his own economic policies Wednesday while condemning as ``leftist
mistakes'' those followed by Mao Tse-tung for two decades, an
official report said.
   The Xinhua News Agency said Deng acknowledged that his
market-style economic reforms face serious problems, including
inflation and wage inequities that have caused widespread
discontent. He said the problems will take five or six years to
resolve.
   But in a meeting with visiting Ethiopian President Mengistu
Haile Mariam, Deng criticized China's policies from 1957-76 for
``bringing the country to a virtual standstill,'' Xinhua said.
   Deng apparently did not mention Mao by name. Mao died in 1976
after 27 years as the most powerful man in Communist China.
   Criticism of Mao's 1957 drive to form huge communes and the
1966-76 radical leftist Cultural Revolution have become routine
under Deng, twice purged by Mao.
   But Deng's condemnation was unusually sweeping, rejecting the
entire two decades as a time when China's ``productive forces went
undeveloped and people's living standards did not improve.''
   He blamed the era's emphasis on class struggle and policy of
isolating China from the outside world.
   At the start of the meeting with Mengistu in the Great Hall of
the People, Deng reminisced about his political exile under Mao.
   ``You made your first visit to China 12 years ago, that is in
1976,'' he told Mengistu.
   ``At that time I was not in Beijing. I was confined in what we
call a cowshed for the second time,'' he said, using a Chinese term
for places of punishment for those purged during the Cultural
Revolution.
   Deng was branded a ``capitalist roader'' in 1968 and exiled to
rural Jiangxi province. He was reinstated in his posts in 1973, but
was purged again three years later.
   He gradually consolidated power after Mao's death and became top
leader in 1978. He since has made economic development his top
priority and declared that talk of reaching communism is premature
until China becomes prosperous.
   ``Communism consists of two stages,'' Deng told Mengistu, head
of Ethiopia's Marxist government, as he expounded China's current
line that it is only in the first stage of socialism.
   Deng said his current policies ``guarantee that production will
develop at a comparatively good speed,'' Xinhua reported.
   He said price increases, which averaged 11 percent in the first
quarter of the year, and wage inequities pose serious problems.
   ``Our plans call for taking five or six years to overcome these
barriers,'' Xinhua quoted him as saying. ``There are many risks.
But we believe we can overcome them.''
</TEXT>
