<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Palestinians 1stLd-Writethru   06-22 0574</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Palestinians, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0606,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arafat Aide's Peace Proposals Fan Palestinian Feud</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 17th graf, `He said...' to clarify that Arafat is being
quoted; picks up 18th pvs: Abu Shariff...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALEX EFTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Feuding between rival Palestinian
factions has been fanned by a statement from a close aide to PLO
chairman Yasser Arafat that the movement is prepared to live in
peace with Israel.
   The unusually conciliatory statement by Bassam Abu Sharif,
Arafat's chief spokesman, was clearly aimed at pushing the United
States to deal directly with the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   It was branded ``high treason'' by five dissident Syrian-backed
guerrilla groups who broke away from the PLO five years ago in a
dispute with Arafat's policies.
   The statement, initially circulated earlier this month, sparked
a new outburst of heavy fighting between Arafat's Fatah faction and
a radical group, Fatah-Uprising, in the refugee shantytowns on
Beirut's southern outskirts.
   At least 51 people have been killed and 204 wounded since the
fighting flared 13 days ago.
   When Abu Sharif's statement was published Monday on the front
page of the leftist As-Safir newspaper, it led to the collapse of a
four-day truce in the camps battle.
   Abu Sharif labeled his statement a ``policy breakthrough.''
   It said: ``The PLO's raison d'etre is not the undoing of Israel,
but the salvation of the Palestinian people and their rights,
including their right to democratic self-expression and national
self-determination.''
   The PLO, backed by the Arab world, wants an independent homeland
in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, where the
Israelis have been fighting to quell a 6-month-old Palestinian
uprising.
   Abu Sharif added that ``as for the fear that a Palestinian state
would threaten its neighbor, the Palestinians would be open to the
idea of a brief, mutually acceptable transitional period during
which an international mandate would guide the occupied territories
to democratic Palestinian statehood.
   ``Beyond that, the Palestinians would accept, indeed, insist on,
international guarantees for the security of all states in the
region.''
   Abu Sharif also said that ``the means by which the Israelis want
to achieve a lasting peace and security is through direct talks,
with no attempts by any outside party to impose or veto a
settlement. The Palestinians agree.''
   The Arabs have endorsed the PLO's role as the sole
representative of the 5 million Palestinians. But the U.S. and
Israel refuse to deal directly with the Palestinians.
   Abu Sharif proposed an internationally supervised referendum in
the West Bank and Gaza to allow the 1.5 million Palestinians living
there to decide whom they want to represent them, the PLO or ``any
other group of Palestinians that Israel or the United States ...
wishes to nominate.''
   Arafat himself has yet to publicly endorse Abu Sharif's
statement, which was first circulated at the Algiers Arab summit
earlier this month without Abu Sharif's signature.
   Abu Sharif's statement was similar in outline to remarks Arafat
made in Baghdad last January.
   Arafat told The Associated Press that he was prepared to
recognize Israel's right to exist and accept U.N. resolutions
declaring Israel's right to exist behind secure borders if
Washington dropped its objections to PLO attendance at an
international peace conference.
   Abu Sharif reiterated that the PLO would accept Security Council
Resolutions 242 and 338 if Israel accepted General Assembly
resolutions that recognize Palestinian rights.
   The PLO has not unconditionally accepted those resolutions
because they make no reference to Palestinian self-determination.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
