<2ND_LINE>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: could say no.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   June 20
   The Los Angeles Herald Examiner on jail sentences for corporate
crimes:
   As commentators have taken to repeating endlessly, our society
is failing to impart decent values to certain of its citizens.
   Hoodlums shoot innocent bystanders, buy Jaguars with money from
drugs they sell to elementary school kids and terrorize the
law-abiding residents of the neighborhoods they designate as their
home turf.
   But moral decay isn't the sole province of street toughs and
drug merchants.
   Take, for instance, the case of the Beech-Nut crooks. Over
several years, these two guys, top officials of the nation's second
largest baby-food maker, ran a major scam that enriched their
company and themselves.
   Unsuspecting parents who thought they were buying nutritious
apple juice for their babies were getting caramel-colored sugar
water.
   Now (the officials are) being made to pay for it. The judge has
fined them each $100,000 and sentenced them to a year and a day in
jail.
   That's the right message to send.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 19
   The New Mexican, Santa Fe, N.M., on day care:
   Congress can soon be expected to get serious about day care.
   The need for day care has become a national emergency, as
working parents scramble to make do with the best care they can
find at a price they can afford.
   This is not an issue just for mothers or an issue just involving
day care. It involves the way we are acquiescing to a restructuring
of our entire economic and societal life.
   The situation will not right itself until we unravel the
economic knots we have bound ourselves in.
   While we muddle with the immediate issue of day care
legislation, we ought to be taking a long view as well and bearing
in mind that no particular future is inevitable.
   We can march down a seemingly inexorable path, or we can find
new ways to create choice for the next generation of children,
mothers and fathers.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 17
   The Duluth (Minn.) News-Tribune on Jim Wright:
   Let's face it, the House of Representatives doesn't have a great
record in ethics investigaton of its own members.
   Slow to act, quick to forgive, errant House members have been
given slaps on the wrist for misdeeds that might land someone on
the ``outside'' in the pokey.
   That is why the House should not be left alone to investigate
its leader, Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas.
   Wright has been charged with several ethics violations ranging
from lobbying his colleagues when he might have had a conflict of
interest to accepting an unusually high royalty for a book
published under his name, but actually prepared by a
congressionally-paid aide.
   Wright has said he has done nothing wrong.
   If the investigation is left to the House Ethics Committee, its
conclusions will have no credibility if Wright is declared to be
innocent.
   The only answer is to engage an independent counsel to lead the
investigation.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   June 20
   The Milwaukee Journal on riding for muscular dystrophy:
   The leather-clad motorcyclists who descended on Milwaukee over
the weekend may have seemed unlikely fund-raisers, but the truth is
that they contributed upward of $500,000 toward the fight against
muscular dystrophy.
   So successful was the effort that officials of Harley-Davidson
Co., which sponsored the bash as part of its 1988 fund-raising
effort, are talking about increasing their goal from $1 million to
$1.5 million.
   The bikers, some 50,000 strong, flocked to Milwaukee like ants
do a picnic, intent on celebrating the 85th birthday of their
favorite cycle, the Harley-Davidson.
   Admission to the party ... covered the cost of entertainment and
a donation to the Muscular Dystrophy Association.
   That so many motorcyclists would turn out for a charitable cause
bebpeaks tender hearts beneath sometimes tough exteriors.
</TEXT>
