<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--CondemnedAppeal     06-22 0136</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Condemned Appeal,0138</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Sentenced to Gallows Freed After 5 Years' Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men convicted of armed robbery and
held on death row for five years have been released by an appeals
court that ruled they may have been victims of mistaken identity,
it was reported Wednesday.
   Mikunya Manyara and Said Waziri walked from the Nairobi Court of
Appeal free men on Tuesday after a three-judge panel ruled that
witnesses may have misidentified them at their trial, Nairobi
newspapers reported.
   The two were sentenced to death for armed robbery, a capital
crime in Kenya, after holding up and assaulting a family in their
home at Kaaga village of central Kenya in November 1982. A
subsequent High Court appeal by the men failed.
   The Court of Appeal quashed both convictions and sentences.
</TEXT>
