<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Blanton     06-22 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Blanton,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blanton: His Administration Was Cleanest In Nation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DYERSBURG, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Ray Blanton, who served a
two-year prison term in a liquor license conspiracy case, says he
ran the cleanest administration in U.S. history.
   Blanton, who is vying for the 8th Congressional District seat,
on Tuesday compared his government to the Reagan administration.
   ``I think we had the cleanest administration in the history of
this country,'' he told a group of reporters and about 150 people
attending a forum for Democratic candidates in the 8th District
race.
   The former governor is one of five candidates in the Democratic
primary Aug. 4; three candidates are seeking the Republican
nomination.
   Blanton alleged that federal agents entrapped him and said his
refusal to answer negative questions led to bad press.
   ``The present administration in Washington _ the Reagan
administration _ has had 150-odd people indicted or gone to prison
and they don't say a thing in the world about him having a
scandal-ridden administration,'' Blanton said.
   Blanton, 58, whose rights of citizenship were restored last
year, is seeking the seat of U.S. Rep. Ed Jones, a Democrat who is
retiring.
   Blanton served the prison term for his 1981 conviction on
charges of mail fraud, extortion and conspiracy in connection with
the issuance of 12 liquor licenses to friends. The mail fraud
convictions recently were vacated and Blanton is appealing the
other convictions.
</TEXT>
