<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 1250EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-CivilRights     06-22 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Civil Rights,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Makes It Easier to Sue Officials Accused of Violating Civil
Rights Laws</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today made it easier for
people to sue in state court those public officials they accuse of
violating federal civil rights laws.
   The justices, by a 7-2 vote, reinstated a Milwaukee man's $2.3
million lawsuit against 10 city policemen. The suit contends that
the white officers used excessive force and falsely arrested Bobby
Felder because he is black.
   State courts had thrown out Felder's suit because he did not
comply with a state law imposing procedural hurdles against those
who sue state and municipal officials.
   But writing for the high court today, Justice William J. Brennan
said the Wisconsin law cannot be applied when the lawsuit alleges
violation of federal civil rights law.
   The Wisconsin law requires that anyone filing suit in state
court against a state or local government official must notify the
defendant within 120 days of the alleged injury.
   The defendant then has 120 days to reach an out-of-court
settlement. If one is not reached, the lawsuit may be filed within
six months of the defendant's refusal to settle.
   Felder sued in state court, charging violations of a post-Civil
War federal law enacted to protect the rights of blacks. He could
have sued in federal court.
   Felder had not notified the policemen about his complaints
within 120 days of his arrest, and his case was thrown out of state
court for that reason.
   ``We think it plain that Congress never intended that those
injured by governmental wrongdoers could be required, as a
condition of recovery, to submit their claims to the government
responsible for their injuries,'' Brennan said.
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justice Sandra Day
O'Connor dissented.
   Felder became involved in a confrontation with the police on
July 4, 1981, when they stopped him for questioning outside his
Milwaukee home. The police were looking for a man reported to be in
the neighborhood.
   Police said Felder was uncooperative and began to shout
profanities at them. As a crowd of neighbors gathered, police said
Felder shoved an officer.
   Felder was arrested on disorderly conduct charges. He said
police officers beat him with batons and threw him into a police
van while he was semi-conscious.
   The case is Felder vs. Casey, 87-526.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
