<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Biaggi-Wedtech 1stLd-Writethru a0492 06-22 0415</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biaggi-Wedtech, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0492,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecution Winds Up Case in Biaggi-Wedtech Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to UPDATE with defense opening its case
today. Picks up in 3rd graf, `The 70-year-old ...' Also subs 9th
graf, `The other ...,' to change second reference to Simon.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors rested in their racketeering case
against Rep. Mario Biaggi and six others after detailing to the
jury the New York Democratic's indictment and conviction in an
unrelated case.
   The defense began its case in U.S. District Court today by
calling a series of witnesses to refute allegations against former
Bronx Borough President Stanley Simon.
   The 70-year-old Biaggi and his co-defendants are charged with
turning Wedtech Corp., a now-bankrupt Bronx defense contractor,
into a racketeering enterprise that paid out millions of dollars in
payoffs to obtain no-bid government contracts.
   The prosecution concluded by telling the jury about Biaggi's
federal indictment on charges of accepting vacations paid for by
Meade Esposito, the former Brooklyn Democratic chairman, in return
for seeking favorable treatment by the Navy and Coast Guard for a
client of Esposito's insurance firm.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Howard Wilson also told the jury Tuesday
that Biaggi was convicted of accepting an unlawful gratuity but is
appealing the verdict.
   Biaggi was sentenced to 30 months in prison for that conviction
but has remained free on bail pending appeal.
   U.S. District Judge Constance Baker Motley told the jurors they
could only consider Biaggi's prior conviction for determining his
intent regarding extortion and bribery charges in the Wedtech case.
   Prosecutors charge Biaggi demanded and was given 5 percent of
Wedtech's stock, and split that with his former law partner,
Bernard Ehrlich. Because of congressional rules limiting his
outside income, prosecutors contend, Biaggi placed his stock in the
name of his eldest son, Richard, who like Ehrlich is a co-defendant.
   Besides Simon, the other defendants are Wedtech founder John
Mariotta, former Small Business Administration Regional
Administrator Peter Neglia and Neglia's friend, Ronald Betso, a
former police officer.
   Several witnesses, including four former Wedtech executives who
pleaded guilty to corruption charges and testified in exchange for
leniency, linked Biaggi with the Wedtech stock.
   One, former Wedtech chairman Fred Neuberger, also said Simon
sought $50,000 in cash, charitable and campaign contributions from
Wedtech in return for his help in a city real-estate transaction.
   But Neuberger also was forced to admit that he lied to the jury
during the trial about hiding his assets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
