<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Military Moves,100</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Went Chosen as Assistant Commandant of Marines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has selected Lt. Gen. Joseph
J. Went to become assistant commandant of the Marine Corps, the
Pentagon said Wednesday.
   Assuming Senate confirmation, Went, 57, would be promoted to the
four-star rank of general and assume his new duties as the corps'
No. 2 officer later this summer. He would replace Gen. Thomas R.
Morgan, who will retire on July 1.
   Went, a native of New Milford, Conn., now is deputy chief of
staff for installations and logistics. A pilot, Went has served
with Marine reconnaissance, transport, fighter and bomber squadrons.
</TEXT>
