<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Sharpton-Brawley     06-22 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sharpton-Brawley,0239</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Sharpton Witness Detained For Benefit Of Federal Grand Jury</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal authorities are holding as a material
witness a man who claims one of Tawana Brawley's advisers hired him
to tape the adviser's conversations with her lawyers.
   Samuel McClease was released to federal custody after he
appeared before a federal magistrate Tuesday. He was brought into
court on a material-witness warrant after he apparently failed to
show up at U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani's office with the tapes.
   Under federal law, a witness whose testimony is deemed crucial
to a case can be detained by authorities.
   McClease, who was reportedly brought to Giuliani's attention by
a tipster, was subpoenaed Friday to appear on Monday, but failed to
show.
   However, McClease's attorney, John Gross, told the magistrate on
Tuesday his client, ``came in voluntarily with me.''
   McClease has said his tapes showed that the advisers didn't
believe Miss Brawley's story that she was kidnapped and raped by
six white men, one of whom showed a police-type badge, but were
using it for personal and political gain.
   Court papers in the matter were sealed; officials would not
comment about what the federal grand jury was investigating.
   Miss Brawley, 16, and her family have refused to cooperate with
a state grand jury, which has been trying to learn what happened to
the Wappingers Falls girl during a four-day period last November.
</TEXT>
