<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 1313EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Summit Bjt   06-22 0727</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Summit, Bjt,0752</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan Beginning to Exercise Some of Its Economic Clout</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN K. PAULSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita went to the Toronto
summit seeking commitments from his economic partners on five
points. By the time the summit ended, he got nearly everything he
wanted.
   The result pleased leaders here, who called it a sign that Japan
is now exercising some of the clout it has won by building one of
the world's leading economies.
   ``As a whole, it was strongly felt that Japan's international
role has heightened,'' said Keizo Obuchi, chief Cabinet secretary.
   A political cartoon in the nationwide newspaper Asahi Shimbun
summed up Japanese feelings toward the summit, showing the
diminutive Takeshita towering over President Reagan and Canadian
Prime Minister Brian Mulroney, boosted in stature by recent
agreements resolving disputes over beef and oranges and a new aid
package for developing countries.
   To ensure a cordial if not warm reception in Toronto, Japan
announced on the eve of the summit that it was absolving 17 of the
poorest Third World countries of $1 billion in debt in the next
five years. Japan also rushed to conclude an agreement with the
United States on beef and oranges, eliminating a major source of
trade friction.
   Before leaving for the summit, Takeshita indicated Japan no
longer was willing to take a back seat in world affairs.
   ``Seen from the international perspective, it is fit that Japan
has gained the status of an economic power. I believe it is my
responsibility to assert that strength in terms of a specific role
Japan should play,'' he said.
   However, Takeshita also acknowledged he was a man of few words,
often content to sit in the background working for a consensus.
This has upset many Japanese, who think it is time for their
country to be more assertive.
   Thus, many image-conscious Japanese were eager to see what kind
of reception Takeshita would get.
   There was more than a little concern here when Takeshita got
elbowed to the edges during a formal photograph session for the
world leaders. Reporters were quick to note it was the first time
Japan missed an inside spot in the official photo since former
Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone first managed to place himself
between Reagan and British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher at the
1983 Williamsburg summit.
   However, any stature he might have lost in Japanese eyes he
regained at the negotiating table.
   Before leaving for Toronto, Takeshita said he wanted to get
commitments on
   _ coordinating economic policy;
   _ preventing trade protectionism;
   _ cooperation on the international debt problem;
   _ a statement on policies toward the Newly Industrialized
Economies; and
   _ a statement of support for the Seoul Olympics.
   The final summit communique urged continued progress toward
reducing agricultural subsidies, called for special attention to
heavily indebted countries, endorsed the free-market economics
urged by Reagan and Mrs. Thatcher, agreed on rescheduling the debt
of the world's poorest countries, and urged constructive talks with
the Newly Industrialized Economies of Hong Kong, Taiwan, South
Korea and Singapore.
   Japan was praised for spurring domestic demand and urged to
continue promoting land-use reform.
   The communique did not include a statement on the Olympics,
partly over concern about linking politics and sports. However,
Mulroney issued a special statement hours after the summit ended,
saying summit leaders expressed support for the Games. The
statement came after strenuous prodding from Japan.
   It was a symbolic victory for Takeshita, who had promised Asian
leaders he would attend the conference as a regional representative.
   At a news conference following the summit, Takeshita said he was
happy with the declaration on Newly Industrialized Economies, and
said he viewed the summit with a ``sense of fulfillment.''
   Another major success for Takeshita was something that did not
occur at the summit _ the Japan-bashing that has preoccupied
previous sessions.
   Takeshita took special steps to ensure that wouldn't happen this
time.
   In addition to initiatives on beef and oranges and foreign aid,
Japan announced June 14 it was more than doubling its overseas
development aid to at least $50 billion in the next five years.
   Michihiko Kunihiro, chief Cabinet councillor for external
affairs, said Takeshita also won compliments for Japan's recent
success in boosting imports and narrowing its trade surpluses.
   In the end, he said, ``statistics talked on our behalf.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
