<DOCNO> AP880622-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 1321EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w BC-ScotusAt-a-Glance     06-22 0559</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Scotus At-a-Glance,540</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are highlights of actions
taken Wednesday by the Supreme Court.
   
   PENSION BENEFITS
   
   The court, rescuing employers from having to pay potentially
hundreds of millions of dollars in pension benefits, limited the
application of rulings requiring equal treatment of men and women
in the workplace.
   By a 5-4 vote, the court said the state of Florida does not have
to pay $43.6 million to male state workers who retired since 1972.
   The justices limited the retroactive impact of a 1978 high court
ruling that barred employers from requiring women to make higher
contributions to pension plans because on average they live longer
than men and thus receive greater retirement benefits.
   The case is Florida vs. Long, 86-1685.
   
   FOREIGN BANK ACCOUNTS
   
   The court said, in a decision that could carry some impact for
the continuing Iran-Contra affair investigation, that grand jury
targets may be forced to help prosecutors get at their accounts in
foreign banks.
   The court, by an 8-1 vote, ruled that prosecutors may compel the
target of a grand jury investigation to provide written
authorization so foreign banks will disclose records of the
target's accounts there.
   The case is Doe vs. U.S., 86-1753.
   
   CORPORATE RECORDS
   
   The court said a custodian of subpoenaed corporate records may
not withhold them from the government by claiming the act of
providing the documents could incriminate the custodian.
   By a 5-4 vote in a case from Magnolia, Miss., the justices said
the subpoena must be honored even when a corporation is
family-owned and the custodian of the records is the principle
owner of the business.
   The case is Braswell vs. U.S., 87-3.
   
   TEXAS DEATH PENALTY
   
   The court upheld the way Texas courts administer that state's
death penalty law, dashing the hopes of more than 260 death row
inmates.
   The justices, by a 6-3 vote, ruled that convicted murderer and
rapist Donald Gene Franklin properly was sentenced to death for a
1975 crime in San Antonio.
   The case is Franklin vs. Lymaugh, 87-5546.
   
   MURDER CONVICTION
   
   The court upheld, by a 5-4 vote, an Oklahoma man's murder
conviction and death sentence even though the presiding judge
wrongly refused to exclude one juror.
   The justices said Bobby Lynn Ross' conviction for killing an
Oklahoma City policeman was not tainted because his lawyer used a
``peremptory challenge'' to oust the juror.
   The case is Ross vs. Oklahoma, 86-5309.
   
   PROSECUTORS MISCONDUCT
   
   The court ruled that federal judges may not throw out
indictments because of misconduct by prosecutors unless the
defendants can show they would not have been indicted were it not
for such misconduct.
   The 8-1 ruling upheld the reinstatment of an indictment in a
Denver case against the Bank of Nova Scotia and others accused of
setting up and taking part in phony tax shelters.
   The case is Bank of Nova Scotia vs. U.S., 87-578.
   
   CIVIL RIGHTS
   
   The court made it easier for people to sue in state court those
public officials they accuse of violating federal civil rights laws.
   The justices, by a 7-2 vote, reinstated a Milwaukee man's $2.3
million lawsuit against 10 city policemen. The suit contends that
the white officers used excessive force and falsely arrested Bobby
Felder because he is black.
   The case is Felder vs. Casey, 87-526.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880622-0152 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 1322EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Bhopal     06-22 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Bhopal,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minor Acid Leak Reported at Closed Union Carbide Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Minor acid leaks from a storage tank at
the closed Union Carbide Corp. plant at Bhopal were detected on two
days this week, the Press Trust of India reported today.
   The first leak, discovered Monday, was stopped by a team of
experts summoned from New Delhi, the news agency said.
   A second leak, described as ``a small trickle,'' was discovered
Tuesday and fixed immediately, it said.
   The plant has been closed since December 1984, when toxic methyl
isocyanate gas leaked from the pesticide plant run by a Union
Carbide subsidiary.
   The Indian government is suing the U.S. company for $3 billion
to compensate the nearly 3,000 people killed and thousands wounded
in the toxic gas leak.
   India has accused Union Carbide of negligence in causing the
fatal leak. Union Carbide contends the plant was sabotaged.
   PTI said that this week there was ``minor leakage'' of
chlorosulphonic acid from the tank.
   PTI quoted unidentified official sources as saying there was
``no cause whatsoever for alarm, nor was there any danger from this
leak.''
</TEXT>
