<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Minister-Attack     06-22 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Minister-Attack,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Minister's Wife Admitted to Hospital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVAN RAMSTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The wife of a former minister who has been in a
coma since being attacked more than a year ago has been admitted to
a hospital for a two-month period of evaluation and rehabilitation,
hospital officials said today.
   Margaret ``Peggy'' Railey was admitted to Baylor University
Medical Center on Tuesday, said Dr. William L. Parker, medical
director of the Baylor Institute for Rehabilitation.
   ``She was brought here at the family's request because she had
not received an evaluation of her injuries'' since she was admitted
to a nursing home in December, Parker said today.
   ``We cannot predict how her improvement is going to turn out,''
Parker said, adding that a team of 12 physicians and specialists
hope to bring Mrs. Railey, 39, out of her coma.
   She now has normal and waking cycles and her eyes follow
movement some of the time, he said.
   Walker Railey, former senior pastor at the First United
Methodist Church in Dallas, said he found his wife on the garage
floor of their home on the night of April 21, 1987. She appeared to
have been choked, investigators said.
   Not long after the attack, Railey attempted suicide. Later, he
surrendered his ministerial credentials and moved to San Francisco
with a psychologist, Lucy Papillon, who admitted a romantic
relationship with Railey dating back to 1986.
   Mrs. Railey's parents have filed a civil lawsuit that accused
their son-in-law in the attack.
   No charges have been filed in connection with the attack;
authorities have said their investigation is at a standstill.
</TEXT>
