<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Lottery-Convict     06-22 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lottery-Convict,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Convicted Murderer Sues For A Chance To Win Lottery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PONTIAC, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted murderer has filed a federal
lawsuit seeking the right to play the state lottery.
   Jesse Hatch, who is serving a life sentence at the Pontiac
Correctional Center, wrote lottery officials in February requesting
an application to play by mail, but they denied the request,
according to the lawsuit filed Monday.
   Steve Clark, assistant to the director of sales for the Illinois
State Lottery, suggested that Hatch seek permission from the
Department of Corrections, according to the lawsuit. But the
assistant warden at Stateville Correctional Center, where he was in
custody at the time, said no.
   So, Hatch filed the lawsuit in U.S. District Court asking a
judge to order state officials to let him try his luck.
   Hatch, 35, has been in Pontiac since April. He was convicted in
1983 of the murder of a contractor, and his sentence specifies that
he has no chance for parole.
   In the lawsuit, Hatch says the state is denying his
constitutional rights by not allowing him to play the lottery.
