<DOCNO> AP880622-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 1335EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SchoolAdministrators     06-22 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-School Administrators,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Publishes Guide for School Superintendents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A school administrators' group unveiled a
manual Wednesday to help teach superintendents how to get the most
out of their schools.
   The guide, ``Challenges for School Leaders,'' summarizes advice
from national reports on school reform and from such bibles of
modern business techniques as ``In Search of Excellence'' by Thomas
Peters and Robert Waterman.
   The study by the American Association of School Administrators
singled out six key challenges for superintendents and other school
leaders: sharing decision-making; attracting and rewarding good
teachers; curriculum leadership; educating the disadvantaged;
forging partnerships with businesses and other organizations; and
promoting greater parental involvement.
   Richard Miller, president of the association, told a news
conference that strong leadership is essential for effective
schools.
   ``If things are going to happen, it will happen largely because
of the expertise or lack thereof of the leadership that exists on a
site level or on a system-wide level,'' he said.
   He took exception to Education Secretary William J. Bennett's
characterization of public school administrators as a ``blob'' that
grows even when enrollment shrinks.
   Miller said, however, it is vital to provide more leadership
training for school executives because more than half the existing
administrators are expected to retire or leave the profession in
the next seven years.
   Strong superintendents already are moving to give teachers a
larger role in decision-making and to give local schools wider
authority to manage their own affairs, Miller said.
   Bennett has also suggested that schools experiment with hiring
business executives and other leaders from outside the education
establishment to run public schools.
   ``It would be interesting if we could take a Lee Iacocca or Ross
Perot and give them the same resources and the same regulations
that Richard Greene as chancellor of the New York City schools
operates under, to see how effective they could be,'' Miller said.
   The report quotes management expert Peter Drucker as writing
that, ``Effective executives do not make a great many decisions.
They concentrate on the important ones. They try to think through
what is strategic and generic, rather than solve problems.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Copies of ``Challenges for School Leaders'' are available for
$12.95 from AASA Publications, 1801 N. Moore St., Arlington, Va.
22209-9988.
</TEXT>
