<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Hostages, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0530,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report: 15 Hostages Held In Hezbollah Barracks In South Beirut</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with six grafs to UPDATE with State Department comment;
picks up 5th pvs: But the...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syria has located the place in Lebanon where 15
foreign hostages are believed held by Iranian-backed guerrillas,
the Independent newspaper reported today.
   The London daily quoted unidentified Syrian intelligence
officers as saying the hostages are imprisoned inside the Hay Madi
barracks of Hezbollah, or Party of God, in Beirut's southern
suburbs.
   The report could not be independently confirmed.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman said
``that report is not new. We have never been able to confirm the
exact location of the hostages and we cannot confirm this latest
report.
   ``Although information on the hostages is conflicting and rarely
reliable we have always believed that some of them are in Beirut's
southern suburbs. We continue to pursue all leads about the
hostages.''
   The Independent said the Syrian officers are convinced the
hostages and their kidnappers ``are bottled up in an area no more
than 1,000 yards square and that there is no possibility of the
captors moving out.''
   But the Syrians also acknowledged that the hostages cannot be
rescued by force and that negotiations are needed with Hezbollah, a
pro-Iranian Shiite Moslem militant faction, if the hostages ``are
to be extricated alive,'' wrote correspondent John Bulloch.
   The barracks is situated close to the line dividing
Hezbollah-controlled territory from the Chiyah suburb dominated by
the pro-Syrian Amal militia, the newspaper said.
   Amal and Hezbollah guerrillas had been fighting for control of
Lebanon's slums until a cease-fire was called in May.
   The report said the single-story building is guarded by about
250 men, including Iranian Revolutionary Guards, and contains three
sections, including a closed section for ``special guards'' who
give the orders.
   The newspaper quoted unidentified intelligence officers in
Beirut as saying U.S. Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins, 43, who
was kidnapped near Tyre on Feb. 17, was moved to the barracks
before the Syrian army entered south Beirut last month.
   The Syrians entered the slums as part of the cease-fire
agreement between Amal and Hezbollah.
   The Syrians established the hostages' whereabouts from
observation and tip-offs and from Amal fighters captured during
fighting with the Hezbollah who were later released in prisoner
exchanges, the report said.
   Eighteen foreigners, including nine Americans, are missing in
Lebanon. The longest-held hostage is Terry Anderson, chief Middle
East correspondent of The Associated Press, who was kidnapped in
Beirut on March 16, 1985.
   Anderson was also reportedly among the hostages in the barracks.
   The three hostages reportedly missing from the barracks were
Alec Collett, 66, a British citizen, and two other hostages of
unknown nationality.
   Collett, a New York-based journalist, was kidnapped March 25,
1985, while traveling south of Beirut. On April 23, 1986, the
Revolutionary Organization of Socialist Moslems said it killed
Collett in retaliation for British complicity in the April 15 U.S.
air attack on Libya. A videotape purporting to show Collett hanged
was made public.
   The two unidentified hostages were kidnapped on Jan. 26, 1987.
</TEXT>
