<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Egypt-Fire     06-22 0588</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Egypt-Fire,0604</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Kills Dozens of Pilgrims, Many of Them Children</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY31</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASSIUT, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sparks from a makeshift food stall were
blamed Wednesday for a fire that killed 47 Christian pilgrims, most
of them children, who had camped outside a monastery to pay homage
to the Virgin Mary.
   Hundreds of tents lay in smoldering heaps in the wake of the
Tuesday night blaze fed by exploding butane lamps.
   Witnesses said monks quickly closed al-Muharraq Monastery's
massive front door after the fire broke out, and some of the dead
were trampled as panicking pilgrims rushing to the door turned back
toward a gate in the fence around the campground.
   About 5,000 pilgrims were at the monastery for the Feast of the
Consecration of the Church of the Virgin.
   Held every June 21-28, the feast commemorates the farthest south
that the Holy Family reached in its flight to save the infant Jesus
from King Herod's order that newborn boys in Palestine should be
slain. The monastery is built on the cave in Mount Qousqam where
Coptic Christian lore says Joseph, Mary and Jesus were sheltered.
   The church, called the Church of the Cave, has its altar atop a
stone where the Holy Family is said to have rested. The altar is
dated 747.
   Neither the church nor the monastery, a 10-acre compound with 70
to 80 monks in residence, was damaged in the tent-city fire.
   A senior provincial security officer for Assiut, the governorate
capital 240 miles south of Cairo, said 26 children, 15 men and six
women died from burns, smoke inhalation or from being trampled. He
said 15 others were injured trying to escape.
   The blaze began when sparks from the food stall, which provided
pilgrims with tea, coffee and sandwiches, set afire nearby tents,
he said. This in turn ignited about three dozen butane lamps, said
the officer, who spoke on condition he not be identified.
   The officer said the stand's two owners, both Copts, were
arrested, but that the fire clearly was an accident.
   ``There was a big rush from the pilgrims toward the main gate of
the camp. Some children fell and were trampled to death,'' he said.
   A survivor, who appeared dazed, said eight pieces of
firefighting equipment arrived from nearby villages but not until
``a full hour after the fire started.'' He said there was no water
at the tent city to fight the blaze.
   A preliminary police report estimated damage at $420,000.
Several of the burned tents were occupied by merchants catering to
the pilgrims, many of whom were camped for the duration of the
religious festival, or ``moulid.''
   In Egypt, such festivals are common among both Moslems, almost
90 percent of the 54 million Egyptians, and Coptic Christians,
whose ancestors gave to the world the concept of monasticism.
   Unlike most monasteries, whose ascetic founders in the first
years of Christianity usually wandered away into the desert for
solitude, al-Muharraq Monastery is relatively accessible. It is in
al-Qusiyyah, near a well-traveled route and the Nile River about 35
miles north of Assiut.
   Moreover, because of its importance to the Copts as the
southernmost haven for the Holy Family in Egypt, its moulid is
among the most famous in the Coptic Orthodox Church, founded by St.
Mark.
   Al-Muharraq formerly was called the Virgin Mary Monastery. Anba
Sarabion, the Coptic bishop for public services in Cairo, said it
took its current name apparently because of the reddish color of
the rocks in the area. The name means ``The Burnt Monastery.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880622-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 1345EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CovertAction     06-22 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Covert Action,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel OKs Bill to Tighten Controls Over Covert Operations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Foreign Affairs Committee gave
party-line approval Wednesday to a bill designed to tighten
congressional control over foreign covert intelligence action,
after defeating a Republican attempt to ease the restrictions.
   The 22-17 vote sends the bill to the full House, where it is
expected to be passed later this summer. It remains unclear,
however, whether the measure will attract enough support to counter
an almost certain presidential veto.
   The bill, which grew out of the congressional Iran-Contra
hearings last year, would spell out more specifically how a
president must notify the House and Senate intelligence oversight
committees when he authorizes a covert action.
   Such actions are defined as government activities designed to
influence political, economic or military conditions abroad while
concealing the U.S. role.
   Under the proposal, a version of which already has been passed
by the Senate, the president would be required to report any covert
action to the intelligence committees within 48 hours of its
authorization.
   In extremely sensitive cases, the president could limit
notification to a so-called ``gang of eight:'' the chairman and
ranking minority member of the House and Senate intelligence
committees and the majority and minority leaders of each chamber.
   Current law requires only that the president give an undefined
``timely'' notice to Congress, and the Iran-Contra investigators
concluded that President Reagan exploited the loophole to put off
notification on the Iran arms-for-hostages deals for more than 10
months.
   Foreign Affairs Chairman Dante Fascell, D-Fla., a member of the
Iran-Contra investigating panel, called the bill ``a modest but
appropriate adjustment in the current law.''
   The Democratic-dominated panel defeated, 19-13, an amendment by
Rep. William Broomfield, R-Mich., that would have limited
notification in sensitive cases to only the minority and majority
leaders of the two chambers, and would have let the president waive
the 48-hour notification limit in ``rare, extraordinary
circumstances'' where national security was at stake.
   Arguing for the amendment, Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., a member of
the House Intelligence Committee, noted cases in which other
countries had come to the United States for help in a covert action
but asked that Congress not be notified because of a perception
that lawmakers can't keep secrets.
   He cited cases in which an Algerian effort several years ago to
damage the standing of Libya's Moammar Gadhafi was ``blown'' by an
apparent U.S. leak to the news media, and where covert aid to
Philippine President Corazon Aquino to combat communist rebels was
disclosed in a news report.
   But Rep. Lee Hamilton, D-Ind., a former Intelligence Committee
chairman who headed the House Iran-Contra panel, said the
legislation is necessary to ensure that Congress can exert a
balancing effect on administration decision making. He said that
need outweighs the risk of occasional leaks.
   ``If you grant the president power to withhold information, the
whole oversight process is irreparably damaged,'' Hamilton said.
``Information, in this town, is power.''
   The panel also defeated, 13-10, an attempt by Rep. Gerald
Solomon, R-N.Y., to impose criminal penalties on government
officials who leak classified national security information.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880622-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 1402EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     06-22 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUWANEE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The home of the Atlanta Falcons wants
motorists to get a kick out of their town and leave some of their
tourist dollars behind.
   City officials plan to erect ``the world's largest football'' to
lure tourists off Interstate 85 and into their town, 30 miles
northeast of Atlanta.
   The Big Football, to be a fascimile of an official NFL football,
will be 200 feet high and 60 feet wide.
   ``We are very fortunate to have the Falcons here,'' said
Councilman Jim Theus, who pitched the idea at Tuesday's council
meeting. ``Whether they win or whether they lose, they are a
professional football team. How many places can boast that? Tourism
is going to be the big thing here.''
   Theus owns Porkland Express, a popular barbecue restaurant at
the Suwanee exit on I-85. Across the street from Porkland is the
Falcons complex, including team offices and the training camp,
where players work out nearly year-around.
   Local merchants favor the idea and are willing to help pay for
the football, which may cost as much as $100,000, he said. However,
Theus also hopes the city's tourism tax will help cover expenses.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Companies contemplating a 1990s version of ``The
Name Game'' might be well advised to stick with the old and
familiar.
   An ill-conceived name chance can hurt a company, says Landor
Associates, a San Francisco-based consulting firm.
   Landor recently asked 1,000 consumers in shopping malls in 12
cities to rate 672 different names in terms of familiarity and
esteem.
   Sara Lee ranked in the top 15 percent in the latest survey. That
was a marked improvement from the days when it was known as
Consolidated Foods and ranked in the bottom 10 percent of the
Landor sample.
   Allegheny Airlines once ranked in the bottom 20 percent in the
Landor survey, but placed in the top 40 percent after changing its
name to USAir.
   ``In the '90s, major corporations will rediscover the raw image
power of their established names and may find it much more
efficient to modify or add meaning to them rather than start from
scratch,'' said Landor President John Diefenbach.
   The survey said consumers scoff at some of the high-tech names _
such as USX, Primerica and Unisys.
   The old names of those corporations _ U.S. Steel, American Can
and the premerger Burroughs and Sperry _ each had placed higher in
previous surveys.
   ``The message is very simple,'' Diefenbach said. ``Meaningless
names and symbols can confuse and alienate the consumer.''
</TEXT>
