<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HospitalSurvey     06-22 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hospital Survey,0188</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hospitals Fear Financial Failure, Questionnaire Finds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forty-eight percent of hospital executives who
answered a mailed questionnaire said they thought their hospitals
could fail financially within five years.
   Hospital occupancy rates were reported to be low. Executives at
46 percent of the hospitals said their hospitals were less than
half full during the year preceding the survey, which was released
Wednesday.
   Three-fourths of the respondents said their hospitals faced a
nursing shortage and that the quality of patient care was declining
as a result.
   The survey was conducted by Touche Ross, a New York accounting
firm. Questionnaires were sent to the top hospital executive in
each of the nation's 5,678 hospitals, Touche Ross said. The
questionnaires were returned by 1,419, or 25 percent, of the
executives, the firm said.
   Seventy-six percent of the hospital executives said that in five
years patients will have less freedom in their choice of doctors
and medical services. And three-fourths of the executives said they
think health care should be limited when the cost of that care
becomes excessive, according to the survey.
</TEXT>
