<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PHS-AIDS     06-22 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PHS-AIDS,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Public Health Service Issues Journal on AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Public Health Service has issued a special
AIDS edition of its bimonthly journal, featuring articles by top
federal and state health officials as well as private leaders in
the fight against the epidemic.
   The 19 articles in the 127-page publication do not make
significant revelations but provide an overview of what various
government agencies and private organizations are doing to halt the
deadly disease and the challenges perceived by each of them.
   For example, the volume includes an article by Dr. Frank Young,
commissioner of the Food and Drug Administration, on the FDA's
role, and one by Dr. William L. Roper, head of the Health Care
Financing Administration, on ``making fair decisions about
financing care for persons with AIDS.''
   The May-June issue of ``Public Health Reports'' also includes
pieces by the head of the American Medical Association, officials
of the National Academy of Sciences' Institute of Medicine, the
president of the American Association of Colleges of Nursing, and
Paul Akio Kawata, executive director of the National AIDS Network,
an umbrella organization of more than 400 community-based AIDS
service organizations.
   Dr. Robert E. Windom, the assistant secretary for health in the
Department of Health and Human Services, commissioned the special
volume and distributed 2,000 copies at the recent international
AIDS conference in Sweden.
   It is available for purchase from the Superintendent of
Documents, U.S. Government Printing Office, Washington, D.C. 20402.
The cost per copy is $4.75.
</TEXT>
