<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-ChinaMissiles     06-22 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-China Missiles,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Would Be Concerned About Chinese Missile Sales to Syria</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Wednesday that
Chinese sales of short-range missiles to Syria would raise ``deep
concern'' and add to the proliferation of dangerous ballistic
weapons in the volatile Middle East.
   Syria is rumored to be talking to China about buying
surface-to-surface M-9 ballistic missiles the Chinese are testing,
according to Israeli leaders, including Foreign Minister Shimon
Peres.
   While the Soviet SS-21 missiles now in Syrian hands would have
to be deployed in vulnerable sites on the Golan Heights to hit
Israeli population centers, a Chinese M-9 could wreak the same
havoc from protected sites near Damascus, according to the Israeli
officials.
   Israeli Chief of Staff Lt. Gen. Dan Shomron has expressed
particular concern that the missiles could be fitted with
chemical-agent warheads.
   State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman echoed the Israeli
view that there is no evidence a Syrian-Chinese deal is imminent.
He did, however, repeat U.S. dismay at ``the global proliferation
of ballistic missiles.''
   ``Especially disturbing are sales to such regional hot spots as
the Middle East. We have raised these concerns with China and other
countries,'' he said.
   ``The Chinese have exhibited their ``M'' family of
surface-to-surface short-range ballistic missiles at arms shows. We
would view the sale of such missiles to Syria with deep concern, as
we would proliferation of other ballistic missile systems,'' Redman
said.
   He noted that the U.S. concern about missile proliferation in
the Middle East was raised with the Soviets during President
Reagan's summit trip to Moscow.
   The United States also has complained to China about sales of
long-range ballistic missiles to Saudi Arabia.
</TEXT>
