<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 1432EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vietnam     06-22 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vietnam Choses Reported Corruption Fighter As Prime Minister</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Do Muoi, a veteran revolutionary who
reportedly directed purges against corruption in Vietnam's ruling
Communist Party, was chosen prime minister Wednesday, Radio Hanoi
said.
   Do Muoi was elected on the opening day of a regular National
Assembly session, the broadcast monitored in Bangkok said. He
replaces Pham Hung, who died of a heart attack in March.
   Do Muoi, 71, is the third-ranking member of the Politburo, the
nation's top policy-making body.
   A party communique, meanwhile, said the party has decided to
regularly change its leadership to promote efficiency and economic
reforms.
   The communique of the Central Committee's recent session said
that when the party elects members to its upper echelons one-third
of the membership should be changed.
   The Central Committee is the policy-implementing arm of the
13-member Politburo. It had 124 full members and 49 alternate
members when it was elected in December 1986.
   At the National Assembly session, Vo Van Kiet, who had been
acting premier, noted among other serious economic problems an
acute food shortage in the northern provinces since early this
year. Vietnam has appealed for foreign emergency aid to offset the
shortages caused by crop failures last year.
   Kiet said that because production stagnated as the population
grew, the amount of food available per capita in those provinces
dropped from 581 pounds in 1982 to 506 pounds in 1987.
   He called for continuation of economic reforms based on
decentralized management and material incentives, according to the
official Vietnam News Agency.
   Do Muoi gave up the vice premiership last year after becoming
the No. 2 man in the party secretariat, where he is said to have
directed a purge of inept and corrupt elements in the 1.8
million-member party.
   Do Muoi, who is little known to most Vietnamese, joined the
Indochinese Communist Party in 1939 and held key party and
government posts during the struggle against the French
colonialists and then the Americans and South Vietnamese.
   In several top economy-related government posts after the 1975
communist victory, Do Muoi helped forge the strict Marxist policies
which the party now says led to Vietnam's ruin.
   Southerners are said to resent him for having led a disastrous
effort in 1978 at ``socialist transformation'' of the private
business and commerce in the traditionally capitalist south.
   Vietnamese sources had said Do Muoi was the most likely choice
as premier because of his reputation as a party organizer and
disciplinarian.
   Some Western diplomats have said the choice of Do Muoi would
send a wrong signal to the average Vietnamese, who preferred acting
premier Vo Van Kiet, 66, a leading pioneer of economic reform. The
selection of Do Muoi could slow down the reform momentum, the
Hanoi-based diplomats said.
   The pragmatic party chief, Nguyen Van Linh, called for the
continuation of purges begun since he took power in December 1986,
according to a partial text of his speech obtained from a Western
embassy in Bangkok on Wednesday.
   Since the party was founded in 1930, its leaders have largely
been veterans of the revolutionary struggle against the French,
Americans, and South Vietnam. Lately, the party has given top
priority to economic reform and said that incompetent,
conservative-thinking members can no longer remain in top posts.
</TEXT>
