<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BusCrash-Forgiveness     06-22 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bus Crash-Forgiveness,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Youngster Forgives Driver Involved In Fatal Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ELIZABETHTOWN, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 13-year-old girl who survived a
fiery bus-truck accident that killed 27 people has sent a message
of forgiveness to the driver charged with murder in the case.
   Katrina Muller recorded her thoughts on tape and said afterward
that she didn't know if Larry Mahoney ``should be put to death or
not, but he should be punished.''
   Mahoney, 34, allegedly was drunk and driving the wrong way on
Interstate 71 near Carrollton last month when his pickup truck
collided with the bus loaded with youngsters returning from a
Cincinnati amusement park to a church in Radcliff.
   Two days later, Mahoney was booked on 27 counts of murder and a
commonwealth's attorney said he would seek the death penalty.
   Katrina made the tape and sent it June 3 while still
hospitalized in Louisville and undergoing three skin graft
operations. Her face, right arm and both hands were burned badly in
the fire that followed the May 14 collision.
   She was released from the hospital Saturday.
   ``The tape is now at the Kentucky Correctional Psychiatric
Center where Larry is being evaluated,'' said one of his attorneys,
Russell Baldani of Lexington.
   Baldani said he checked Wednesday with Mahoney ``and he hasn't
heard the cassette but he knows about it from his family. I'm going
to talk with the center's director tomorrow at LaGrange to see if
he will release it to us.''
   The teen-ager's mother, Mickie Muller, said the idea for the
tape came during one of those days when Katrina was ``having a lot
of pain. This was in the midst of some of the worst time she was
having.''
   She recalled her daughter saying, ``I wish Larry Mahoney was
right here in front of me. I would tell him I forgive him and maybe
it'd make him feel better.''
   Mrs. Muller said that on the tape, Katrina ``introduced herself
and told him some things about herself, just to make herself not
just a statistic but a real person.''
   Aware of reports that Mahoney had become a born-again Christian,
Mrs. Muller said Katrina hoped that the rumor was true.
   ``Just keep on doing right,'' Katrina said to Mahoney. ``And
then when it's your time to go, then you'll be with the children
who've go on before.'' Most of the victims were teen-agers.
   Katrina also sent along a photograph taken of herself before the
crash.
   Mrs. Muller said ``I can't honestly say I'm not still angry with
Larry Mahoney _ not as a person but as a drunk driver. But that's
all right too. The Bible says to `be angry and sin not.'''
   Despite her anger, she said she still could forgive.
</TEXT>
