<1ST_LINE>u a PM-LakersMania 2ndLd-Writethru a0667 06-22 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lakers Mania, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0667,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lakers Fans Fill Downtown With Purple</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs with parade under way, crowd estimate.
PICKS UP 5th graf pvs, `The 108-105 ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE V. BIGELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ecstatic Lakers fans, relishing the
back-to-back basketball title promised a year ago by Coach Pat
Riley, filled downtown in a sea of purple today to bask in the
presence of their heroes.
   ``Ain't it great?'' asked a beaming Tyrone May, 22.
   Thousands of people stood along a mile-long section of Broadway
and cheered the champions, who wore Lakers T-shirts and ballcaps
and waved to fans from floats headed to a noon City Hall ceremony.
   An estimated 15,000 lined the parade route and 4,000 had
converged on City Hall, said police spokesman Don Lawrence.
   The single-word headline ``CHAMPS!'' in Lakers purple splashed
across the top of the Los Angeles Herald Examiner in 2{-inch type,
and the parade route was clogged with vendors hawking T-shirts,
buttons and posters as fans grabbed prime spots to view the floats.
   The 108-105 victory Tuesday night over the Detroit Pistons made
the Lakers the first team since the Boston Celtics of 1969 to
repeat as consecutive NBA champions.
   ``It's party time,'' said Gus Corona, 29. ``This is great, it's
the first time in 19 years. This has got to be the greatest.''
   Corona stood on a milk crate to tape the parade with his video
camera.
   At City Hall, voice-of-the-Lakers Chick Hearn and Mayor Tom
Bradley were to preside at the noontime rally to introduce the
players.
   It was during similar ceremonies last year that Riley
``guaranteed'' that the Lakers would repeat as champions in 1988.
   The parade culminated two days of Laker fever that began
building early Tuesday. T-shirts, confetti, glitz, glamour,
parties, celebrities, music and Magic (as in Lakers' superstar
guard Earvin ``Magic'' Johnson) were on the minds of most fans.
   During the game, traffic was strangely light on Southern
California's usually busy freeways. Sounds of the play-by-play
could be heard drifting out of apartments throughout the city.
   ``Go Lakers Go. Beat Detroit,'' read the shopping center marquee
in Malibu, the celebrity enclave that many fans call home.
   Tickets were at a premium three hours before game time: A $1,100
price tag was set on the last pair of tickets remaining at Tyson
Choice Ticket Service.
   ``It's been nuts all day,'' said Mike Gubner at the Sports
Section, a souvenir store six blocks from the Forum in Inglewood,
the Lakers' home court. Selling at a brisk pace were $10 T-shirts
reading: ``We're shootin' for two, back to back.''
   At the Sports Deli in Century City, assistant manager Marvin
Smith described the post-game scene as ``bedlam.''
   Smith, a Pistons fan, said he played ``Respect'' by Aretha
Franklin over the bar's stereo system ``because we beat the Celtics
and we took the Lakers all the way to seven games.''
</TEXT>
