<1ST_LINE>r p AM-ConventionCriticism     06-22 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Convention Criticism,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Atlanta Mayor Says City Close To Ready For Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young on Wednesday blasted
criticism of the city's preparations for the Democratic National
Convention, saying reports that the host city will not be ready in
time are exaggerated.
   ``I don't care what people say about Atlanta. Anybody who
doesn't like Atlanta can go somewhere else,'' Young said. ``This is
a building and growing city and it will be for some years to come,
but whatever we need for the convention is going to be ready by the
time the convention gets here.''
   Young was responding to recent news articles that reported bad
judgment calls by convention planners working on space for
convention sessions and hotel accomodations. The articles also said
some major transportation routes are still under construction and
convention planners have been fighting among themselves.
   ``I don't know what (they're) talking about in terms of
confusion and chaos,'' Young said. ``Peace and quiet and
tranquility and everybody getting along is not news, and that's
what we got.''
   Young said he is in frequent contact with convention planners
and party officials. He estimated that the city is about ``85 to 90
percent ready'' for the convention, a condition with which he is
``very comfortable.''
   ``The things we intended to get ready by the convention will be
ready,'' Young said. ``We had a convention bigger than this a month
ago, so we can take care of the convention as we are.''
   Young said state officials never expected to complete expansion
on Interstates 75 and 85, which pass through downtown Atlanta,
before the convention begins July 18.
   Georgia Gov. Joe Frank Harris also defended the city's readiness
for the convention at his weekly news conference Wednesday, saying
``we handle almost on a weekly basis conventions that large and
even larger.''
   ``I saw the same kind of stories from the California convention
before we went there (San Francisco in 1984) ... and it all worked
well. And I think Atlanta and Georgia are going to do the same
thing,'' he said.
   Harris, noting the convention's importance to Atlanta's image,
announced a stepped-up litter collection program using non-violent
criminal offenders sentenced to community service as part of their
probation.
   Officials said such offenders, most of whom were convicted of
drunken driving, already have collected 70 tons of trash in
downtown Atlanta in sweeps over the last three months.
</TEXT>
