<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 1458EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Burma     06-22 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Arrest 77 in Street Battles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities arrested 77 people following
street battles between protesters and riot police in Rangoon that
claimed the lives of nine people, the state radio announced
Wednesday.
   Calm returned to the streets of the capital as authorities
enforced a 6 p.m. to 6 a.m. curfew and banned public gatherings.
The restrictions were ordered late Tuesday, hours after 5,000
students and other protesters fought stone-throwing duels with
police.
   The restrictions are to last until Aug. 19.
   Students at several institutions had peacefully demonstrated the
past week for release of detained students, reinstatement of those
expelled after previous protests, and legalization of student
unions. Violence erupted after the government responded by closing
the schools.
   The radio said 10 students and three women were among the 77
people arrested. It said six policemen and three demonstrators were
killed.
   The government earlier said five policemen were killed and 26
others seriously injured. One rioter was killed and several others
were injured, it had said.
   The radio also announced the closure of Medical College Two.
Closure of the Rangoon Institute of Technology was announced
earlier in the day, and classes were suspended at the Institute of
Medicine and the Institute of Dental Science. The Education
Institute was the only institution of higher education still open
in the capital.
   There was no apparent extra security on the streets, which were
calm but with less traffic than usual. Few people went to offices
or schools, and markets had few customers. Local officials went
into residential areas warning people not to gather in groups of
five or more.
   Burma is ruled by the one-party regime of military strongman Ne
Win, who seized power in a 1962 military coup. Ne Win's ``Burmese
way to socialism'' is an amalgam of socialist economics, strict
military control and isolationism.
   For decades, the government has been fighting a dozen
ethnic-based insurgencies in the country, one of Southeast Asia's
poorest, and has dealt with other domestic opposition swiftly and
decisively.
   The country's first riots since 1974 erupted last October when
the government declared invalid much of the currency in
circulation, making life difficult for many people. On March 18,
several days of student unrest at two universities climaxed in a
rampage by students and other protesters that was swiftly crushed
by police and military units.
   Diplomatic sources told reporters in Bangkok, Thailand, that as
many as 100 people may have died in the March 18 violence. A
government panel announced only two deaths and said 625 people were
arrested, many of them since freed.
   Witnesses said Tuesday's fighting began as some 1,000 students
of the Rangoon Arts and Science University, which was closed after
Monday's classes, marched from the campus towards downtown Rangoon.
High school students joined them.
   They said 200 police swung batons and hurled stones to stop them
near the Singaporean embassy, in the Myenigone area about two miles
south of the campus.
   The demonstrators, by then about 5,000 strong, hurled stones and
forced the police to retreat a block south, where a strong military
barricade stood. The protesters then dispersed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
