<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon     06-22 0685</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0716</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Car Bomb Explodes in Beirut, Killing One and Injuring 18</HEAD>
<HEAD>By MOHAMMED SALAM</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car bomb in Christian east Beirut
killed one person and wounded 18 on Wednesday, while Palestinian
militias battled in the city's refugee camps in a power struggle
that has claimed more than 50 lives.
   A police spokesman said a green sedan loaded with 44 pounds of
explosives detonated at 11 a.m. in a narrow alley in the Karantina
district.
   The blast set six shops on fire and damaged eight cars parked
nearby, according to the spokesman, who asked not to be identified.
   Wednesday's explosion raised the death toll from six car
bombings in Lebanon this year to 94 people killed and 251 wounded.
   The Lebanese Forces, the main right-wing Christian militia that
controls east Beirut, said explosives experts defused another car
bomb in Karantina minutes before it was to explode. The Lebanese
Forces said in a statement that the car contained a 22-pound time
bomb.
   The second car bomb was meant to explode shortly after the first
one ``to inflict as many casualties as possible among rescuers,''
the statement said.
   Police could not confirm there was a second car bomb.
   The Lebanese Forces blamed the recent bombings in east Beirut on
a rival militia force led by Elie Hobeika, a Syrian-backed
Christian leader.
   The leader of the Lebanese Forces, Samir Geagea, ousted Hobeika
as the militia's commander in a bloody rebellion in January 1986,
after Hobeika signed a Syrian-brokered peace treaty with rival
Moslem warlords in Lebanon.
   Hobeika then set up a base in the Syrian-controlled Bekaa Valley.
   Also in Moslem south Beirut on Wednesday, police spokesman said
five people were killed and 18 wounded in clashes between Yasser
Arafat's Fatah guerrilla faction and Col. Saeed Mousa's
Syrian-backed Fatah-Uprising.
   Mousa broke away from Arafat's Palestine Liberation Organization
in 1983 and set up headquarters in Damascus, the Syrian capital.
   The casualties raised the death toll to 51 people killed and 206
since the latest round of fighting between the two Palestinian
militias erupted 13 days ago.
   The factions are fighting for control of the devastated Chatilla
and Bourj el-Barajneh camps. Both sides are using howitzers,
rockets and mortars to pound each other's positions in the camps,
already badly battered from years of violence.
   A Fatah spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, accused
unidentified ``other sides'' of supporting Mousa's fighters with
artillery fire from positions in Syrian-policed west Beirut.
   Arafat's guerrillas dislodged Mousa's followers from the two
camps on Beirut's southern outskirts in earlier battles. But the
dissidents regrouped in Syrian-controlled territory along the edges
of the shantytowns.
   Libyan mediators and other Palestinian factions have failed to
secure a cease-fire to end the fighting.
   Arafat's loyalists and Mousa's dissidents have been fighting for
supremacy in the camps despite a reconciliation between the PLO
chief and Syrian President Hafez Assad in Damascus in April.
   Their efforts were aimed at ending the often bloody 5-year-old
feud over who would control the Palestinian movement.
   The battles between rival Palestinian factions have been fanned
by Arafat's chief spokesman, who has said that the PLO is prepared
to live in peace with Israel.
   The unusually conciliatory statement by Bassam Abu Sharif,
initially circulated earlier this month and repeated again Monday
on the front page of Beirut's leftist As-Safir newspaper, led to
the collapse of a four-day truce in the camps battle.
   The statement, which Sharif labeled a ``policy breakthrough,''
said:
   ``The means by which the Israelis want to achieve a lasting
peace and security is through direct talks, with no attempts by any
outside party to impose or veto a settlement. The Palestinians
agree.''
   ``The Palestinians would accept, indeed, insist on,
international guarantees for the security of all states in the
region.''
   The PLO, backed by the Arab world, wants an independent homeland
in the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, where the
Israelis have been fighting to quell a 6{-month-old Palestinian
uprising.
   Arafat himself has yet to publicly endorse Sharif's statement,
which was first circulated at the Algiers Arab summit earlier this
month, without Abu Sharif's signature.
</TEXT>
