<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Earthquake     06-22 0177</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Earthquake,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quake Jolts Armenia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An earthquake capable of cracking plaster and
knocking pictures off walls rumbled through the southern republic
of Armenia on Wednesday, the Tass news agency reported.
   The quake damaged old buildings in the Gukasyan district, about
68 miles northeast of the Armenian capital of Yerevan, according to
Tass. No injuries were reported.
   The quake struck the ancient land east of Turkey and south of
the Soviet republic of Georgia at 5:18 a.m. (9:18 p.m. EDT
Tuesday), with a magnitude of six on the 12-point Soviet scale at
the epicenter.
   A quake registering six is strong, felt by all people in the
area, knocking pictures from the walls and cracking plaster. Light
damage to buildings is possible.
   The Soviet scale measures the effects of an earthquake rather
than its intensity. It cannot be converted to the Richter scale
more widely known in the West.
   Armenia has been in the news since February because of a
campaign by ethnic Armenians to annex Nagorno-Karabakh, a region in
the neighboring republic of Azerbaijan.
</TEXT>
