<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 1834EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ContraTroubles     06-22 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contra Troubles,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dissidents Challenge Strapped Contra Leadership</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dissidents within the Nicaraguan Contras assembled
Wednesday to demand drastic leadership changes as the U.S.-backed
rebel group prepares for massive layoffs and cutbacks.
   Contra Director Pedro Joaquin Chamorro backed the dissident
former military commanders at an unprecedented Miami headquarters
news conference, apparently widening the split in the movement
against the Sandinista government of Nicaragua.
   The six commanders and their supporters, many of whom were fired
by rebel military chief Col. Enrique Bermudez, stopped short of a
full break with the Contra umbrella organization, the Nicaraguan
Resistance. Instead, they announced the formation of a new
``current'' within the group.
   Chamorro denied the open split hurts the image of the
financially strapped Contras just as the Reagan administration goes
back to Congress to ask for more aid. In March, Congress adopted a
limited $47.9 million budget limited to humanitarian aid.
   ``What hurts the image of unity is to marginalize people who
have so much support inside the movement,'' said Chamorro. ``It
hurts the image to throw them out in the street like dogs.''
   Chamorro confirmed that massive administrative layoffs are being
planned, but refused to give details, saying only that as many as
400 people in rebel political offices in Miami, Washington, Latin
America and Europe might be affected.
   Contra spokeswoman Marta Sacasa said the cuts would not affect
troops in the field or financial support for their families, and
were part of a wholesale ``restructuring'' of the rebel
organization.
   Chamorro said the dissident's formation of a group was no
different from the shifting alliances within the directorate
itself, which has been bitterly divided since peace talks began
with the Sandinista government, he said.
   The dissidents Wednesday demanded total restructuring and
renovation of the movement, accusing the directors of serving U.S.
interests instead of those of Nicaragua.
   ``We want the Resistance be open to everyone, and not subject
the interests of the Nicaraguan people to foreign pressure,'' said
Diogeenese Hernandez, known as Commander Fernando.
   Hernandez said new faces in the six-member directorate ``would
be healthy,'' but did not specify any names.
   He once again called for the removal of Bermudez, as he and the
other commanders did when they were expelled from the military. But
the dissidents offered a conciliatory solution to Bermudez's
departure, suggesting he be elected to the empty seat in the
directorate, which would force him to resign as commander of the
rebel forces.
   The commanders strongly backed the peace talks with the
Sandinistas, although they accused the Nicaraguan government of
failing to fulfill its commitments under the cease-fire agreements.
Chamorro said no date has been set for the next round of talks.
</TEXT>
