<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Ambassador     06-22 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Ambassador,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Names INF Negotiator To Ambassadorial Post</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan intends to nominate Maynard
Glitman, one of the administration's negotiators on the
Intermediate-Range Nuclear Forces treaty, to be ambassador to
Belgium, the White House announced Wednesday.
   If confirmed by the Senate, Glitman will succeed Geoffrey
Swaebe..
   Glitman, a 54-year-old Chicago native, was named in 1981 as the
State Department representative and deputy negotiator to the INF
negotiations, with the rank of ambassador. He served in this
capacity until 1984, when Glitman was named chief U.S.
representative to the Vienna talks on East-West conventional forces.
   Since 1985, Glitman had been the chief U.S. negotiator on the
INF issue in Geneva.
   Glitman, a 1955 University of Illinois graduate, entered the
Foreign Service in 1956 after graduating from the Fletcher School
of Law and Diplomacy.
   He was an economics officer in the State Department and then a
fiscal and financial officer. He also was a consular officer in
Nassau from 1956-61, and also in Ottawa, Canada, from 1961-65.
   From 1967-68, he was an international relations officer in the
State Department, and then did tours at the U.N. General Assembly
and at the National Security Council.
   Glitman also served as a political officer in Paris, and then
returned to the State Department to be director of the Office of
International Trade Policy.
   From 1977-81, he was deputy chief of mission at the U.S. Mission
to NATO in Brussels, Belgium.
</TEXT>
