<DOCNO> AP880622-0188 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 1600EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Baker Bjt   06-22 0868</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baker, Bjt,0891</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baker Says U.S. Still Wants Farm Subsidies Scrapped By Year 2000</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: All dollar figures are in U.S. dollars.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan still wants global farm
subsidies eliminated by the year 2000, despite the economic
summit's more moderate call for only a reduction in the handouts,
Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III said Wednesday.
   ``The president's position remains the same and will be advanced
in Montreal in December,'' Baker told reporters after addressing a
Canadian Importers' Association luncheon.
   The $200 billion subsidy war, in which support for farmers has
caused surplus production and slumping prices, caused the most
heated debate of the seven-nation summit that ended Tuesday.
   The United States proposed the phaseout of all subsidies by the
end of the century, while most European countries and Japan said
that was unrealistic and Canada looked for compromise language.
   ``Everyone agreed the summit was not the place to reach the
final agreement,'' Baker said, noting that the real deadline for
action is the December midterm review in Montreal of the current
Uruguay Round of talks within the 96-nation General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade. The GATT system sets rules for international
trade.
   ``What we wanted to do was direct our negotiators at the midterm
review to develop a framework that includes both long-term and
short-term (measures),'' Baker said.
   Canadian Prime Minister Brian Mulroney said at a summit-ending
news conference Tuesday that the farm subsidy clause in the
declaration was ``not perfect'' but sent a strong signal to GATT
negotiations for reform of a system that is draining treasuries and
dislocating economies.
   In his speech, Baker termed the Toronto summit the best of the
eight he has attended as chief of staff and then treasury boss for
Reagan. But he added that the multilateral trading system remains
threatened by new forms of protectionism and the belief by some
countries that exports are good but imports are bad.
   He said the United States might explore a ``market
liberalization club'' approach to trade, if the current
renegotiation of GATT rules does not reduce tariff and non-tariff
barriers around the world.
   He pointed to the U.S.-Canada Free Trade Agreement, facing
ratification hurdles in both countries but due to take effect Jan.
1, as an important catalyst for this ``new trade policy strategy.''
   In Ottawa, meanwhile, British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
gave a ringing endorsement to the Free Trade Agreement during an
address to a joint session of the Canadian Parliament.
   She termed it courageous and dismissed Canadian opposition party
claims that the deal might result in Canada losing its identity.
   ``On the basis of Britain's experience of joining the European
Community, you need have no fear that Canada's national personality
will be in any way diminished,'' Mrs. Thatcher said. ``Fifteen
years of European Community membership have left our people no less
British.''
   Later, in an angry exchange, opposition party leaders blasted
the Mulroney government for allowing Mrs. Thatcher to make such
partisan comments. They said it was like a Canadian prime minister
telling the British what to do about Northern Ireland.
   But Foreign Minister Joe Clark snapped back: ``If members
opposite think Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher lets other people
tell her what to say, then they know a different Margaret Thatcher
than I do.''
   The Thatcher and Baker testimonials to free trade, a deal that
would eliminate all tariffs in 10 years and more closely integrate
the Canadian and U.S. economies, were in contrast to
behind-the-scenes battling during the economic summit.
   Mulroney had sought strong backing for the treaty in the final
communique, but the French and Japanese were among governments
concerned that the sweeping bilateral agreement could deprive them
of market share in North America.
   The tentative draft of the communique said only that summit
partners ``welcome'' the U.S.-Canada deal, but under last minute
pressure from Canada, that was changed to ``strongly welcome'' _
which British Chancellor of the Exchequer Nigel Lawson pointed out
was awkward English but agreed to accept.
   Baker said the pact will enhance trade liberalization, and break
ground by covering services, investment and technology and possibly
dislodging differences over agriculture.
   ``Canada and the U.S. are lowering barriers between themselves,
not raising barriers to others,'' he said. ``The rewards of this
agreement offer an incentive to other governments.
   ``We hope ... follow-up liberalization will occur in the Uruguay
Round. If not, we might be willing to explore a `market
liberalization club' approach, through minilateral arrangements or
a series of bilateral agreements. In this fashion, North America
can build steady momentum for more open and efficient markets.''
   Baker spoke as crews cleaned up the Metropolitan Toronto
Convention Center where 1,500 delegates and 3,000 journalists
gathered for the $16 million summit.
   Reagan and the other six heads of state or government pledged to
ease the debt burden of the poorest Third World nations, combat
drug trafficking and continue a policy of encouraging growth
without inflation.
   The 3,000-member security force assembled for the summit was
relieved to see the leaders go. Apart from two demonstrations
resulting in more than 160 arrests and an arson attack on a
derelict building a block from Reagan's hotel, the meetings went
off without incident.
</TEXT>
