<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brewery-Soviets     06-22 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brewery-Soviets,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ad To Be Aired After 9 Years; Glasnost and Afghanistan Pullout
Credited</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Blitz-Weinhard Brewing Co. has
announced it plans to air a 60-second television commercial filmed
nine years ago but canceled after the Soviet invasion of
Afghanistan.
   The commercial depicted a group of visiting Soviet sailors who
discover the company's Henry Weinhard's Private Reserve Beer, and
is loosely based on an actual incident.
   Gene Clark, a brewery spokesman, said the Soviet pullout from
Afghanistan and the spirit of glasnost has made it possible to put
the ad on television.
   ``The goal of our advertising is to entertain the viewer and
sell beer, not to make political statements,'' Clark said. ``In
today's climate, however, we feel the commercial can be aired and
accepted for what it is _ 60 seconds of entertainment that we hope
sells beer.''
   Filmed in 1979, the $200,000 commercial portrays a group of
Soviet sailors touring the city in 1973 after two Russian fishing
trawlers collided off the central Oregon Coast and one had to be
docked in Coos Bay for two weeks for repairs.
   The sailors keep telling their hosts that life in the Soviet
Union is better, until they are introduced to the beer.
</TEXT>
