<DOCNO> AP880622-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 2122EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SouthAfrica-Sanctions     06-22 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa-Sanctions,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Africa Sanctions Bill To Go Ahead Despite Dim Prospects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate supporters of a bill imposing harsh new
sanctions against white-dominated South Africa acknowleged
Wednesday they do not have the votes to override a certain veto by
President Reagan.
   But they said that in order to highlight opposition to South
Africa's racial policies, they would battle for Senate passage of
the bill, which requires an end to most trade with South Africa as
well as the withdrawal of all U.S. corporate investment.
   Testifying before the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, Deputy
Secretary of State John C. Whitehead strongly opposed the harsh
sanctions measure as counterproductive.
   And Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., the leading opponent of using
sanctions to increase pressures on South Africa to adopt majority
rule reforms, said he will introduce legislation repealing the less
severe sanctions bill passed over President Reagan's veto two years
ago.
   Whitehead said that while the Reagan administration believes
apartheid is repugnant, ``sanctions are the wrong tool because
South Africa has the resources to resist an economic siege and has
been preparing for such a contingency for many years.''
   He said it has become clear over the past two years that the
industrial allies of the United States will resist the U.S. lead
and will not impose sanctions of their own.
   He said South Africa could at will cut off exports of strategic
minerals vital to U.S. industrial efforts.
   Americans must accept the fact that U.S. leverage in South
Africa is limited, Whitehead said.
   ``Resorting to drastic remedies, such as the misuse of American
power to destabilize the South African economy, only increases the
chances of a catastrophic outcome for all South Africans,''
Whitehead said.
   Instead, he said, `'our mission should beone of using all
available means to maximize our influence and leverage.'
   Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., a strong sanctions supporter, said
the administration's attitude demonstrates that the ``thoroughly
discredited'' administration policy of ``constructive engagement''
to nudge South Africa toward reform still survives.
   Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., said the 1986 sanctions bill has not
produced results because ``the administration has been dragging its
feet, creating loopholes, doing nothing to urge our allies to join
in the sanctions.''
   But he and other senators said the drive to impose virtually
total economic sanctions likely will fall short, at least for now.
   ``Candidly, right now I don't think we have the votes to
override a veto,'' Simon said.
   But he said the effort should proceed to demonstrate the breadth
of the U.S. opposition to apartheid and to support internal
pressures for change in South Africa.
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., another sanctions supporter,
told the committee: ``There are those who say that waging economic
war against South Africa will only hurt the people we want to help,
the black workers. But those people are already being hurt more
profoundly by apartheid than any trade sanction we could possibly
devise or impose.''
   The sanctions measure calls for the total removal of all U.S.
corporations and businesses from South Africa and for the end of
two-way trade except for U.S. imports of certain strategic South
African minerals.
   A similar sanctions bill apparently has gathered stronger
momentum in the House.
   So far it has been consdidered favorably by the House Foreign
Affairs, Intelligence, Armed Services and Banking committees and is
pending before the Ways and Means Committee.
   It is likely to be considered on the House floor at a relatively
early date. Passage is expected by a large majority, probably
greater than the two-thirds needed to override a veto.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
