<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hyundai     06-22 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hyundai,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hyundai Plant Fails To Resume Production</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hyundai Motor Co., South Korea's No. 1
automaker, remained closed Wednesday as management rejected a new
labor union demand for payment of wages lost during a 24-day strike
for higher wages.
   The union leaders had called off the strike on Monday, prompting
the company to announce that its auto plant in the southern city of
Ulsan would resume production Tuesday.
   Union leaders said no firm agreement had been reached with the
company, but they indicated Hyundai officials assured them of the
pay raises, which would be negotiated after the workers returned to
the assembly lines. The union leaders, however, changed their
strategy Tuesday after a militant faction of workers refused to
return to work and demanded a compensation for lost wages.
   ``We can't pay wages, under the principle of no work and no
pay,'' said one company official, who requested anonymity.
   The official said union officials would continue negotiating
with the company, which he indicated would find what he called
``indirect'' ways to meet the workers' demand. He refused to
elaborate.
   The company last offered the 20,000 striking workers a pay
increase of $106 a month. The union is demanding $130. Hyundai
autoworkers earn an average of $800 a month after six months,
including allowances. Company officials said Wednesday they would
stick to their last offer, but they said they would consider
additional fringe benefits.
   Hyundai said it has lost production of some 40,000 vehicles
during the strike. About two-thirds of the production was intended
for export to the United States and other countries.
</TEXT>
