<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--MislocatedWarehouse     06-22 0167</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Mislocated Warehouse,0171</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Honest Mistake' Will Cost $400,000; Warehouse In Way Of Highway</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A change in design plans for the
expansion of Interstate 95 will result in the razing of a new
$400,000 city warehouse, officials said.
   ``It just happened,'' said Grady Greene, district director of
production for the Department of Transportation.
   The warehouse was built on land that will used as right of way
for an expansion of I-95. When work on the warehouse started, plans
for the road were different.
   The city is hoping the state will buy the buidling, which cost
$395,787 to build, then scrap it at state taxpayers' expense.
   Salem A. Salem, city Public Works director, said no single
person or agency is to blame. But Greene said the city knew the
state was in the process of expanding I-95 in the vicinity of the
warehouse.
   Because of the mix-up, Salem said his department created a new
department head in charge of attending all DOT planning discussions.
</TEXT>
