<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Nigeria-Waste,0150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Experts Test Waste Italians Dumped In Nigeria</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A team of U.S. experts Wednesday tested
barrels of European toxic waste an Italian company has dumped in
this West African nation.
   The 2,000 tons of waste _ transported as construction material _
was reportedly dumped near the town of Koko, about 150 miles
southeast of the capital of Lagos.
   The material includes poisonous chemicals and radioactive
material from at least 10 European companies.
   Infuriated by the incident, Nigeria has recalled its ambassador
to Italy, seized an Italian ship and arrested 15 people, including
some Italians.
   The military government has warned Nigerians convicted of
involvement in the dumping that they will be shot by a firing squad.
   The five-man U.S. team, sent at Nigeria's request, will advise
the government on how to dispose of the waste.
