<DOCNO> AP880622-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 1709EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Medvedev     06-22 0767</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Medvedev,0786</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dissident Historian Appears At Official News Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dissident historian Roy Medvedev, expelled from
the Communist Party almost 20 years ago and officially silenced
since, emerged Wednesday to espouse his independent Marxism at a
government-sponsored news conference.
   It was the first official appearance in decades for Medvedev,
and occurred less than three weeks after Andrei D. Sakharov, Nobel
Peace Prize winner and former political exile, met with reporters
at the Soviet Foreign Ministry press center.
   The officially sponsored appearances by two men who were leading
figures in the evolution of the Soviet dissident movement would
have been unimaginable a couple of years ago. They reflected not
only the Soviet Union's more liberal atmosphere under Mikhail S.
Gorbachev but an effort to consolidate support for the Soviet
leader's reforms.
   Medvedev said he was not seeking readmittance to the Communist
Party, but that he would accept it if offered.
   ``I would take it with appreciation, but I'm not going to write
to anybody'' to ask for it, he said.
   In his decades of dissident, Medvedev has emphasized reforms in
Soviet society rather than complete changes in its character. But
he was expelled from the party in 1969 and his major works have
only been published abroad.
   Asked how he felt about being given a public forum to state his
views, he said, ``Of course it's hard to obtain the same form after
20 years, but it's pleasant to answer your questions.''
   Best known for his book ``Let History Judge'' _ a work on
dictator Josef V. Stalin never published in the Soviet Union _
Medvedev said he was invited Tuesday by the government news agency
Novosti to take part in a news conference the next day about the
Soviet Union's review of Stalin's purges.
   Despite the review of Stalin's dictatorship, Soviet authorities
have an equal right to govern the Soviet Union as the U.S.
government has to rule its land, he said.
   ``We are reviewing our history very deeply, but the review
wouldn't undermine the legal basis of our state,'' he said. ``It
has emerged and will continue to function in the future.''
   He defended the Communist Party's monopoly on power through the
one-party system, saying the Soviet Union must develop a democratic
spirit both within and outside the party but that ``at the same
time we need centralism, because without subservience to the
decisions of the central organs, without subservience to the local
centers we may have anarchy.''
   But he said minorities must always have the right to their
opinions.
   Medvedev also cited George Orwell's novel of totalitarianism
``1984,'' a reference that until recently would not have been
possible in an officially sponsored meeting. In answer to a
question about the torture of old Bolsheviks killed by Stalin, he
said Orwell understood well the pressure that could be brought on
people to confess to crimes they didn't commit.
   Medvedev and his brother, Zhores, were among the first prominent
members of what eventually evolved into the Soviet dissident
movement. Zhores, a biochemist and gerontologist, was placed in a
psychiatric hospital before being forced to leave the Soviet Union
for London in 1973.
   Sakharov has said that Medvedev's views were an important
influence, even though they later separated and were leading
figures in contrasting dissident movements.
   Roy Medvedev remained in the Soviet Union. Despite being
expelled from the party and being unable to publish, he was
tolerated by authorities and became a valuable unofficial source
for journalists who often sought his views on history and Kremlin
politics.
   On June 12, the weekly paper Moscow News published a commentary
he wrote about the roots of Stalinism. He told the news conference
Wednesday that several state-owned publishing houses were
interested in publishing his books that so far have only been
released abroad.
   His appearance came on the 47th anniversary of the Nazi invasion
of the Soviet Union in World War II. On Monday, the party newspaper
Pravda blamed Stalin for the poor preparation of Soviet forces that
allowed Nazi forces to drive deep into Soviet territory before they
were stopped.
   Medvedev declined to tell reporters which members of the ruling
Politburo he thinks support Gorbachev and which might oppose him.
   But another panelist, philosopher Yuri Koryakin, said Soviets
need much more information about the personal views of Politburo
members and said he was ``very worried about statements by (Kremlin
No. 2 leader Yegor K.) Ligachev.''
   In his public statements, Ligachev has taken a more conservative
line than Gorbachev on the question of how much openness to allow
in Soviet society.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
