<DOCNO> AP880622-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 2136EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Democrats-Money     06-22 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democrats-Money,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats To Gather For Fund-Raising Unity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The also-ran Democratic candidates are
pitching in with a $2,500-a-person dinner Thursday to help likely
presidential nominee Michael Dukakis raise the $8.3 million the
party can spend to elect him in November.
   As part of the effort to achieve a Democratic Party first _
raising the maximum allowable general election fund _ three of the
candidates and their finance chairmen were scheduled to attend the
dinner at the Georgetown home of developer Joseph Kaempfer,
Democratic National Committee spokeswoman Julie Anbender said
Wednesday.
   She said former candidates Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee,
Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri and Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois
would attend the event with their finance chairmen. Earlier in the
day, the finance chairmen as well as finance representatives of
Dukakis and candidate Jesse Jackson will meet with DNC officials to
discuss fund-raising plans for November.
   DNC officials said the Democratic candidates have established a
cooperative attitude toward helping the man who beat them all in
the primaries.
   ``There is by all accounts more unity and cooperation than any
time in the recent past that anyone can remmeber,'' said Tony
Blinken, deputy director of the DNC's Victory Fund for November.
   So far, the party has raised about $1.5 million of the $8.3
million that election law allows the party to spend on its nominee,
said Anbender.
   That money is in addition to the $46 million each candidate
receives from the federal Treasury to fund his campaign.
   The party already has more than $4 million in so-called soft
money, which it will distribute to the state party officials to
spend on their own state activities _ which ultimately can help the
national ticket as well.
   Robert Farmer, the Boston money whiz who engineered Dukakis'
successful fund-raising effort, has pledged to raise $42 million in
soft money.
   Soft money refers generally to funds that are banned in federal
elections _ like union and corporate donations _ but that are
permitted in many states and can be used for such activities as
voter registration, which ends up helping the national ticket as
well.
   Among other planned fund-raising events, the Democrats hope to
raise $200 at each of 10,000 televison parties on the last night of
the Democratic national convention next month.
   People will be invited to pay admission to attend one of the
parties nationwide and watch the Dukakis acceptance speech the last
night of the conventon.
   In addition, the party is sending out direct mail and is asking
50 top fund-raisers to pledge to raise $100,000 each, Anbender said.
   ``The soft money is going extremely well,'' she said.
   In 1984, when the hard money limit for the parties was just over
$6 million, the party raised a total of $2.4 million, said Anbender.
</TEXT>
