<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WoodChipperTrial     06-22 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wood Chipper Trial,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Closing Arguments Heard In Crafts Case; Jury Gets Case Thursday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEAN GOLEMBESKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW LONDON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor told a jury Wednesday that
a collection of body fragments were sufficient to prove that an
airline pilot killed his wife and disposed of her body with a wood
chipper.
   State's Attorney Walter Flanagan mounted photographs of hair
strands, skull fragments, a thumb, a toe bone and other body
fragments on a picture of a body outlined in charcoal on white
poster board.
   In closing arguments to the 12-week trial, Flanagan acknowledged
that only one tooth recovered by police was positively identified
as belonging to Helle Crafts, but he told the jurors, ``you can put
everything together and you look at other evidence.''
   Mrs. Crafts, a 39-year-old flight attendant for Pan American
World Airways, wasn't the type of person who would have abandoned
her three young children, as the defense has argued, Flanagan said.
   Richard Crafts was upset over his wife's plans to file for
divorce, giving him a motive, and he was the last person to see his
wife alive, the prosecutor said.
   But defense attorney Daniel Sagarin sought to cast doubt on the
evidence, saying that the 75 or so body fragments weighed no more
than two-thirds of an ounce.
   ``Ask yourself what's not there. ... You say to yourself, `Where
is the evidence?' We have a very small amount of evidence we're
dealing with,'' he said.
   Crafts, a 50-year-old pilot for Eastern Airlines and part-time
police officer, is charged with murdering his wife, who was last
seen Nov. 18, 1986, after returning from an overseas flight.
   The prosecution has alleged that Crafts killed his wife, cut up
her body with a chain saw and then fed the body parts through a
rented wood-chipping machine.
   Flanagan told the jurors they could be convinced that the body
parts found by police along the banks of the Housatonic River in
southeast Connecticut and in a U-Haul truck rented by Crafts were
indeed from his wife. He reminded jurors that an expert had
identified a tooth as belonging to Mrs. Crafts.
   But Sagarin noted that Dr. Henry Lee, the state's top forensic
expert, testified that a tooth crown also presented as evidence was
not made at the laboratory where Mrs. Crafts had her dental work
done.
   Flanagan also reminded jurors that Mrs. Crafts had paid an
attorney $2,500 in cash to represent her in divorce proceedings.
``This is an indication that she intended to pursue a divorce, not
to flee,'' he said.
   Sagarin contended there was reasonable doubt whether Crafts
could have committed murder.
   The case is expected to go to the jury Thursday.
</TEXT>
