<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Newman     06-22 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Newman,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newman Jury Deliberations Halted Over Improper Evidence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA STOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The discovery that unauthorized
evidence was at the jury's disposal brought to a halt Wednesday
jury deliberations over a delicatessen owner's claims that Paul
Newman reneged on a promise to give him a share of the actor's food
business.
   The jury, which had deliberated for eight hours over two days,
was sent home at 3:30 p.m. after its foreman told the court that it
had received depositions from the plaintiff, Julius Gold of
Westport, and some defendants, and wanted to see Newman's.
   The depositions weren't entered into evidence during the
three-week trial and shouldn't have been given to the jury,
attorneys said. W. Patrick Ryan, Newman's attorney, said it
appeared a clerk who took the exhibits into the jury room
inadvertently also took the depositions in.
   Judge Howard Zoarski said attorneys will have to discuss the
situation.
   ``I'm very upset,'' said Gold's lawyer, Richard Albrecht.
   Gold sued Newman, another Westport resident; his two food
companies, Newman's Own Inc., and Salad King Inc.; Newman's partner
and longtime friend, A.E. Hotchner; and food distributor David
Kalman.
   Gold claimed he helped develop and market Newman's Own salad
dressing and was promised 8 percent of the stock. Gold said he
contributed 30 months' effort to Newman's company and believed his
work led to the corporation's success. There was no estimate of
what the 8 percent interest was worth.
   The defendants have denied all the allegations.
   Newman, president and founder of Newman's Own, testified that
the idea for the company's salad dressing, its label, recipe and
packaging were his.
   Newman's Own, whose products include spaghetti sauce, lemonade
and popcorn, has donated $15 million to charity since 1982 and
helped create a camp for seriously ill children in northeastern
Connecticut.
</TEXT>
