<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FAA-Ameriflight     06-22 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FAA-Ameriflight,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Grounds Cargo Airline Over Safety Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration ordered
Ameriflight Inc., a California-based cargo carrier, grounded
Wednesday because of a broad range of alleged safety violations.
   Ameriflight, which has its headquarters in Burbank, Calif.,
operated about 90 aircraft, most of them propellar planes, in cargo
service. It has branch offices in Salt Lake City and Seattle,
according to the FAA.
   The FAA said it has revoked Ameriflight's operating certificate
because of violations of federal air safety regulations that agency
inspectors found in a review in March and April.
   Executives of Ameriflight could not immediately be reached for
comment. A secretary said they were in a meeting.
   The FAA said in its inspection it found Ameriflight had used
pilots who had not had timely proficiency checks, improperly
converted passenger compartments to cargo use in 17 planes, failed
to comply with airworthiness directives on six aircraft and failed
to make checks to determine if maintenance work had been done
properly on 35 aircraft.
   The airline also was found to have operated aircraft for long
periods without performing required repairs, said the FAA. It cited
one instance in which a Piper aircraft flew 540 flights over three
months with 16 maintenance deficiencies not being corrected.
   FAA spokesman Fred Farrar said that while Ameriflight had held a
certificate that would have allowed it to fly passengers, none of
its planes is believed to have been configured for passenger use.
</TEXT>
