<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Chappell-Aide     06-22 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chappell-Aide,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Consultant Identified As Aide Rode Pentagon VIP Jet</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Defense Probe Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A consultant to a defense contractor was given top
security clearance and two days of free travel on a Pentagon VIP
jet after being wrongly identified as an aide to Rep. Bill Chappell
Jr., the Dallas Morning News reported Wednesday.
   Chappell, D-Fla., is one of five House members reportedly under
scrutiny in a massive FBI investigation into allegations that
defense consultants obtained classified and proprietary information
through bribery and fraud. Chappell, who is chairman of the House
Appropriations defense subcommittee, has denied the allegations.
   According to Air Force records obtained by the newspaper, W.
Leonard Killgore Jr., a consultant to Oshkosh Truck Corp., rode
aboard an Air Force C-20 jet from Washington to Daytona, Fla., to
Portland, Ore., and back to Washington on Sept. 27-28, 1987.
   Killgore has been a private consultant to defense contractors
since 1980. But the Air Force order authorizing the flights and
security clearance listed him as ``Legislative Assistant to
Representative Chappell,'' according to the records obtained
through a Freedom of Information Act request.
   Killgore rode in on the jet which picked up Chappell and his
wife in the congressman's home district. They flew to Portland for
the annual meeting of the National Guard Association of the United
States and returned to Washington the next day, travel records show.
   ``I was invited to make that trip and I made it,'' Killgore said.
   Capt. Andrea Shaffron, an Air Force spokeswoman, said Tuesday
that the service was unable to explain immediately how the
authorizing order was issued.
   Killgore and Chappell aide Kay Thomas told the News the order's
description listing Killgore as an aide was an apparent error.
   ``Mr. Killgore was invited by the Guard Association to be a
guest at their convention and to travel on the airplane under
appropriate Air Force orders,'' Ms. Thomas told the News. ``When
the Air Force personnel prepared the aircraft manifest, they
apparently assumed that Mr. Killgore was a member of Chairman
Chappell's staff. Until you raised the issue, no one had noticed
the mistake.''
   Chappell was in a conference Wednesday and was unavailable for
comment, his office told The Associated Press.
   Killgore, a retired National Guard colonel, said the National
Guard Bureau granted him the authority to board the plane.
   But Lt. Col. Jim Ragan, a spokesman for the National Guard
Bureau, said the Air Force C-20 jet is not one the bureau could
authorize private citizens to ride.
   The cost of the 11.7 hours of flight time logged by the aircraft
during the two-day trip was $29,565.90, Air Force records show.
   Killgore was one of three Oshkosh officials at an April 1987
breakfast where several members of the House Armed Service
Committee received $2,000 honorariums only hours before a vote to
force the Army to buy 500 more Oshkosh trucks than the Army wanted.
</TEXT>
