<HEAD>Dollar, Bond Rallies Push Stocks to Post-Crash High</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also on financial wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rise in the dollar spurred a rally in the bond
market Wednesday, which in turn propelled the stock market to its
highest level since the October crash.
   The Dow Jones industrial average closed 43.03 points higher at
2,152.20, easily eclipsing the previous post-crash high of 2,131.40
set a week ago.
   Three stocks rose for every one that fell on the New York Stock
Exchange, where 217.51 million shares changed hands.
   The catalyst for the rally appeared to be a surprising surge in
the value of the dollar overseas, which eased worries about
inflation.
   That fed a rally in bond prices that pushed yields on the
closely watched 30-year Treasury bond back under 9 percent, which
buoyed stock prices.
