<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WritersStrike     06-22 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Writers Strike,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rancorous Writers Prepare To Vote On Contract Offer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A badly divided screenwriters guild made
last-minute maneuvers before a bicoastal vote Wednesday on whether
to end a 4-month-old strike.
   Leaders of the Writers Guild of America have urged rejection of
the proposed contract from the Alliance of Motion Picture and
Television Producers, which claims its offer is worth $71 million
over the next four years.
   A dissident group within the union has urged approval and a
return to work as the new television production season gets under
way. Jobs from craft workers to caterers would be affected by a
prolonged strike.
   The vote, during membership meetings Wednesday night in Los
Angeles and New York, comes on the eve of the television production
season. Results of the vote will be announced Thursday.
   Both sides within the union predicted an angry gathering.
   Brian Walton, the guild's chief negotiator and its West Coast
executive director, found his leadership challenged publicly on
Tuesday by a dissident group within the union that urged approval
of the producers' offer.
   ``The guild is at an important crossroads,'' Walton told members
in a mailed message that forecast the acromony. ``You and your
guild are likely to be bombarded with an intense PR barrage from
the alliance and its allies designed to persuade you that their
third and latest offer is good enough for you to vote up and and
that you have no realistic choice.''
   Members of the loosely formed Writers Coalition said at a news
conference Tuesday they believe the union has already squeezed far
more from producers than most expected.
   The group includes some of Hollywood's top writer-producers such
as Steve Bochco, John Hughes, John Milius, and Stephen Cannell, who
also is a member of the alliance.
   ``Some of us were surprised that as much has been accomplished
as has been in the last 16 weeks,'' Bochco said. ``One wonders how
much further we would go in another four, six, eight, 10 or 12
weeks. It has an economic impact that hits everyone in our
business. People aren't working,'' he said.
   The 9,500-member Writers Guild struck on March 7 over the issue
of payments for reruns of one-hour domestic television shows and a
bigger share in the increased foreign market. They also sought
better guidelines to protect a writer's work and allow writers to
re-acquire unproduced scripts.
   Agreement was reached on matters of creative control, but both
sides remain divided on the economic package.
   Writers agreed with the producers' position that the rerun
payments, known as residuals, for one-hour television shows should
be tied to a sales formula rather than a fixed payment.
   Producers have argued that the market for such shows has grown
soft, and it was unfair for them to pay writers a big residual for
selling the rerun package in only a few markets.
   But Walton has claimed the producers failed to reciprocate with
a more generous offer in the area of foreign distribution
residuals. The union has linked the two economic items.
</TEXT>
