<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0670 06-22 0883</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0670,840</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Calls for Tougher Sentences in Law Enforcement Incidents</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 1 graf after 4th graf pvs, bgng, `The comment,' and
2
grafs after 20th graf pvs, bgng, `And he,' with Bush comment from
interview with local reporters.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush on Wednesday
called for tougher sentences for crimes against law enforcement
officers, saying that for too long politicians and judges held
captive by civil libertarians have controlled the nation.
   The all-but-certain Republican nominee called for establishing
tough mandatory penalties for any violent crime against a law
enforcement officer and said the FBI should have clear authority to
investigate attacks against law officers anywhere in the United
States.
   ``For too many years, we've been held hostage by well-meaning
but misguided politicians and judges who get their legal views from
the ACLU (American Civil Liberties Union),'' Bush told a meeting of
the National Sheriffs Association.
   The comment won hearty applause from the audience of sheriffs.
   Later, Bush told local reporters that Dukakis had called himself
``a card-carrying member of the ACLU. That was a quote of his.''
   Bush also said bullet-proof vests should be made available to
every officer in the country who wants it.
   ``A lot of lives could be saved. We owe it,'' Bush said, holding
up a police vest that he said had been fired at three times at
point-blank range without injuring the wearer.
   He did not indicate who would pay for such protective clothing.
   As an aside, the vice president joked when he held up the vest
that the bullets ``were not fired by Carl Rowan, I might add. They
hit right here in the middle.''
   Rowan, a syndicated columnist, last week shot a backyard
intruder in the hand.
   Bush, in a speech he claimed was non-political, took another
swipe at what is becoming a favorite target: a Massachusetts prison
furlough system.
   The vice president claims that the program, administered by his
Democratic rival, Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, permitted
convicted first-degree murderers to go free on weekends to
terrorize innocent people.
   He called such a program naive and irresponsible, but without
mentioning Dukakis by name.
   However, one member of the audience, Robert C. Rufo, sheriff of
Suffolk County (Boston), Mass., took issue with Bush's comments.
   ``This is no more than a Republican smokescreen to try to divert
attention from where they are weak,'' Rufo, who was wearing a
Dukakis button on his lapel, told reporters after Bush's speech.
   Rufo claimed Dukakis inherited the furlough program and that it
no longer applies to convicted murderers.
   ``You're never an unmovable object in politics. I'm not and he
(Dukakis) is not. He shares the vice president's views on furloughs
(for convicted murderers),'' Rufo said.
   The vice president also reiterated his support for tougher
sentences for drug offenses and the death penalty for drug
kingpins. ``If this is a war, let's treat it as such. Let's get
these killers off the street,'' Bush said.
   He said drug offenders should be put in prison and that a
federal rule that suppresses evidence obtained in warrantless
searches _ the so-called exclusionary rule _ should be abandoned.
   ``There's someting wrong with the system when the modern-day
version of a prison break is crawling through a loophole,'' Bush
said.
   And he accused ``liberals in the Senate'' of derailing new
sentencing guidelines for a federal death penalty.
   But later, in the interview, Bush said he would not urge the
death penalty for crimes involving drunken driving. In Kentucky,
the issue is an emotional one in the wake of a bus-truck accident
that left 27 people dead. The driver of the truck, who has been
charged with murder, allegedly was drunk.
   ``I don't think a death penalty for drunk driving is proper ...
I don't think a drunk driver is making a conscious decision under
the influence. Do I think drunk driving is bad? Do I think they
ought to pay a penalty? Absolutely. But I draw the line there.''
   Bush also called for a denial of parole of some convicts,
saying: ``The view that all convicts can be rehabilitated is not
just naive, it's dead wrong.''
   ``When first-degree murderers sentenced to life without parole
get unsupervised weekend furloughs and commuted sentences, that
view goes from naive to dangerous, from well-meaning to
irresponsible,'' Bush said.
   Bush recounted details of the case of Willy Horton, a convicted
Massachusetts murderer who was released on a weekend furlough and
accused of raping a woman while he was free.
   Rufo, who is the president of the Massachusetts Sheriffs'
Association, told reporters that ``there were 121,000 successful
furloughs before that incident.''
   Speaking with reporters aboard Air Force Two, Bush accused
Dukakis of waffling on many issues, including his support for the
prison furlough program and his public statements on the B-1 bomber.
   ``People need to know. Where's the guy coming from?'' said Bush.
``I can't count on others to do this. I've got to spell it out and
then get surrogates, those other people who believe as I do, to
spell it out.''
   Bush denied he was engaging in a negative campaign against the
likely Democratic nominee.
   ``It's the record _ what he favors and what I favor. It's not
name-calling,'' he said.
</TEXT>
