<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--Reagan-Rail     06-22 0130</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Reagan-Rail,130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Signs Rail Safety Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan signed legislation Wednesday
aimed at improving rail safety in the wake of a January 1987 crash
of Amtrak and Conrail trains that killed 16 people.
   The legislation, among other things, requires the licensing and
certification of locomotive operators and prescribes new
requirements for the use of safety-related equipment on trains.
   It also provides for enforcement of subpoenas and orders by the
secretary of transportation in connection with railroad
investigations and revises federal rail safety statutes to increase
penalties for violations.
   Investigators of the crash near Chase, Md., that killed 16 and
injured 175 found that a device had been disabled on the Conrail
train that would have warned the train's operators they had passed
a stop signal.
</TEXT>
