<1ST_LINE>r w AM-PanamaDeployment     06-22 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama Deployment,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>250 Support Troops Ordered to Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon on Wednesday ordered 250
additional military personnel sent to Panama, most of them to
provide logistical and administrative support to the troops already
there.
   Maj. Kathy Wood, a Defense Department spokeswoman, said the
contingent consisted of a 50-man Air Force security team and 200
Army troops. The personnel are being deployed from several bases
around the country and should be in place in Panama by Friday, she
added.
   The soldiers being dispatched will help provide administrative,
communications and logistical support to Army units already in the
field, she said.
   The deployment brings to roughly 2,250 the number of additional
military personnel sent to Panama since early this spring, when the
Reagan administration began pressuring military leader Gen. Manuel
A. Noriega to step down and return the government to civilian rule.
   Most of the earlier deployments involved Air Force, Marine and
Army security and police personnel who were dispatched to ensure
protection for Americans in the country.
   The U.S. Southern Command, which oversees all U.S. military
activity in Central and South America, is based in Panama. About
10,000 military personnel work for the Southern Command at bases in
the Panama Canal Zone.
</TEXT>
