<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Iraq-US     06-22 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iraq-US,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Middle East Envoy due in Baghdad</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. envoy Richard Murphy, touring the
Middle East, is expected in Baghdad over the weekend to smooth
diplomatic feathers ruffled by the visit of an Iraqi Kurdish rebel
leader to the State Department.
   Iraq is unhappy with U.S. officials for receiving Jalal Talabani
earlier this month. The visit was perceived here as a diplomatic
slap and unsettled what had been a year of improved U.S.-Iraq
relations.
   Six Kurdish groups formed an alliance in May to fight for
self-rule in northern Iraq and, with Iranian help, have turned the
Kurdistan mountains into another front of the Iran-Iraq war, now
nearly eight years old.
   By publicly meeting with Talabani, who leads the Patriotic Union
of Kurdistan, U.S. officials were regarded by Baghdad as dealing
with an enemy of the state and interfering in Iraq's internal
affairs.
   Washington said it was following the policy of listening to
anyone who wants to talk, not sending diplomatic signals. After
meeting with the Kurdish leader, State Department officials said
Iraq had no reason to question overall U.S. policy.
   President Saddam Hussein's government called U.S. regional
policy into question in an editorial attributed to the political
editor of the official Iraqi News Agency and another editorial in
Al-Thawra, official newspaper of the ruling Baath Party.
   Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz canceled a scheduled meeting with
Secretary of State George P. Shultz.
   The news agency editorial recited a list of Iraqi grievances,
including allegations that United States supplied direct or
indirect technical assistance to Iran and gave it intelligence
information about Iraq.
   ``Is this also a fault committed by a junior officer, or is it
once more a badly calculated move pushed by Zionist hatred?'' the
editorial asked, referring to the U.S. explanation of arms sales to
Iran arranged through lower-echelon White House officials working
with Israeli arms dealers.
   ``In essence (the Talabani meeting) was a very grave and serious
mistake which clearly and directly infringes on the principle of
non-interference in the internal affairs of Iraq,'' it said.
   Murphy, an assistant secretary and specialist in Middle East
affairs, is on an eight-nation tour for talks about Arab-Israeli
peace and the war between Iran and Iraq.
</TEXT>
