<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0741 06-22 0624</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0741,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Says Dukakis' National Health Plan is Insufficient</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS two grafs after graf 5 pvs, bgng ``Asked if...'' with
Jackson aide saying he did not request spot on ticket</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential contender Jesse
Jackson told a labor convention Wednesday that a national health
insurance plan proposed by expected Democratic presidential nominee
Michael Dukakis is ``not sufficient.''
   However, Jackson told a news conference later that he would
support Dukakis's health program because ``it is an improvement
over what we have now.''
   Jackson also reaffirmed that he and Dukakis discussed the
Massachusetts governor's selection of a vice presidential running
mate in their private meeting here Tuesday, but again refused to go
into any specifics.
   ``We talked in more detail than I choose to talk about now. The
process is in motion,'' Jackson said.
   Asked if he wanted the vice presidential nomination, Jackson
replied, ``I have not yet made that decision.''
   The head of Jackson's convention team, Ron Brown, was asked by
reporters in Washington if Jackson had asked Dukakis to put him on
the ticket.
   ``He did not,'' Brown replied. ``That has not been his public or
private position,'' he said, repeating the campaign's position that
Jackson deserves serious consideration for the job.
   And when asked if he would be disappointed if Dukakis didn't
offer him the No. 2 spoton the ticket, Jackson said tersely: ``I
choose not to respond to that now.''
   However, Jackson did say that his campaign has received Dukakis'
request for the personal financial information he is seeking from
potential running mates, and that his wife and attorney, among
others, were reviewing the request in Chicago.
   In his address to about 3,500 delegates to the national
convention of the American Federation of State, County and
Municipal Employees, Jackson cited the same health insurance
statistics and voiced the same concerns Dukakis recited in his
Tuesday address to the AFSCME convention.
   But Jackson offered a much broader health program and criticized
the Dukakis plan.
   Describing heath care as ``the birthright of every family and
every citizen'' Dukakis told the labor convention that as president
he would seek to extend nationwide the program he signed into law
in Massachusetts to require every employer except a few very small
firms to provide health insurance for all of their employees.
   Jackson told the labor convention ``there is no question that
the Massachusetts plan applied nationally would be a great leap
forward,'' but then he suggested it wasn't the best approach.
   ``It's time to jump in another direction. We do not need a great
leap forward throwing more money into our wasteful, public-private
patchwork medical delivery system. We need to ... move away from
the precipice towards a rational comprehensive plan,'' Jackson said.
   Instead of Dukakis' proposal, Jackson outlined a much broader
``federally funded and publicly administered'' health plan for all
Americans which he said ultimately would cost less that Dukakis'
``patchwork'' proposal.
   ``A health care program that is not adequate should not be
supported,'' Jackson said.
   Asked if that meant he would oppose the Dukakis plan, Jackson
said no.
   ``If he puts it forward in legislation, I certainly would
(support it), but I would also seek to amend it and expand it,''
Jackson said. ``It is an improvement over what we have now, but it
is not sufficient.''
   Jackson also charged that the Pentagon procurement scandal ``is
no aberration _ it is systemic,'' and a product of President
Reagan's policies.
   ``What's the result? Cost-plus contracts that remove risk,
sole-source contracts that remove competition, systematic waste,
pervasive corruption,'' Jackson said. ``Reagan loved private
enterprise so much that he even privatized his foreign policy. What
else was the Iran-Contra scandal all about?''
</TEXT>
