<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Greece-Explosives     06-22 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Greece-Explosives,0402</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinian Receives Three-Year Sentence For Arms Possession</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK QUINN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PIRAEUS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian accused of driving a car
containing arms and explosives onto a ferry bound for Israel was
convicted Wednesday and sentenced to three years in jail, but
claimed he was set up.
   The court in Piraeus, the port of Athens, found Omar Mohammed
Soffareny, a 41-year-old naturalized West German photo technician,
guilty of illegal possession and importation of weapons.
   He also was fined 70,000 drachmas ($522). Soffareny appealed and
was jailed pending an hearing, for which no date was set.
   Soffareny was arrested Monday after port authorities and Israeli
security officers found a revolver and liquid explosives hidden in
his car on the 3,895-ton ferry Paloma.
   The court was told 19 bottles of liquid explosive, 20
detonators, a silenced revolver and 101 rounds of ammunition were
concealed in the car.
   ``I didn't know they were there,'' Soffareny said. ``I had no
idea about this. Somebody else must have put them there.''
   He was arrested shortly before the Paloma sailed for the island
of Rhodes, the Cypriot port of Limassol and the Israeli port of
Haifa with 400 passengers and 100 crewmen.
   About 100 of the passengers were bound for Israel, according to
an official of Afroessa Lines, the ferry owner.
   Soffareny arrived in Greece June 18, driving from West Germany
through Austria and Yugoslavia. He told the court he was going to
Israel to visit his ailing mother in Nazareth. He has lived in West
Germany 20 years.
   ``Every time I think about the things that were in my automobile
and could have exploded at any minute, I start to cry,'' he told
The Associated Press. ``I would never take weapons to Israel
because I go there every year.''
   He said he bought the car second hand in Nuremberg last February
from a Lebanese dealer. He said he returned it to the dealer three
weeks ago for repairs and it was sent to a Syrian mechanic in
Nuremberg.
   ``I've been married to a German woman for 18 years and didn't
even know any Arabs until we moved to Nuremberg from Hanover two
years ago,'' he said.
   Soffareny was born in Nazareth and held an Israeli passport
until becoming a naturalized West German citizen five years ago,
his lawyer told the court.
</TEXT>
