<DOCNO> AP880622-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 2149EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Angola     06-22 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Angola,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angolan Leader Sees Hope for Ending Warfare</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Angolan leader met with Secretary of State
George P. Shultz on Wednesday and expressed hope for success at
talks aimed at ending 13 years of guerrilla warfare that has
inflamed his country and other parts of southern Africa.
   In rare U.S. discussions with a cabinet member of Angola's
Cuban-backed government, Planning Minister Pedro Castro Van Dunem
and Shultz talked about a meeting to be held in Cairo later this
week by South African, Angolan, Cuban and U.S. representatives.
   Wednesday's meeting reflected a stirring of hopes in the Reagan
administration that a settlement leading to withdrawal of Cuban
troops from Angola can be devised.
   Under an envisioned settlement, the peace in Angola would be
accompanied by independence for Namibia, the vast region south of
Angola controlled by South Africa.
   Van Dunem told reporters after his meeting with Shultz, ``let us
hope things will go very well'' at the Cairo session.
   He said Shultz expressed some concern about whether warring
factions within Angola can be reconciled. The factions are the
Angolan government on one side and a U.S.-backed guerrilla
movement, UNITA, led by Jonas Savimbi.
   Savimbi is scheduled to hold talks in Washington with Reagan
administration officials next week.
   Angola has been identified by the United States and the Soviet
Union as one of the regional hot spots that needs to be cooled, and
now that Russian troops are pulling out of Afghanistan, the Angolan
question has been receiving more attention.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
