<1ST_LINE>r i AM-CostaRica-Fishermen     06-22 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Costa Rica-Fishermen,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sailors Welcomed Home After 144 Days Adrift</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUAN MALTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five fishermen came home Wednesday
after 144 days adrift in the Pacific Ocean, vowing to return to sea
despite a grueling odyssey they survived by living off sharks,
turtles and rainwater.
   ``The sea is the source of life for us and our families,'' a
moist-eyed Joel Omar Gonzalez, 27, said, hugging his wife after
arriving at Juan Santamaria Airport from Los Angeles. ``We're sea
dogs. The sea calls to us.''
   A Japanese tuna boat rescued the crew of the 33-foot Cairo III
drifting 700 miles southeast of Hawaii on June 15.
   The Cairo III set sail January 19 from Puntarenas, west of San
Jose, for what was to be an eight-day fishing trip. A storm
disabled the boat five days later, leaving it adrift in the Pacific.
   Capt. Gerardo Obregon, 33, and his crew _ Gonzalez, Juan Cernas
Bolivar, 47, Pastor Lopez Rojas, 30, and Jorge Hernandez Castillo,
22, _ said they survived by catching turtles and sharks and
collecting rainwater.
   Doctors in Honolulu pronounced the five sailors in perfect
health after their rescue.
   Costa Rica's first lady, Margarita de Arias, joined the
relatives, friends, neighbors and fellow fishermen who arrived in
buses from Puntarenas, 95 miles away.
   ``It was a torment for us ... not knowing if he was alive or
dead,'' Mrs. Lopez said as her sons, 3-year-old Alvaro and
2-year-old Roger, clung to their father's knees.
   Obregon was unwilling to discuss the ordeal at length.
   ``Imagine,'' he said, ``our little boat in the middle of the
ocean, directionless. The hot sun of the daytime, the darkness of
the night, the stars and the cold. They were truly terrible days.''
   Gonzalez said the most critical point of the 3,600-mile journey
was being without water for four days. ``There was a moment when
were drinking the blood of a turtle and I looked at Pastor and he
was foaming at the mouth,'' Gonzalez said.
   After a news conference, the sailors headed for the cathedral at
nearby Cartago to give thanks for their rescue.
   The Cairo III was left where the tuna boat found it, drifting in
the Pacific, stripped of much of its wood by the stranded fishermen
desperate for firewood.
   An official at the Puntarenas Naval Base said the Cairo III and
its crew may have broken the record for survival at sea.
   The Guinness Book of World Records lists the record for survival
on a raft as 133 days, set by a Hong Kong man who was adrift in the
Atlantic Ocean from Nov. 23, 1942, to April 5, 1943 after his ship
was torpedoed.
</TEXT>
