<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PoliticalRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0769 06-22 1060</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0769,1,070</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Renews Attacks on Dukakis; Jackson Receiving `Serious
Consideration'</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS grafs 7-8 with Biden endorsement; SUBS 11th graf pvs,
``I have, with Jackson aide saying Jackson did not ask for vice
presidency</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush resumed criticism of Michael Dukakis on
Wednesday, saying he has waffled on major issues and permitted a
murderer to win a prison furlough. Dukakis, his search for a
running mate in full swing, said Jesse Jackson was getting ``very
serious consideration.''
   Bush denied he was engaging in name-calling in his attacks on
Dukakis and said he would continue to point out differences between
himself and the Democratic presidential nominee-to-be.
   ``It's the record _ what he favors and what I favor. It's not
name-calling,'' the vice president and Republican presidential
candidate told reporters aboard Air Force Two en route to
Louisville, Ky.
   Bush also accused Dukakis in his talk with reporters of waffling
on many issues, including public statements on the B-1 bomber.
Dukakis opposed the B-1, but aides say he would not cancel
contracts for purchases.
   ``People need to know: where's the guy coming from?'' Bush said.
   Dukakis, spending the day in Boston, was peppered with questions
about his vice presidential search _ including the polling his
campaign is conducting on the running mate question and requests
for background information from at least two potential candidates.
   The Massachusetts governor also picked up the endorsement of
former rival Sen. Joseph Biden of Delaware, who dropped out of the
race in September.
   Biden's departure came after Dukakis' top aide John Sasso
distributed an ``attack video'' that depicted Biden borrowing
without credit a speech by a British politician. Biden quit as
other allegations of plagiarism and resume-puffing surfaced; Sasso
left the Dukakis campaign after admitting his role in the incident.
   On the matter of a running mate, Dukakis said Jackson's lack of
government experience does ``not necessarily'' rule him out for the
No. 2 spot on the Democratic ticket and said he was getting ``very
serious consideration.''
   He sidestepped questions about whether Jackson would be a
liability on the ticket, based on public polls.
   ``I'm not going to be checking a lot of polls, believe me,''
Dukakis said. ``We all have our strengths and our weaknesses.''
   Jackson, refusing to concede the Democratic presidential
nomination to Dukakis despite the Massachusetts governor's delegate
majority, spoke to a union audience in California and later
declined to say if he wanted the vice presidential nomination.
   ``I have not yet made that decision,'' he said, despite earlier
statements that it should be offered to him. Jackson aide Ron Brown
said that when the two met on Tuesday, Jackson did not ask for the
No. 2 spot.
   Appearing before the same union of government workers where
Dukakis stressed increased health care programs a day earlier,
Jackson dismissed Dukakis' plan for national health insurance as
``not sufficient.''
   Jackson offered his own broader program but said he would
support Dukakis' plan as better than nothing.
   Holding a Statehouse news conference, Dukakis said his search
for a running mate would expand beyond the candidates who have been
asked for background information. They include Jackson and Sen. Bob
Graham, D-Fla.
   One senator popular with Dukakis, Sen. Bill Bradley of New
Jersey, has said he is not interested in joining the ticket and,
according to his office, has not been asked to provide background
information.
   But Dukakis said that doesn't mean Bradley has been ruled out.
He pointedly said Bradley ``has not told me personally'' that he
shouldn't be considered. But Bradley's office said flatly the New
Jersey senator is not interested.
   Bush spoke to the National Sheriffs Association, where he called
for tougher sentences for crimes against law enforcement officers
and said bullet-proof armor should be made available to every
officer in the nation who wants it.
   He avoided mentioning Dukakis by name but again pointed to what
has become a favorite target: a Massachusetts prison furlough
system administered by Dukakis as governor.
   Bush recounted details of the case of Willy Horton, a convicted
Massachusetts murderer who was released on a weekend furlough and
accused of raping a Maryland woman while he was free.
   ``The view that all convicts can be rehabilitated is not just
naive, it's dead wrong,'' Bush said.
   ``When first-degree murderers sentenced to life without parole
get unsupervised weekend furloughs and commuted sentences, that
view goes from naive to dangerous, from well-meaning to
irresponsible,'' Bush said.
   Bush also declared that ``for too many years, we've been held
hostage by well-meaning but misguided politicians and judges who
get their legal views from the ACLU,'' a reference to the American
Civil Liberties Union.
   Dukakis is a member of the ACLU.
   Dukakis defended himself against Bush's attacks, saying he had
tightened eligibility requirements to exclude first-degree
murderers from the furlough program.
   He charged Bush was focusing on the escape case because he had
no record of his own on crime issues, and pointed to decreased
crime rates in his state.
   Dukakis attended an event touting a Massachusetts state program
that provides job training for welfare recipients. It marked the
graduation of the 50,000th participant.
   In other developments:
   _ In Atlanta, where the Democratic National Convention will be
held in less than a month, host Mayor Andrew Young said the city is
``85 to 90 percent ready'' for the convention that opens July 18.
He dismissed critics who say the preparations aren't adequate.
   ``I don't care what people say about Atlanta,'' Young said.
``Anybody who doesn't like Altanta can go somewhere else. ...
Whatever we need for the convention is going to be ready by the
time the convention gets here.''
   _ Some of the rivals Dukakis defeated for the nomination were
pitching in to help Dukakis raise money by attending a
$2,500-a-person dinner Thursday in Washington. The money will go
toward the $8.3 million the Democratic Party can spend on the fall
election, aside from federal campaign financing.
   Former candidates Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee, Rep.
Richard Gephardt of Missouri and Sen. Paul Simon of Illinois plan
to attend.
   _ Credentials battles involving several states were resolved in
private negotiations between Jackson and Dukakis campaigns,
increasing the potential for a peaceful Democratic convention. As a
result Jackson will pick up a handful of delegates in Kansas and
Dukakis a few in Maine.
</TEXT>
