<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Congress-Drought     06-22 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Drought,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farm Lawmakers Approve Drought Aid Battle Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drought-Cities Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farm lawmakers responded to reports of a
worsening drought by approving a broad blueprint for aid to the
Grain Belt on Wednesday but cautioned that producing actual
legislation would take longer.
   ``The bad news is that the drought is spreading, it's worsening,
something has to be done,'' House Agriculture Committee Chairman E.
``Kika'' de la Garza, D-Texas, told a congressional drought task
force.
   Approval of the battle plan came after chief Agriculture
Department meteorologist Norton Strommen warned lawmakers that rain
must come to the central Corn Belt in three weeks or so to avoid
the type of drought damage currently hitting the Grain Belt.
   Senate Agriculture Committee Chairman Patrick J. Leahy, D-Vt.,
issued a sharply worded warning to food companies not to take
advantage of the drought to raise prices.
   He noted that beef and pork prices actually are falling and said
there was no reason to raise consumer prices, although eventually
there may be.
   Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng said President Reagan did
not mean that he opposed federal aid to drought-stricken farmers
when he suggested at a Toronto news conference that there was
little he could do.
   Lyng said Reagan merely ``exhibited some of the frustration that
some of the rest of us have that you can't do anything to make it
rain.'' He said the president actually favors some form of
assistance.
   The task force was formed a week ago to search for ways to
combat the drought after Lyng told lawmakers to be ready to pass an
assistance package but not to make anything final until the full
scope of the problem was known.
   The battle plan approved by the task force contained a number of
features that would not require congressional action.
   It did call for action to guarantee the income of farmers in
drought-stricken areas, a move that eventually could wind up as the
central feature of any drought bill approved by Congress. But it
offered no specific means of doing so. A number of ways have been
suggested.
   The blueprint called for speeded up action by the Agriculture
Department to allow farmers in disaster counties to get 92 percent
of their normal income-support payments, even if they were
prevented from planting a crop because of drought conditions.
   This would be part of USDA's ``zero-92'' program designed to cut
the link between the amount of a farmer's production and the amount
of his federal payments, believed by some to contribute to farm
surpluses.
   The task force plan urged ``maximum flexibility'' in applying a
requirement that farmers must plant cover crops, such as perenniel
grasses, on land idled for conservation uses.
   The plan also would:
   _Search for ways to make sure producers will have sufficient
herds to resume livestock breeding when the drought ends. Breeders
are selling off stock because of lack of feed.
   _Assess the need for supplemental feeding programs for the poor
next winter with an eye toward possible food scarcity caused by
drought.
   _Find ways to expand participation in the Federal Crop Insurance
program.
   _Use all authority provided in last year's bailout bill for the
financially troubled Farm Credit System to restructure loan
repayments for farmers hard hit by drought.
   _Provide emergency loans to farmers if drought conditions
persist.
   Task force members have been attempting to discourage their
fellow lawmakers from dumping a spate of election-year drought aid
bills in the hopper, but two Michigan lawmakers pushed ahead
Wednesday, saying there was no time for delay.
   Sen. Don Riegle, D-Mich., and Rep. Bob Traxler, D-Mich., offered
a measure that would use in-kind payments to reimburse farmers for
up to 50 percent of their major losses. Traxler said the
legislation had no dollar limit and that it might not pass this
year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
