<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Canada-Thatcher     06-22 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Thatcher,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thatcher Hails Canada-U.S. Trade Pact, Drawing Ire Of Opposition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher of Britain
praised Canada's trade agreement with the United States on
Wednesday, and opposition legislators accused her of interfering.
   Mrs. Thatcher, addressing Parliament, was cheered repeatedly by
Prime Minister Brian Mulroney's Conservatives as she also urged
NATO to modernize its nuclear arsenal despite Soviet moves toward
liberalization.
   ``On the basis of Britain's experience of joining the European
Community, you need have no fear that Canada's national personality
will be in any way diminished,'' the British Conservative Party
leader said of the trade agreement with Canada's giant southern
neighbor.
   ``Fifteen years of EC membership have left our people no less
British and no less proud of their history and independence,'' said
Mrs. Thatcher, who stopped in the capital for a day on the way home
from the seven-nation economic summit in Toronto.
   After the speech to a joint meeting of the House of Commons and
Senate, her second in five years, Mrs. Thatcher signed agreements
on drugs and air services with Mulroney.
   Ed Broadbent, leader of the opposition New Democratic Party,
said Mrs. Thatcher ``abused her diplomatic status'' by praising the
Free Trade Agreement before Parliament.
   The pact signed by Mulroney and President Reagan in January,
which must be approved by Parliament and Congress, would eliminate
trade barriers over a 10-year period and more closely integrate the
two economies.
   Opposition leaders claim Canada sacrifices soverignty in the
agreement, including control of its energy and natural resources.
   Along with opposition Liberals, the New Democrats also sat in
silent disapproval while Mrs. Thatcher urged NATO to modernize its
nuclear and conventional arsenals. The New Democrats oppose
Canadian membership in the 16-nation North Atlantic Treaty
Organization.
   Canadian television carried the address live, underlining Mrs.
Thatcher's high profile during the three-day summit of the United
States, France, Britain, West Germany, Italy, Japan and Canada.
   The drugs agreement was part of a British bid to get some 40
nations to sign a reciprocal agreement allowing for the seizure of
trafficking profits and making money laundering an offense. Britain
and the United States have signed a similar agreement.
</TEXT>
