<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WelfareOverhaul     06-22 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Welfare Overhaul,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Michel Requests House Vote On Senate-Passed Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Republican Leader Robert H. Michel on
Wednesday requested a House vote on a Senate-passed welfare
overhaul bill, saying there isn't enough time to work out a
compromise with a much more expensive House bill.
   ``Normally, I would not be inclined to suggest such a course of
action,'' Michel, R-Ill., said in a letter to House Speaker Jim
Wright, D-Texas.
   But Michel said ``the time and the opportunity for welfare
reform and the hope it holds out for many American families is
slipping beyond our grasp'' because the end of the 100th Congress
is approaching. He said the needs of welfare families could be best
served ``by setting the House bill aside.''
   But Rep. Tom Downey, D-N.Y., chairman of the House subcommittee
that handled the welfare bill, dismissed Michel's concerns as
``nonsense.''
   The $2.8 billion Senate bill and the $7 billion House bill, both
centered on a major new jobs, education and training program for
welfare recipients, are awaiting reconciliation in a House-Senate
conference committee.
   Michel said only 25 working days at most are left before the
last push of the Congress in September, after which members will
return home to campaign for re-election.
   ``Such constraints make the prospects for a successful
conference and a presidential signature very dim,'' Michel wrote.
   Michel cited last week's 93-3 vote for the Senate bill sponsored
by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., as evidence of a powerful
bipartisan consensus.
   He said the House, which passed its bill much more narrowly and
along party lines, could muster similar broad support ``if we can
bring ourselves to relinquish pride of authorship as well as some
both controversial and costly provisions.''
   ``I believe that I could convince the president to sign such a
bill,'' Michel said.
   Sticking points between the House and Senate negotiators are
likely to include:
   _A House provision giving states financial incentives to raise
cash benefits, not included in the Senate bill.
   _Cash benefits to poor two-parent families, which the House
requires year-round and the Senate requires for only six of any 12
months.
   _The amount of federal money available for the jobs, education
and training programs the states will have to set up. The Senate
bill starts at $500 million and moves gradually to $1 billion; the
House bill is uncapped.
   Downey said he and Moynihan ``are the best of friends and can
deal with these problems thoughtfully and quickly.''
   He added, ``There is no need for House to somehow suggest that
welfare reform can only be dealt with by the Senate. We have a
better bill and I think we will make their bill better.''
</TEXT>
