<1ST_LINE>u w AM-SpaceStation     06-22 0664</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Space Station,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Allots $10.7 Billion to NASA in Approving $60 Billion
Appropriations Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House beat back an attempt Wednesday to
divert $400 million from space station funds to social programs and
voted to appropriate $10.7 billion to run the National Aeronautics
and Space Administration next year.
   The measure still must pass the Senate, whose appropriations
committee on Wednesday also voted $10.7 billion for NASA. The
Senate bill, however, assumes that $600 million will be transferred
to the space station from unspent defense funds.
   That proposed fund transfer was called unacceptable in a letter
that President Reagan sent to Sen. John C. Stennis, D-Miss., and
Mark Hatfield, R-Ore., the chairman and ranking minority member of
the appropriations committee.
   At the same time, however, the president said that letting the
space station wither for lack of funds would be ``totally
unacceptable.''
   NASA had asked for $967 million in the fiscal year that begins
Oct. 1 to start the design phase of the $16 billion space station.
Under the bill passed by the House, the agency would get $902
million.
   The NASA funds are part of a $59.7 billion appropriation bill
for the Department of Housing and Urban Development and 15
independent agencies that passed the House 377-40.
   That appropriation is 4 percent, or $2.4 billion, more than the
current level and 2 percent, or $1 billion, more than the Reagan
administration had requested. It provides substantially more
funding than the administration requested for low-income housing
assistance, community development block grants, Environmental
Protection Agency construction grants and pollution control, and
veterans' medical care.
   Before voting on the appropriations bill, the House turned down,
256-166, an amendment by Rep. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y. that would
have distributed $400 million from space station funds among
programs for the homeless, veterans and the elderly, and urban
development.
   ``This amendment is a disaster,'' said Rep. Jack Brooks, D-Tex.,
whose district includes the Johnson Space Center.
   On the Senate side, one appropriations subcommittee had voted
only $200 million last week for starting the design phase of the
$16 billion space station, a level that would not allow the program
to go forward. On Tuesday, another Senate subcommittee acted to add
$600 million by transferring unspent defense funds.
   The full Appropriations Committee on Wednesday voted the $200
million. The committee was expected to approve the $600 million
transfer from defense funds on Thursday.
   ``I wish the administration would work with us on this,'' Sen.
Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, told reporters. ``Frankly, I think we have
a way of accomplishing the objective. I was very pleased to see the
House beat back an amendment that would have, in effect, gutted the
space station. It shows there is strong support for it.''
   In his letter, Reagan recalled that he had made the space
station a priority and that he had asked nearly a billion dollars
for it next year.
   ``This is not the time to turn our backs on the future or on
needed defense spending,'' the president said.
   Funding the station with only $200 million ``would be totally
unacceptable,'' Reagan wrote, adding, ``Equally unacceptable,
however, would be any plan that takes critical funds away from
another national priority, our country's defense budget.''
   He said such a money shift would be not only counterproductive
for both the defense and space station programs, ``but funding the
space station at the expense of national security violates the
budget agreement that the White House reached with the
congressional leadership last November.''
   The president offered no substitute money source.
   The United States is about to sign agreements with the European
Space Agency, Canada and Japan for their participation in the
station _ agreements that call for the partners to spend a total of
$7 billion.
   ``The Congress' failure now to fund adequately this vital
project will significantly undermine our national space effort and
raise serious questions about our reliability as a leader and
partner,'' Reagan said.
</TEXT>
