<2ND_LINE>AM-Baby Kidnapped, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0703,0639</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baby Returned to Mother One Day After Appeal</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with quotes from mother, second woman in
custody, no comment on motive, other detail. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MEG REYNOLDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGH POINT, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police returned a 4-day-old boy to his
joyful parents Wednesday, two days after a woman dressed as a nurse
carried him out of his mother's hospital room, authorities said.
   Renee McClure of Lexington clung tightly to her sleeping son,
Jason Ray McClure, and said she would not ``take my eyes off him''
after the infant was returned.
   The alleged abductor and a second woman were taken into custody,
police said.
   The baby was ``in perfect health,'' said Meredith Eanes,
spokeswoman for High Point Regional Hospital, where employees
cheered when the baby's return was announced.
   ``I had my (older) son on my lap,'' Mrs. McClure said at a news
conference after the baby was returned. ``He said, `Mommy, I want
to see my baby brother.'''
   ``It wasn't five minutes (later) they were coming around with my
baby,'' she said, her voice breaking. ``We're just so glad and so
thankful.''
   Brenda Joyce Nobles, 37, hometown unknown, was to be charged
with kidnapping, according to police Capt. Earl Whitaker. He would
not comment on a possible motive.
   Police said officers went to a house here after receiving a tip.
They decided to raid the house after a woman answered the door and
police could hear an infant crying in the background. They found
Ms. Nobles in a closet with the abducted baby, authorities said.
   The woman who answered the door was also taken into custody and
charges were expected, Whitaker said.
   Mrs. McClure, 27, had told police that a woman dressed as a
nurse entered her room at about 9:30 a.m. Monday, told her she
needed to weigh the baby and then carried him from the room.
   At the news conference, Mrs. McClure sat holding a sleeping
Jason on her lap, flanked by her husband, Richard; 3-year-old son,
Kevin; the baby's paternal grandparents and maternal grandmother;
and more than a dozen other relatives.
   The baby, wrapped in a blanket, wore a blue and white striped
hat, which his mother removed to show where the child's hair had
been cut during the abduction in an attempt to disguise him.
   Mrs. McClure said she had mixed feelings about Jason's kidnapper.
   ``I really feel sorry for her that she felt she had to go in a
hospital and take a baby that was not her own,'' she said.
   ``I'd like to ask her why,'' she said.
   ``We live in a rather cruel world,'' Mrs. McClure said. ``I was
just afraid she would hurt him.''
   Asked by photographers to hug the infant for a picture, Mrs.
McClure said, ``I sure don't mind that!''
   Wednesday was the due date for Jason, the baby's father said.
   Pat Pegram, executive secretary to the hospital president, said
the hospital operator ``was all choked up'' trying to make the
announcement on the hospital's public address system that the baby
was found. Staff members then began cheering.
   ``Everybody is joyous,'' she said. ``It's hard to conduct any
work. It's just been wild. We're happy. We're joyous.''
   The return of the baby came almost 24 hours after Mrs. McClure
made a tearful appeal for the return, saying, ``We love our son
very much and we need him so desperately.''
   The infant was the first baby born on Father's Day at the
hospital and was the subject of a feature story on a television
station.
   At least $9,000 in reward money was offered by police, the
hospital, the company where the baby's father works, and others,
according to Whitaker.
</TEXT>
