<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Terrorists     06-22 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Terrorists,0545</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Men Sentenced For Smuggling Bomb Into Vermont</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANICA KIRKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BURLINGTON, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Lebanese-born Canadians who the
government alleged were members of a Middle East terrorist group
were sentenced Wednesday to up to 16 years in prison for smuggling
a bomb into the United States.
   U.S. District Court Judge Albert Coffrin told the men it didn't
matter to him whether they belonged to an extremist political
party. But he said there was little doubt that the explosive device
the men had been carrying could have caused serious damage.
   ``The lethal potential, however, is clear,'' Coffrin said. ``Any
victim of a bombing is an innocent victim.''
   Coffrin sentenced George Younan and co-defendant Walid Kabbani
to 16 years each in federal prison. Walid Mourad, who pleaded
guilty before the others went to trial, was sentenced to eight
years in prison. The men faced maximum sentences of as much as 35
years.
   The defense attorneys claimed victory with the sentences, saying
they were less than 20-year terms that the government had offered
in a plea bargain that the defendants rejected.
   The attorneys had described their clients as bunglers rather
than terrorists, but even they say they have no idea what the men
were planning to do with the bomb. Younan and Kabbani pleaded
innocent but never testified in their trial.
   U.S. Attorney George Terwilliger III said the sentence was
appropriate, saying their acts attacked the country at its very
foundations and that ``violence in the pursuit of any goal is
unsatisfactory.''
   The three were arrested last October and charged with smuggling
a homemade bomb into the United States through Richford, a small
town on the Vermont-Canadian border.
   The U.S. government claimed the men were members of the Syrian
Social Nationalist Party. The party was founded in the 1930s and
was devoted to the formation of ``Greater Syria,'' which would have
united Lebanon and what was then Palestine, but is now Israel,
under Syrian hegemony.
   Floyd Clarke, an assistant director of the FBI's criminal
investigative division, said members of the group have claimed
responsibility for the 1982 assasination of Lebanese
President-elect Bashir Gemayel.
   Last month, Justice Department spokesman John Russell said the
men were believed to be the first alleged Middle Eastern terrorists
arrested in the United States carrying explosives.
   Attorneys for Kabbani and Mourad have denied their clients were
members of the SSNP. A cousin of Younan's said Younan belonged to
the party but denied that it was a terrorist group.
   None of the three defendents addressed the judge Wednesday.
Their attorneys said the government's allegations of their
political affiliations were greatly exaggerated.
   ``He says `I'm not a terrorist,' '' Kabbani's attorney Mark
Keller said. ``He simply says I know what I am ... He asked me not
to beg on his behalf, not to grovel on his behalf.''
   But Terwilliger dismissed defense claims that the men were
amateurs.
   ``There is a real naivete at work when you look at these
individuals as bumblers or amateurs or whatnot or that they don't
look like terrorists,'' he said. ``What do terrorists look like?
What someone out of central casting out of Hollywood would decide?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
