<DOCNO> AP880622-0241 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 2125EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Aldicarb 1stLd-Writethru a0699 06-22 0798</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Aldicarb, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0699,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA Moves to Order Tighter Controls Over Pesticide</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf to clarify why states were selected for EPA
action</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In its first proposal aimed at protecting
groundwater from pesticides, the Environmental Protection Agency
said Wednesday it will require at least 10 states to adopt
additional controls on highly toxic aldicarb or lose use of that
chemical.
   Aldicarb, sold under the trade name Temik, has been found in
groundwater in 16 states, in 11 of them in concentrations above
what EPA considers safe.
   The proposal published for public comment contained an
alternative that could require as many as 24 states to act.
   The 24 were not identified, but EPA said the 10 from which it
plans to require ``pesticide management plans'' are Pennsylvania,
Michigan, North Dakota, Georgia and Alabama, where aldicarb has not
been found; and Maine, New York, Wisconsin, Minnesota and Florida,
where it has been found in concentrations above EPA's ``health
advisory'' of 10 parts per billion _ sometimes 50 times greater.
   But EPA considers the 10 states it selected the most vunerable
because of the characteristics of the groundwater and the pattern
of aldicarb use in those states. The proposal comes as a result of
EPA's draft groundwater strategy, which would leave most key
decisions to the states.
   Aldicarb also has been found in California, Massachusetts, North
Carolina, New Jersey, Rhode Island and Virgina in concentrations
above 10 ppb and in Arizona, Arkansas, Oregon, Texas and Washington
below that. Overall, one-third of some 35,000 groundwater samples
tested by EPA contained some aldicarb.
   Florida, New York and Wisconsin have aggressive aldicarb
programs of their own, said John A. Moore, EPA's assistant
administrator for pesticides.
   The only manufacturer, Rhone-Poulenc Ag Co. of Research Triangle
Park, N.C., would be required to monitor groundwater in 16 other
states where EPA considers it highly vulnerable.
   Those states are Connecticut, Hawaii, Idaho, Illinois, Indiana,
Kansas, Massachusetts, Missouri, Montana, Nebraska, New Hampshire,
Ohio, Rhode Island, South Carolina, South Dakota and Vermont.
   The draft would forbid use of aldicarb within 300 feet of a
well, and would add label warnings that would force state training
programs for applicators to discuss groundwater.
   EPA said it was still checking residues on food, but
Rhone-Poulenc said a new study showed ``residues were rarely
present.''
   The company said EPA's plan reflects ``sound principles for
drinking water protection,'' and said it would cooperate.
   The U.S. Public Interest Research Group, which frequently argues
for tighter pesticide controls, attacked the agency's plan as
``insufficient to prevent contamination of future drinking water.''
Much of the criticism was directed at the agency's draft
groundwater strategy, which would permit states to decide that some
groundwater should not be protected.
   Asked if states could submit plans that permit aldicarb
contamination of groundwater, Moore said, ``I would say yes. But we
would require them to clearly state that to the citizens of the
state, and the citizens would have to have a chance to comment.''
   If a state refuses to submit a plan, ``I would say we would
cancel the use of adlicarb in that state,'' Moore told reporters.
   EPA's decision is not a ``license to pollute'' up to 10 ppb,
Moore said. `If you've got 10 ppb, you've failed. I would expect at
1 ppb (about the limit of detection) ... you would kick in step two
of the management plan, more heroic surveillance, additional
restrictions on use, and things like that.''
   State plans might also ban use in certain areas or at certain
times like rainy months, reduce per-acre use, limit frequency of
application or other measures.
   Because their own wells are often contaminated, ``There is such
an interest on the part of people that use this, I think (the
chance of compliance) is very high compared with a lot of things we
do,'' Moore said.
   EPA expects to adopt aldicarb requirements in about a year and
state plans under it should take effect two years from then.
   As much as 5.7 million pounds of aldicarb are used each year to
protect potatoes, citrus, peanuts and other crops against insects,
root worms and mites. EPA said banning aldicarb could cost farmers
$135 million.
   Widespread contamination of groundwater, frequently at 200 ppb
or more, led Suffolk County on New York's Long Island to ban its
use, and 3,100 homes have costly activated carbon filters on their
wells.
   More than 1,000 people were reported poisoned in 1985 in seven
western states and Canada from California watermelons contaminated
with aldicarb. Two babies were stillborn.
   Aldicarb breaks down in soil in a few weeks, but in groundwater
it can last decades.
   It works by inhibiting nerve transmission and can cause
digestive upset, dehydration, blurred vision, disorientation,
seizures, unconsciousness and eventually death.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
