<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DoctorWoes     06-22 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Doctor Woes,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Medical And Financial Problems End Bid To Bring Doctor To Vandalia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VANDALIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of this southern Illinois town
thought they were building for the future when they loaned $63,000
to attract a new doctor, but the intended doctor developed cancer
and filed for bankruptcy before completing his training.
   ``I'm losing a lot of sleep about some of these widows that
helped recruit a doctor,'' said James Rowland, 45. ``I just can't
pay them back.
   ``I just don't know what to say.''
   The town has other doctors, but residents aren't happy about
losing the money.
   ``Sometimes you win and sometimes you lose,'' said investor
Edward D. Taylor Sr., adding that the city ``just had some bad
luck.''
   Residents of this town of 5,100 contributed $63,000 in loans and
outright donations to the Vandalia Civic Advancement Association to
attract Rowland. At least 45 investors loaned between $250 and
$10,000 each.
   The association loaned the money to Rowland, who came to town in
1980 with his wife, Ann, a registered nurse with the county health
department, and two daughters aged 10 and 13.
   However, Rowland developed cancer in his left kidney and had it
removed by July 1983. Cancer has spread since into his bones and
cannot be treated. Rowland believes he has little chance for
recovery.
   The illness kept him from completing a residency program or
repaying his loans. A former chemical engineer in Pittsburgh,
Rowland enrolled at the American University of the Caribbean for
four years or medical school in 1975. He said he subsequently
received clinical training at three Chicago hospitals.
   The civic association has no cash to repay the investors,
President Steve Stombaugh said. It tried to recoup the money by
suing Rowland in Fayette County Circuit Court in April for
$131,151.76 to cover the loans and interest.
   But Rowland stalled the lawsuit by filing for bankruptcy May 18.
His first meeting with creditors is set for Thursday at the Keller
Ramada Inn in Effingham.
   ``There's no argument I owe the money,'' Rowland said. ``They
raised it in good faith and I came here in good faith. But I had an
illness.''
   Documents on file in U.S. District Court in East St. Louis show
Rowland has earned no income since 1986. His wife made $22,684 in
1987.
   About the only way investors appear likely to recoup their money
is if Rowland dies. The civic association has $100,000 in life
insurance on Rowland and his wife, he said.
   They didn't take out disability insurance.
</TEXT>
