<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0701,0588</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strike Fading in Disputed Southern Region; Tatars Strike For
Homeland</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Tatar strike, more on
Armenians; recast for clarity and to TRIM. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethnic Armenians in Nagorno-Karabakh began
returning to work Wednesday after a month-long strike, but held
another demonstration for the disputed territory's annexation to
Soviet Armenia, residents said.
   In another ethnic disturbance in the southern Soviet Union, a
dissident source said at least 5,000 Crimean Tatars were on strike
to demand the return of the homeland that dictator Josef Stalin
took from them in World War II.
   Armenians make up more than three-quarters of Nagorno-Karabakh's
160,000 residents. Some of them apparently were swayed to end the
strike by the legislature's request Tuesday that the territory be
made independent until its future is settled.
   A resident of Stepanakert, the territorial capital, said about
half of the original 30,000 strikers continued the walkout.
   Agitation began early this year in Armenia and Nagorno-Karabakh
for annexation of the territory, which was assigned to the
neighboring republic of Azerbaijan in 1923. Azerbaijan has refused
to give it up.
   The chairman of the legislature read the resolution on
television Wednesday in Stepanakert and answered questions from a
reporter in the studio and from people who telephoned, the resident
said on condition of anonymity.
   He said the chairman urged people to return to work. Other
residents have said the strike and daily street demonstrations
began May 23, shutting down most retail and agricultural production
in the region.
   A strike also began this month in Yerevan, capital of Armenia,
in support of the demand for annexation. The newspaper Socialist
Industry reported Wednesday that the strike was ending and said
Yerevan factory managers had urged employees to make up for lost
time by working Saturdays.
   Not all was quiet in Yerevan. A dissident who lives in Moscow,
Valery Senderov, said up to 10,000 people gathered outside KGB
headquarters in Yerevan on Wednesday evening to demand the release
of a jailed Armenian activist.
   Paruyr Ayrikyan was arrested in March. He led an Armenian
nationalist group and had informed foreign journalists about
demonstrations in February.
   According to the resident of Stepanakert, ethnic Armenians held
another demonstration Wednesday but organizers decided to stop the
protests until Moscow acts on the legislature's request. The
Kremlin has not said whether it will decide the fate of
Nagorno-Karabakh.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov told reporters
Wednesday: ``We have an address to the Supreme Soviet on the side
of Armenia, and on the side of Azerbaijan. We can guess this
question will be on the agenda of the Presidium of the Supreme
Soviet, but it won't happen overnight.''
   The Supreme Soviet is the national parliament and the Presidium
its executive council.
   Dissident historian Roy Medvedyev told reporters Wednesday the
territory is ``a historic part of Armenia'' that ``should belong to
Armenia.''
   In a telephone interview about the Tatar strike, Alexander
Podrabinek, an editor of the dissident journal Express-Chronicle,
said Tatars met on Sunday at Nizhnaya Bakanka near Krasnodar to
plan it, then returned to their homes throughout the region to
begin the walkout.
   Tatars are Turkic-speaking descendants of Mongols. According to
Podrabinek, the strikers plan to stay off the job until the
national government returns the homeland taken from them because of
alleged collaboration with the German invaders in World War II.
   He said police were not interfering.
</TEXT>
