<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NorthernIreland     06-22 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northern Ireland,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mourners Pay Tribute To Six Soldiers Killed In IRA Blast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBURN, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 8,000 people gathered
Wednesday night to pay tribute to six British soldiers killed by an
Irish Republican Army bomb explosion.
   In another development, a sniper shot a British soldier in the
arm Wednesday in Belfast, but the man was not seriously wounded,
police said. The outlawed IRA claimed responsibility for the
shooting.
   Security forces checked all cars entering this town seven miles
from Belfast, and armed soldiers patrolled from rooftops as
townspeople gathered for a memorial service in Lisburn's market
square.
   Mourners, many weeping, laid wreaths at a simple monument by the
traffic lights where the soldiers' van blew up June 15 as they were
returning to their barracks after taking part in a charity footrace.
   A bugler played taps as Mayor Billy Bleakes laid a wreath on
behalf of Lisburn, home of the British army headquarters in
Northern Ireland.
   The Rev. Howard Cromie, former Presbyterian moderator for the
province, observed that both Protestants and Roman Catholics turned
out for the service.
   ``There is no difference between Catholic tears and Protestant
tears when tragedy strikes,'' he said.
   ``The way forward,'' Cromie added, ``is certainly not down the
blind alley of retaliation, reprisals; for that is something which
must be repudiated in the strongest possible terms.''
   Three of the six soldiers killed in the bombing were buried with
full military honors Wednesday in their hometowns in mainland
Britain.
   In claiming responsibility for the bombing, the IRA vowed to
wage ``unceasing war'' against British security forces in the
province.
   The guerrilla group, in its modern form, has been fighting for
nearly 20 years to force the British from Northern Ireland and
unite the Protestant-dominated province with the mainly Catholic
Irish Republic to the south.
   Earlier Wednesday, Sir John Hermon, the province's police chief
for eight years, announced that he will retire next year.
   Hermon, 59, chief constable of the Royal Ulster Constabulary
could have stayed on until 1994 _ the mandatory retirement age is
65 _ but he said that after 38 years on the force he felt it was
time to retire.
   He said his decision had nothing to do with allegations that his
force operated a shoot-to-kill policy six years ago.
   John Stalker, a police officer from England appointed to inquire
into the six killings by the police, was suddenly pulled out of
Northern Ireland before completing his task.
   Stalker later quit the police and wrote a book claiming Hermon
refused to cooperate with him and that there was a conspiracy to
conceal the truth.
   At his news conference, Hermon repeated his earlier dismissal of
the book as ``rubbish.''
</TEXT>
