<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-22 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hot Enough For You?</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Summer heat grilled the nation Wednesday from the central Plains
eastward to the mid-Atlantic states and the Carolinas, with
temperatures in the 90s. Two dozen cities, from Des Moines to
Washington, D.C., had record highs for the date.
   A few cities reached the 100-degree mark, including Washington,
D.C., Philadelphia. Tucson, Ariz., which reached an all-time record
high of 112 degrees Tuesday, reached 108 degrees along with Phoenix.
   Pittsburgh had a 98-degree reading; Indianapolis reached 99
degress; and Milwaukee had its 10th day this month of 90-degree
readings; normally, the city reaches 90 degrees only 8 times in an
entire year.
   A Canadian cold front promised cooler weather across the Great
Lakes, Ohio Valley, New England and the mid-Atlantic regions. Early
afternoon temperatures behind the front were 10 to 15 degrees
cooler than Tuesday over the Dakotas, the upper Mississippi Valley
and the upper Great Lakes.
   Showers and thunderstorms developed along the front from New
York across lower Michigan and southern Iowa into southwest
Nebraska, but rainfall was not nearly enough to break the drought
in the Plains and the Ohio Valley.
   Other showers and thunderstorms were widely scattered across the
Southeast from the Carolinas to Florida and westward along the Gulf
Coast to Texas, as well as over the central Rockies and portions of
the Southwest,
   Temperatures along the northern Pacific Coast were only in the
50s and low 60s as cloudy skies and cool winds off the Pacific kept
temperatures down.
   The low temperature for the nation Wednesday morning was 42
degrees at Truckee, Calif. Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m.
EDT ranged from 56 degrees at Crescent City, Calif., to 108 degrees
at both Phoenix and Tucson, Ariz.
   In the national weather forecast for Thursday, showers and
thunderstorms will be scattered from the upper Texas coast to
Florida. Isolated to widely scattered showers and thunderstorms
will develop from the mid-Atlantic states, across the Ohio and
Tennessee valleys to the mid Mississippi Valley, and the northern
central Rockies. Isolated afternoon and evening thunderstorms will
develop across the remainder of the Southeast and eastern Texas.
   High temperatures will again be in the 90s to near 100 degrees
across much of the nation; between 100 and 105 over eastern
montana; 100 to 115 for the desert Southwest and Southern and
central California valleys; in the 70s and 80s from New England,
across the Ohio Valley and Great Lakes to the upper Mississippi
Valley, the Pacific Northwest and along the California coast. A few
locations across upper Michigan will remain in the 60s.
</TEXT>
