<HEAD>Key Navy Official Is Cooperating with Authorities in Defense Probe</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Defense Probe Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   James Gaines, a key Navy procurement official
whose offices were searched last week, is cooperating with the
government in the Pentagon bribery probe, sources familiar with the
investigation said Wednesday night.
   Another Pentagon official whose offices were searched, Victor
Cohen, also is negotiating with the government on whether to
cooperate with authorities, said the sources, speaking on condition
of anonymity.
   The two-year probe included wiretaps on the telephones of Gaines
and Cohen.
   Shortly after the investigation became public June 14, federal
investigators sounded out Gaines about the possibility of
delivering information to the government, said the sources.
   Gaines made an appointment to hire a Washington-area defense
lawyer, but then abruptly canceled the meeting after getting a call
from a federal investigator who told him that ``you have until 9
a.m. tomorrow to decide whose side you're on,'' according to one
source. Gaines decided several days ago to cooperate, said the
sources.
   ABC News reported that the government has made no deal with
Gaines for lenient treatment in a possible prosecution, but that
such an arrangement is expected later. ABC News also reported that
another key figure in the probe, former Pentagon-official-turned
consultant Melvyn Paisley, has so far refused to help authorities.
   Paisley's attorney, Lawrence Barcella, refused to comment.
   Gaines was deputy assistant Navy secretary for acquisition
management while Cohen was deputy assistant Air Force secretary in
charge of buying tactical command, control, communications and
computer systems. Because of the bribery investigation, both men
have been reassigned to jobs having nothing to do with procurement.
   The offices of both men were searched and sealed last week by
FBI agents as investigators obtained 38 search warrants in 12
states to seize documents at the offices of 15 defense contractors
as well as consultants and Pentagon personnel.
</TEXT>
