<HEAD>House of Commons Approves Accord Recognizing Quebec As Distinct
Society</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House of Commons gave overwhelming approval
Wednesday to a 1987 accord recognizing Quebec as a ``distinct
society'' and bringing the French-majority province back into the
Constitution.
   But the vote of 200 to 7 was not the final hurdle for the
controversial Meech Lake Accord, signed by the federal government
and all 10 provinces at Meech Lake, Quebec.
   The historic change also requires ratification by the 10
provinces and so far only five have done so. At least two have
demanded amendments before putting the accord to a vote.
   Eighty-one percent of Quebec's population speaks French, the
province's official language. Quebec has its own system of civil
law established by its French founders, and proponents of the 1987
accord want constitutional guarantees their legal and social
traditions will not be altered by the federal government.
   Prominent opponents of the pact include former Liberal Prime
Minister Pierre Trudeau who claims it will erode Ottawa's power and
lead to the disintegration of the Canadian federation.
   Conservative Prime Minister Brian Mulroney, a native of Quebec,
has made a constitutional settlement with Quebec one of his main
priorities. He says arguments over special rights for other
minority regions, native groups and women can be settled later.
   The Liberal-dominated Senate, an appointed body, held up the
accord for months but all of its proposed changes were defeated
when the measure was sent back to the elected House of Commons.
   The leaders of both opposition parties, John Turner of the
Liberals and Ed Broadbent of the socialist New Democrats, voted for
the accord and persuaded most of their followers to do likewise.
   However, members from the Northwest Territories and Yukon
Territory voted against Meech Lake because it will make it more
difficult for their remote regions to become full provinces.
   Under the accord, the approval of all provinces will be needed
before the territories can obtain provincehood. At present, it only
requires approval by two-thirds of the provinces containing at
least 50 percent of the Canadian population.
   The House of Commons originally ratified the accord 242-16 in
October but the Senate sent it back with amendments, requiring a
second final vote.
   Quebec has boycotted constitutional affairs since 1981 when
Trudeau repatriated the Constitution from Britain and added a new
Charter of Rights and Freedoms, but failed to recognize Quebec's
distinct culture.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
