<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Yugoslavia-Strike     06-22 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Strike,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands of Workers Protest Low Wages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 5,000 striking auto workers
rallied for a second day Wednesday to protest low wages, the state
Tanjug news agency reported.
   Workers of the TAM company, Yugoslavia's largest producers of
trucks and vehicles, gathered on a square in the northern city of
Maribor in Slovenia to demand a 50-percent pay increase, the news
agency said. They were joined by workers from a nearby textile
mill, it said.
   The protesters, who staged another rally on Tuesday, elected a
strike committee to voice their grievances after Slovenia's Vice
Premier Janez Bohoric told them Wednesday that ``nobody has the
money needed to fulfill your demands,'' the news agency said.
   Last month the Yugoslav government linked wages to productivity
as part of an economic recovery program designed to cut inflation,
currently running at 170 percent, and overcome a severe economic
crisis.
   The austerity measures have sparked a wave of labor unrest.
   In Belgrade Wednesday, Vice Premier Janez Zemljaric attended a
meeting at an agricultural machinery plant whose striking workers
staged a noisy demonstration last Friday in front of Parliament,
protesting low wages and demanding government assistance for their
firm, Zmaj.
   Zemljaric reportedly said the government was determined to
introduce a more market-oriented economy, adding that ``the
consequences of the market forces (for loss-making companies) will
be very serious.''
   An estimated quarter of all Yugoslav enterprises are loss-makers
that have so far been kept afloat with substantial government
grants.
   Under the terms of an agreement signed with the International
Monetary Fund, the Yugoslav government has pledged to phase out the
subsidies. Officials claim there is no alternative if the country
is to repay its $21 billion foreign debt.
</TEXT>
