<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Liberia-Reporter     06-22 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Liberia-Reporter,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Liberia Bans Washington Post Reporter For Story On Graft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONROVIA, Liberia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has banned a Washington
Post reporter from this West African country because of a critical
report he wrote on graft, but the correspondent said Wednesday he
stands by his story.
   Information Minister Emmanuel Bowier called the May 29 article
``erroneous and misleading.''
   But Bowier said it was not surprising because of ``extremely
cordial relations'' that existed between the newspaper and former
President William Tolbert, assassinated in an April 1980 coup led
by Gen. Samuel K. Doe.
   A person who answered the telephone at the office of Washington
Post managing editor Leonard Downie on Wednesday said comment would
come only from Katharine Graham, the newspaper's chairman of the
board. A message for Mrs. Graham to return a call was not answered.
   ``I stand by my story,'' Post correspondent Blaine Harden told
The Associated Press in Nairobi, where he is based.
   Harden, who has reported in Africa since 1985, wrote an article
describing how Doe and his close associates allegedly circumvent
U.S.-imposed spending controls. American experts were invited by
Doe's government to curb crippling official corruption.
   The report quoted Liberian businessmen as arguing the invitation
is another example of Doe's manipulation of Washington.
   At a news conference Monday, Bowier denied Harden's assertions
that 17 American economists, accountants and consultants hold
deputy ministerial rank and cosigned government checks.
   But a U.S. Information Services document explaining the two-year
$18.4 million ``economic stabilization project'' said the
technocrats ``will be assigned at the deputy minister or equivalent
level and will co-approve revenue and expenditure documentation.''
   Bowier said Harden's article was part of ``blatant distortions
and the misinformation campaign launched against the Doe
administration'' because he said Mrs. Graham was decorated by
Tolbert's government.
</TEXT>
