<2ND_LINE>AM-Melton Trial,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Melton Found Guilty In Mardi Gras Kidnapping Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BILOXI, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New Orleans construction worker was found
guilty on a federal kidnapping charge Wednesday in his trial for
the Mardi Gras abduction of a North Carolina woman who died trying
to escape from him.
   The jury deliberated for three hours in U.S. District Court
before returning the guilty verdict against Cyril Melton, 27, who
faces a maximum sentence of life in prison. No sentencing date was
set.
   Prosecutors contended Melton posed as a cab driver in New
Orleans Feb. 14 and persuaded Marjorie Cox, 35, of Highlands, N.C.
and a male companion to let him give them a ride to Gulfport.
Melton was not driving a cab, however.
   Melton took the witness stand in his own behalf Tuesday and was
cross-examined by prosecutors Wednesday morning.
   Melton testified that he tricked Cox's companion into getting
out of the car during the trip and was driving alone with Cox when
she jumped out and was killed.
   Melton said he tried to convince Cox that he had no intention of
hurting her and was looking for a phone so she could get another
ride. Prosecutors said Melton had other motives and passed several
phones before she jumped.
   Melton said Tuesday, the second day of in his trial, his car was
traveling about 65 mph along Interstate 10 and had just passed a
tractor-trailer rig when Cox jumped and was killed by oncoming
traffic.
   Melton said he continued driving because ``I didn't think the
lady got hurt.''
   Police said Cox died after being struck by several vehicles. Her
body was found Feb. 15.
   Prosecutors say a Hancock County grand jury may consider a state
manslaughter charge in addition to the kidnapping charge.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
