<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Panama     06-22 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noriega Denies Cuban, Libyan Soldiers In Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega on
Wednesday again denied reports that Cuban or Libyan soldiers are in
Panama, saying his own armed forces have no need for them.
   Rumors of Cuban or Libyan troops in Panama have circulated here,
in Washington and elsewhere for more than two months, but U.S.
officials have tended to discount them.
   The latest report of armed Cuban involvement in Panama surfaced
in the United States earlier this week in a syndicated column by
Rowland Evans and Robert Novak. The writers quoted unidentified
intelligence sources.
   But Noriega scoffed at the report. He called alleged incursions
by Cuban commandos onto U.S. military bases near Panama City
earlier this year ``the phenomenon of the palm trees.''
   Panama's government-controlled press has long referred to the
incidents as the ``battle of the palms,'' claiming that U.S.
Marines shot at shadows and waving palm trees.
   ``There are no Cuban commandos, no Libyans or other foreigners
in this territory,'' Noriega said, ``because the (Panamanian)
Defense Forces do not need them.''
   Noriega spoke at the closing session of the Third Assembly of
Anti-Imperialist Organizations of the Caribbean and Central America.
   The more than 100 delegates attending the three-day meeting
adopted a resolution denouncing the ``aggressive and destabilizing
campaign of the Reagan administration against the people and
constitutional government of Panama.''
   Washington has been seeking Noriega's ouster since last fall.
The general, who is chief of the Defense Forces and Panama's de
facto ruler, was indicted on federal narcotics charges in Florida
earlier this year.
</TEXT>
