<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Lakers-Mania     06-22 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lakers-Mania,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Confetti-Covered Fans Applaud World Champions _ Again</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE MANNING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hanging from windows and balconies, perched
on trees and ladders and eight-deep on downtown sidewalks,
thousands of Lakers fans applauded basketball's world champions
Wednesday during a victory parade.
   The single-word headline in Lakers purple said it all:
``CHAMPS!'' splashed across the top of the Los Angeles Herald
Examiner in 2{-inch type, and the parade route was clogged with
vendors hawking T-shirts, pennants and hats.
   The Lakers, with a 108-105 victory over the Detroit Pistons in
Game 7 of the National Basketball Association championship series
Tuesday night, became the first team to win back-to-back titles
since the 1969 Celtics.
   Gia Neil of Panorama City, wearing one purple sock and one gold
sock and waving pompons, carried a homemade sign that read: ``Back
to Back, Mission Accomplished.''
   The traditional downtown parade in their honor drew more than
40,000 Laker lovers, most wearing hats, T-shirts or socks in bold
purple and gold team colors. Others carried signs, banners and
balloons, waved towels and munched on purple cotton candy.
   ``It's party time once again,'' Earvin ``Magic'' Johnson told
the cheering throng at City Hall. ``How do you like us now? Let's
do it again next year.''
   ``We've got the best team and God knows we've got the best
fans,'' said James Worthy, the most valuable player in the
championship game.
   Byron Scott urged fans to join him in chanting ``Repeat, Repeat,
Repeat,'' echoing cheers that rippled across the crowd as Mayor Tom
Bradley declared it Lakers Day in the city.
   Police spokesman Don Lawrence, who provided the crowd estimates,
described the crowd as well-behaved.
   Chick Hearn, the 68-year-old ``Voice of the Lakers,'' emceed the
rally. It was during a similar celebration last year that Riley
``guaranteed'' a repeat championship.
   Kevin Anthony, 33, of Long Beach waved a banner that matched his
shirt, shoes, armbands, hat, pins and towel while carrying his
8-year-old son, Kareem Jamaal on his shoulders.
   He said he was at the tribute ``to cheer. I love it. I've been
with them since 1980. We should have more next year and the year
after that.''
   His son was named after Lakers Captain, 41-year-old Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar and former Laker Jamaal Wilkes.
   As the Lakers floats approached fans along the one-mile route to
City Hall, they were greeted by the slow clap, a team tradition.
Shredded paper rained on the players and they waved, passing to
cheers, hoots and hollers. The fans danced in the streets and
swayed back and forth to carry on another Laker tradition despite
the absence of music until they got to City Hall.
   The championship game drew a huge television audience, with the
final game seen in an estimated 20.2 million homes, according to
the Nielsen ratings.
</TEXT>
