<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Britain-GloriousRevolution     06-22 0134</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Britain-Glorious Revolution,0139</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>English Revolution Tricentenary Opens At Buckingham Palace</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The tricentenary celebration of England's Glorious
Revolution of 1688 opened Wednesday as the English Chamber
Orchestra and a cast of singers performed in the ballroom of
Buckingham Palace.
   Prince Charles hosted the performance of British composer Henry
Purcell's ``Dido and Aeneas,'' one of England's most important
17th-century operas, while the British Broadcasting Corp. made
history as the first network to transmit live from the palace.
   Princess Margrit, sister of Queen Beatrix of the Netherlands,
was also present, helping to commemorate the June 1688 arrival of
the Dutch Protestant William of Orange and his English wife Mary on
English soil.
   William and Mary unseated the Roman Catholic James II from the
English throne and were jointly crowned in 1689.
</TEXT>
