<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 2304EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 2ndLd-Writethru a0783 06-22 0755</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0783,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Dodges Veep Questions; Hails Welfare Programs</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS graf 11, According to, to change tense</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis said Wednesday that Jesse
Jackson's lack of government experience did ``not necessarily''
rule him out for the No. 2 spot on the Democratic ticket and said
his search for a running mate would expand beyond people who have
been asked for background information.
   Meanwhile, Dukakis was endorsed by a former Democratic rival _
Sen. Joseph Biden of Delaware, who dropped out of the race last
fall, before the primary season began.
   Biden quit amid allegations of plagiarism and puffing up his
academic record. Dukakis' top aide, John Sasso, resigned after
admitting to being the source of an ``attack video'' showing clips
of Biden giving a speech that had been largely lifted from from
British politician Neil Kinnock.
   At a Boston news conference, the Massachusetts governor was
peppered with questions about his search for a running mate but
offered little insight into the process.
   ``I don't think it's helpful ... to do it with press conferences
at the end of the driveway everytime you talk to somebody,''
Dukakis told a Statehouse news conference. ``We've just begun the
process.''
   Dukakis danced around repeated questions about whether Jackson's
lack of government experience and whether polls showing that
Jackson might hurt the Democratic ticket would affect his choice.
   ``I don't know that you have to have held public office to in
fact be qualified to be president,'' said Dukakis. ``It helps.''
   He said Jackson was under ``very serious consideration.''
   Later, pressed about whether he thought Jackson would be a
liability, Dukakis said:
   ``I'm not going to be checking a lot of polls, believe me. ...
We all have our strengths and our weaknesses.''
   According to sources, Florida Sen. Bob Graham and Jackson have
been asked to supply the Dukakis campaign with background and
financial information. Campaign sources indicated similar requests
were made of at least several more members of Congress, including
Ohio Sen. John Glenn and Georgia Sen. Sam Nunn. Spokesmen for Glenn
and Nunn declined comment.
   One source said House Majority Leader Thomas Foley of Washington
was also among those being asked for background information but
another source said no decision had been made regarding Foley.
   One senator considered mentioned frequently as a possible
Dukakis running mate, New Jersey's Bill Bradley, said through a
spokesman that he had informed the Dukakis campaign that he was not
interested.
   New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley's office said Tuesday that it had
not been asked to supply the Dukakis campaign with background
information.
   Dukakis answered with a quick ``no'' when asked if that meant
Bradley would not be considered. He added that Bradley, who has
said he is not interested in the vice presidency, ``has not told me
personally'' he did not want to be considered.
   But Bradley spokesman Nick Donatiello said that Bradley had
``made it absolutely clear, both publicly and privately'' to
Dukakis campaign chairman Paul Brountas that he was not interested
in the No. 2 slot on the ticket. Brountas is heading the search for
Dukakis.
   ``He's absolutely unambiguous about this,'' Donatiello said.
   Dukakis was asked about a statement by Jackson's campaign
manager that his rival would not concede the nomination before the
roll call vote at the convention.
   ``It's over,'' Dukakis responded, adding: ``That's a decision he
has to make.''
   Dukakis continued to defend himself against certain Republican
nominee George Bush's attacks on a Massachusetts furlough program
that allowed for the release of a murderer who then escaped while
on furlough and raped a Maryland woman.
   Dukakis noted that he had since tightened eligibility
requirements for furloughs to exclude first-degree murderers and
that 45 states and the federal government have some form of
furlough system.
   He said Bush was focusing on the furlough-escape case because he
had no record of his own to promote on crime issues.
   Before the news conference, Dukakis attended a celebration
marking the graduation of the 50,000 participants in Employment
Training, a Massachusetts program that provides job training for
welfare recipients. He said the program had helped reduce the
state's welfare caseload by 35 percent in five years.
   ``I think of all the things that I've been involved in, ET is at
the top of the list,'' Dukakis said.
   He called the welfare reform bill before Congress a ``major,
major step forward,'' and took credit for job training provisions
he said were modeled after the Massachusetts program.
</TEXT>
