<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 2356EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater     06-22 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Green Card' Opens American Theater Exchange</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   How many ways are there to look at immigration?
Playwright Joanne Akalaitis has found a great many and written them
into ``Green Card'' as scenes and vignettes.
   It's interesting and well played by a versatile cast that keeps
switching accents and becoming new characters. But the production
doesn't build the way a play with a narrative line does. Impact
also is lessened because the evening has an over-all sense of
classroom learning about it.
   ``Green Card,'' first performed at the Mark Taper Forum in Los
Angeles in 1986, is now running at the off-Broadway Joyce Theater.
The play is part of the First New York International Festival of
the Arts and is the first entry in this summer's American Theater
Exchange at the Joyce.
   ``Green Card'' opens with Jesse Borrego as a stand-up comedian
specializing in racial-insult remarks. From that startling
beginning, ``Green Card'' moves to the expected _ a Jewish
immigrant at Ellis Island telling of Lithuania's pogroms, then
running a sewing machine in New York and finally proclaiming ``next
to work the most important thing is learning.''
   Dana Lee appears from time to time as a well-dressed Vietnamese
Marshall Nguyen Cao Ky, who says he went on the lecture circuit
because his agent told him that he'd only be good for a year. A
young woman lists events of her day as an illegal alien, cleaning
houses. A boy tells of being arrested as an illegal and of being
held and mistreated before deportation to San Salvador.
   Repeatedly, somebody says, ``He was a victim of spirits of this
country. Last night when he died he was watching the Incredible
Hulk.'' Light touches are inserted by two women who cross the stage
burbling Beverly Hills rich matron chitchat: ``He combines massage
with mantra.''
   Act 2 becomes much more heavy, with a history of Vietnam's
conquerors, a travelogue of Cambodia, faded Vietnam War films, a
lecture on the Latin American ``disappeared'' and torture methods.
   Miss Akalaitis seems in Act 1 to disparage the values of
Americans whose ancestors immigrated some time ago and to say that
America is better than the other countries she mentions in Act 2.
   The playwright, who also directed, developed her material over a
two-year period. With a Rockefeller Foundation
playwrights-in-residence grant, she lived among Hispanic,
Vietnamese, Salvadoran, Panamanian and Indo-Chinese immigrants in
Los Angeles. The daughter of immigrants, she grew up in a large
Lithuanian neighborhood in Chicago.
   The other actors in ``Green Card'' are Abraham Alvarez, Raye
Birk, Rosalind Chao, Pamela Dunlap, George Galvan, Jim Ishida,
Josie Kim, Alma Martinez and Jessie Nelson.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880622-0266 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 2322EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-ForgeryTrial     06-22 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Forgery Trial,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mountain, Company Found Guilty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEN HERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN MARCOS, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Houston political consultant and his
firm were convicted Wednesday of forging signatures on petitions
that put former Delaware Gov. Pete du Pont on the state's
Republican Party presidential primary ballot.
   Jurors found the consultant, Rocky Mountain, and his firm,
Southern Political Consulting, Inc., guilty of 38 counts each of
misdemeanor forgery after about four hours of deliberations.
Punishment phase of the trial was to begin Thursday.
   Mountain, 27, allegedly masterminded a ``forgery party'' at
which workers signed phony signatures on petitions to put du Pont
on the March 8 primary, which was won by Vice President George
Bush. Du Pont withdrew from the race.
   Mountain, who testified he did not intend the petitions to be
submitted, faced a fine of up to $2,000 per counts and a year in
jail. The company faced a fine of up to $10,000 on each 38 count.
   Mountain said he was ``disappointed'' after the verdict but did
not comment further. Kevin Burnette, president of Southern
Political, declined comment.
   Martin testified Tuesday that he instructed temporary employees
to forge the signatures only as an angered reaction after a du Pont
official goaded him about the inability to get legitimate
signatures.
   ``Was there an intent to defraud or harm? I don't think so,''
Joe Bailey, Mountain's lawyer, said in Wednesday's closing
argument. He said Mountain told the du Pont official not to submit
the phony petitions.
   Du Pont and his campaign officials have denied any knowledge of
the forgeries and no one from the du Pont campaign testified.
   Prosecutor Casey O'Brien dismissed Mountain's claim that he did
not intend to deceive anyone.
   Charles Soechting, attorney for Southern Political Consulting,
told jurors the company was innocent because Mountain, though a
vice president of the firm, was working as a du Pont volunteer when
he masterminded the forgeries.
   Soechting also argued that Mountain and the firm were being
singled out for prosecution because they are not liked by Texas GOP
officials.
   The defense tried to show that supporters of Bush's presidential
campaign were upset because Mountain's firm helped organize a 1987
Houston presidential debate in which Bush did not want to
participate.
   Under Texas GOP rules, candidates needed 5,000 signatures to get
on the presidential primary ballot.
   Seven people testified during the trial that Mountain bought
them beer and showed them how to forge signatures at a Dec. 19
party.
   Mountain and the company also were implicated in possible
forgeries on petitions submitted for GOP presidential candidates
Sen. Robert Dole and Alexander Haig, but no indictments were
returned in those cases.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
