<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Poland-Workers Adv29   06-22 1115</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland-Workers, Adv 29,1153</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs June 29 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Polish Workers Determined to Fight for Better Life</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At Workers Hotel No. 6 near the Ursus
tractor plant on the outskirts of Warsaw, men mill in the lobby or
sprawl lazily on couches in their small rooms watching television.
   Girlfriends may visit until 10 p.m. and one movie theater is in
the district, but for the most part the men have little to do,
especially on a salary the equivalent of about $100 a month.
   These are young, single Polish workers trapped, they say, with
virtually no chance for upward mobility in what was supposed to be
a workers' state _ frustrated not only off the job but by the
tedium and low pay on the job.
   For Poland's communist authorities, they are a tinderbox.
   Thousands of Ursus workers live in hotels like Workers Hotel No.
6 or small privately rented rooms because of the shortage of
apartments in Poland.
   ``You have to be very strong psychologically to avoid
drinking,'' said one of them, 20-year-old Mariusz Szulecki. ``For
some, it's the main recreation.''
   At Workers Hotel No. 6, five men cram into a two-room suite,
sharing a small kitchen and bathroom. The building is modern and
clean, but the conditions are like those of a college dormitory.
   During a wave of labor unrest across Poland April 25-May 10,
activists of the banned Solidarity trade union said they were
surprised by the militancy of younger workers who rallied to the
strike actions.
   Zbigniew Bujak, a dismissed Ursus worker who led the national
underground of the banned Solidarity union during the martial-law
years in Poland of 1981-83, describes the life of the young workers:
   ``First of all, they are not paid enough to make a living. They
can't afford even a bicycle. ... They would have to pay the entire
monthly salary to buy a normal, good bicycle. They can't even dream
about buying a motorcycle, unless they get some big money from
their parents in the countryside. ...
   ``They can't see any chance of getting an apartment. They mainly
drink. When I ask them, `Well, how long are you going to keep
getting drunk?' they say: `What else can we do? What can you
suggest? We have no chances.'''
   Bujak added that workers are demoralized by inefficiency in the
factory and embarrassed by the shoddiness of the goods they are
told to produce.
   ``They feel that if we are supposed to be making changes, then
we should change everything. Only then can they see the chance for
them to mean something in this country.''
   The assessment is shared to some extent by Alfred Miodowicz,
member of the Politburo of the Polish United Workers Party, as the
Communist Party is called, and the leader of the officially
recognized All-Poland Trade Union Alliance.
   ``We, unfortunately, are losing these youths,'' he was quoted as
saying in a recently published interview in the weekly Przeglad
Tygodniowy.
   ``A big group is growing of impatient people. ... They want to
act. They are full of determination. ... One has to create a chance
for them.''
   Official trade unions launched after the banning of Solidarity
have tried to provide an outlet for the frustration. Though still
derided by Solidarity activists as subservient to the authorities,
the unions in recent months have spoken out for higher wages and
better housing.
   Membership in official unions nationwide is about 7 million,
compared to Solidarity's 10 million in 1981.
   In an evening's conversation, four Ursus workers active in
unofficial organizing activities at the plant spoke about the poor
pay, lack of housing, lack of efficiency in the plant, a feeling
that they have no future.
   ``Thinking about marriage, about families, is out of the
question,'' said Henryk Tachasiuk, 26. ``The wages provide a
vegetation existence for one person, and it spoils life for me and
my girl.''
   He added that if he and his girl got married, they would have to
continue to live separately because he could not find an affordable
apartment.
   ``To get married just to be married makes no sense, so we are
all bachelors.''
   The workers said they have trouble earning enough for stereos or
television sets.
   The tiny Polish Fiat 126 _ designed as the car for the common
man when the government started producing it in the 1970s _ is now
for them the ``utmost dream.''
   At the plant, ``there is no organization at all,'' said
28-year-old Marek Jarosinski.
   He said his department is idled in the first two weeks of the
month by lack of materials.
   ``In the second half they will bring them, and we will have to
make it up by the end of the month.''
   Only about a third of the plant's 14,000 workers are directly
involved in production and one-fifth are in administration and the
rest are ``supporting personnel,'' said Tachasiuk.
   ``Our work has to provide for all these clerks,'' he said.
``It's discouraging.''
   Nevertheless they stay on, basically because they have no place
else to work. Ursus is one of the country's biggest factories and
the men said they don't think the situation is any better at other
plants. The only option would be to emigrate.
   ``To quit the job means to ask for a passport,'' said Tachasiuk.
   Jarosinski said he wants to stay and try to change things, even
if it means suffering defeats like workers in past years.
   ``Every generation gets its whipping, at least in our country,''
he said.
   But Tachasiuk conceded, ``It's a dream of many young people to
leave and earn some real money. That's their only real chance to
get an apartment or a car.''
   During the April-May labor unrest there was an attempted strike
at Ursus, but it fizzled after a protest march through the plant
and a rally in a factory canteen. According to Bujak, older workers
were reluctant to join in and most of the would-be strike leaders
had been detained. Tachasiuk said another strike was certain.
   ``There will be one and probably soon. Definitely this year.''
   The four said virtually everybody in the plant feels as they do,
and that workers join the official union only because it controls
benefits ranging from vacation facilities to day-care services and
waiting lists for housing.
   Asked if government attempts to reform the economy and
authorities' stated desire for dialogue would change their outlook,
the workers were skeptical.
   Said Zbigniew Budukiewicz, 29, who has been working at Ursus for
seven years, ``The greatest enemy of the people's government is the
working class.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Wed PMs June 29 or Thereafter</NOTE>
