<1ST_LINE>a a BC-Honda-Boomtown Adv25-26   06-22 0729</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Honda-Boomtown, Adv 25-26,0747</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv25</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions June 25-26 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Bellefontaine Feeling Unprecedented Growing Pains</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Honda-Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH GRACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELLEFONTAINE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight years ago, anyone living in
this community would have laughed at the suggestion that one day
there would be more people than available houses, more jobs than
people to fill them, more school children than classrooms to hold
them.
   But then came Honda.
   Since the early 1980s, the presence of Honda of America
Manufacturing Inc. _ the fourth-largest automaker in the nation _
and the arrival of its numerous suppliers have beefed up coffers in
14 Ohio counties, but nowhere more noticeably than here in Logan
County.
   ``Nobody knows what's going on here,'' said Leland Dorsey,
executive director of the Logan Area Chamber of Commerce. ``You
just have to come see for yourself. It's pretty unbelievable.''
   Bellefontaine, which is between the Honda auto complex in
Marysville and its engine plant in Anna and a mile or two west of a
new Honda auto plant under construction in East Liberty, is a prime
growth target, he said.
   ``We're becoming the center of Honda because of where we are,''
Dorsey said.
   Suppliers have begun moving in, and a new warehouse called Honda
Express, specifically aimed at warehousing parts for Honda, is
planning to open a 1 million-square-foot operation on the
Logan-Union County line.
   Honda's growth has caused problems, as well. This community of
11,500 at the beginning of the decade had enough housing to serve
its needs, but a recent survey showed the county was at least 2,200
units short of demand, Dorsey said.
   There is not an apartment to be had in the city, said Doug
Zimmerman of LeVan and Zimmerman Realty. Zimmerman said his office
gets about 20 inquiries about apartments every day.
   ``There isn't a one available. I've never seen anything like
it,'' he said. ``I was a farmer for 10 years before I got out of
it. I guess if I've made one right decision in my life, this sure
is it.''
   Although he would not say what has happened to the price of
purchasing a home, he said the number of listings the two LeVan and
Zimmerman offices in Logan County handle have soared.
   ``Honda buyers can now buy houses in the $60,000 to $80,000
range, whereas a few years ago they just couldn't afford that,'' he
said. ``This is a really exciting place to be right now. Builders
are in here every day looking for land, people are moving in. It's
a real seller's market. The sky's the limit.''
   But Dorsey said there are other problems. Even though
unemployment has dropped from an early 1980s high of almost 8
percent to around 5 percent, smaller employers are having trouble
filling lower-paying jobs because Honda and its suppliers pay more.
And traffic is becoming a problem.
   Logan County Sheriff Michael Henry says his 12 road officers
have seen a significant increase in traffic problems, vandalism and
drug trafficking as the population has risen.
   The construction of the new Honda plant and a projected county
population of 42,000 by 1990 _ up 9 percent from 39,155 in 1980 _
will create more patrol problems, he said. Population in the city
also has grown, In 1980, census figures show the count was 11,880.
Since then it has risen to about 12,500 and estimates show that it
could reach 13,500 by the end of the decade.
   The attitude in the Benjamin Logan School district on the
county's eastern border remains nonetheless optimistic. Once one of
the poorest school districts in the state, Honda's planned East
Liberty expansion will add $2.4 million into the district's annual
budget. The district's annual budget currently is $5 million, said
Anne Schrader, district treasurer.
   Officials who have watched Honda and other Japanese firms around
the state say Bellefontaine's attitude toward growth and the
Japanese helped make it grow.
   A study commissioned last year by the Institute for Japanese
Studies at Ohio State University cited Bellefontaine's
International Friendship Center, opened to help the Japanese and
other foreign investors learn American ways, as a model for other
communities hoping to attract foreign investment.
   The center, organized in 1986 and funded by churches, private
organizations and donations, assists Japanese families in the
transition from their native country.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, June 25-26</NOTE>
