<1ST_LINE>s p BC-OilmanBush Adv26 1stLd-Writethru 06-22 1166</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Oilman Bush, Adv 26, 1st Ld-Writethru, b0632,1193</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 26, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 10th graf, ``At age ..., to CORRECT spelling of Procter
& Gamble.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Snapshot '88: Even With Family Aid, Bush Never Made It `Big Rich'
In Oil</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush arrived in Texas in 1947 with his
wife, his Studebaker and a job lined up by his investment banker
uncle. He learned the ways of the oil patch and helped establish
tiny Zapata Petroleum Co. Much later Zapata grew into the giant
Pennzoil Co., but Bush was long gone to politics. Here's a look at
Bush's years as an oilman.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT McCARTNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In 1952, a young oilman just getting his feet wet
in politics drew the task of arranging an airport campaign stop for
Richard Nixon.
   He set up a stage, decorated it, brought out a crowd. Then
George Bush stood in the back with his business partner, John
Overbey, as the vice presidential candidate spoke.
   ``Nixon said a few words when a couple of seedy-looking
characters started yelling at him and waving signs,'' Overbey
recalled. ``Bush took one look at them and tore over there. He
ripped up their signs and told them to get the hell out.
   ``He can be a pretty aggressive guy, you know,'' Overbey said.
   The vice president isn't known for such forcefulness in
Washington, but in the Texas oil patch, he is remembered as an
energetic businessman who headed West to make his mark in the
corporate world. He succeeded _ not only by quickly learning the
ins and outs, but also by relying on generous amounts of family
money for backing.
   The Republican presidential contender was known then _ as now _
as a ``team player'' who built decisions by consensus and was
considered a faithful friend.
   Bush, who went to Congress in 1966 tagged with the label ``Texas
oil millionaire,'' saw some risky drilling ventures pay off during
his oil career, but he actually left the wheeling-dealing days of
the 1950s West Texas oil boom with only modest success by local
standards.
   ``George made a comfortable amount of money out of it,'' said
his friend and one-time partner, Pennzoil Co. Chairman J. Hugh
Liedtke. ``It was a substantial sum, but he's not what in Texas is
called `Big Rich.'''
   At age 24, after a tour as a Navy pilot and three years at Yale
University, Bush decided against joining the family business,
investment banking. He wrote in his autobiography that he was
turned down for a job at Procter & Gamble and considered farming,
but thought it too risky.
   So he set out to make it in oil. He began as a trainee for an
equipment supply company in 1948 _ a job arranged through the
family and one that included long days painting scalding hot pump
jacks and pipe. He became an equipment salesman, moving from Odessa
to California then to Midland, Texas.
   It was there that he quit the company and went out on his own
with Overbey, a neighbor and pal from touch football games and
barbecues, in a venture called the Bush-Overbey Development Co.
   ``I was trading minerals and royalties. He decided he wanted to
get involved in exploration and he suggested he could raise the
money,'' Overbey said. ``We didn't set the woods on fire but we
stayed in the black for three years.''
   Bush and Overbey bought and sold portions of other firms'
projects instead of drilling their own wells. The financial backing
of $350,000 was arranged through Bush's uncle, George Herbert
Walker Jr., and the investors included Bush's father, Prescott, and
Eugene Meyer, owner of The Washington Post.
   After three years, Bush and Overbey decided to join forces with
Bill and Hugh Liedtke, who also had their own trading company. The
Liedtkes raised $500,000 in Tulsa, Okla., their hometown, Bush
raised $500,000 on the East Coast, and they named their venture
Zapata Petroleum after the famed Mexican rebel leader portrayed by
actor Marlon Brando in ``Viva Zapata!''
   The partners tried to be conservative, Liedtke said, and never
made a move unless all agreed.
   ``I think George has always been kind of a team player and I
think the rest of us were kind of that way,'' he said. ``When
you're young, you don't have enough sense to get scared.''
   Zapata's first play was a $1 million bet on one oil field. Hugh
Liedtke was convinced the oil under a series of six wells spread
across Coke County, Texas, was actually part of one huge source.
Zapata threw its entire $1 million into the Jamieson field, took on
$4.5 million in debt, and raised a second $1 million from the same
investors.
   For a time it seemed the company was imitating the movie _ it
wasn't clear whether Zapata was a hero or bandit. Then slowly but
surely, the Jamieson field came out a winner.
   ``We drilled around 130 wells and never got a dry hole,'' said
Liedtke, now a corporate legend who steered Pennzoil to an $11
billion court judgment against Texaco over Texaco's takeover of
Getty Oil.
   But the toughest business decision for the partners came when
they found they had to fire employees _ most of whom were also good
friends _ before the fields paid off. Bush often refers to that
painful experience on the campaign trail.
   Eventually, Zapata split. Bush and his East Coast investors took
over Zapata Off-Shore, based in Houston, and the Liedtkes and their
backers stayed in production.
   In Houston, the Bushes and their five children settled into a
comfortable lifestyle, although Bush at one point developed a
bleeding ulcer.
   ``Dad shielded us from his business activities,'' said Jeb Bush,
now Florida commerce secretary. ``He spent a lot of time away, and
when he was there, we didn't talk about business, we talked about
baseball and sports.''
   Bush moved up quickly in local politics, which were dominated at
the time by Democrats. He became Harris County Republican chairman
in 1962 and ran unsuccessfully for the U.S. Senate in 1964. In
February 1966, he resigned as chairman of Zapata Off-Shore to wage
a full-time campaign for the House, and he won a seat in November.
   On his way to Washington, he sold his 6 percent stake in Zapata,
netting $1.1 million. Within 18 months, the Zapata stock, under new
management, took off, doubling in value. Liedtke's Zapata gave
birth to Pennzoil.
   ``If he had stayed in ... he could have made an enormous amount
of money if that had been what he really wanted to do,'' Liedtke
said.
   ``That was not his aim, I don't think. I think he wanted to
prove to himself and perhaps to others that he could, and once that
was accomplished, well, I don't think he was really interested in
it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Scott McCartney is the AP Southwest regional
reporter, based in Dallas.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
