<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 1326EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s i BC-PassingtheTorch Adv26   06-22 0652</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Passing the Torch, Adv 26,0667</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 26, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Reagan's Forced Retirement Leaves Summit Club Leaderless</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The club of economic summitry is viewing with
apprehension the forced retirement of President Reagan, aware that
none of its remaining members can fill the void and uncertain about
who might.
   If seniority were the only key, Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
might certainly be voted most likely to assume the summit
leadership. But she is clearly aware that taking the job requires
more economic wherewithal than her country has.
   The United States ``is the largest most prosperous nation in the
world, and let's be thankful she has taken a leadership role,'' the
three-term British leader said in a March radio interview. ``None
of us can substitute for it. We could all help with it.''
   French President Francois Mitterrand, the host of the 1989
economic conclave, has not shown any inclination to don the mantle
of world leadership. His country is not even a member of NATO's
military structure, although it does participate in the alliance's
political bodies, and his left-leaning economic policies are at
odds with those of the other allies.
   Japan, fast overtaking the U.S. economy in many ways, cannot
assume leadership of the summit seven; its markets are virtually
closed to the outside world, its ability to expand militarily is
limited by constitutional restraints and it is not a member of the
NATO alliance to which the other summit countries belong.
   ``There is no evidence of any country in the world anxious to
replace us in our leadership position,'' said Penelope
Hartland-Thunberg, an international affairs scholar at the Center
for Strategic and International Studies in Washington. ``The cost
and responsibility of leadership is something they wish to avoid.''
   Still, the economic decline that has turned the United States
from the world's biggest creditor in 1982 to its biggest debtor in
1988 has left a leadership vacuum begging to be filled.
   Even at this, his final summit, Reagan was unable to sway his
partners on his agenda priority _ the elimination of all
agriculture subsidies by the end of the century.
   The summitteers are hoping Reagan's successor can turn things
around.
   But the stakes are high, and many of the summit leaders would
prefer that Reagan be replaced with a known quantity like George
Bush, his vice president who has pledged to carry on the
president's program, said Simon Serfaty, an academic at the School
of Advanced International Studies of John Hopkins University in
Washington.
   This was underlined by the newest member of the summit club,
Italian Prime Minister Ciriaco De Mita, who emphasized to the other
leaders the importance of continuity in U.S. policy.
   ``Obviously, the current policy has been so successful, we want
to ensure it goes on,'' said an Italian official, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Some of the other leaders feel a Republican like Bush also would
be more likely to maintain the free market policies that led to a
surge of prosperity in the summit countries during the Reagan
administration, said Serfaty.
   But the other presidential hopeful, Michael Dukakis, also
appears to be an economic moderate. In a broad-ranging foreign
policy speech recently, Dukakis stressed the importance of
cooperating with America's allies.
   Regardless of who wins the November election, Reagan has left
for his successor little maneuvering room, given the U.S.
indebtedness that resulted from his economic policies of deep tax
cuts and enormous military buildup.
   The heavy debt to Japan and other summit countries, growing
foreign investment and bulging budget and trade deficits virtually
ensure the continued closeness that has characterized the club in
the Reagan years.
   ``Reagan leaves a difficult legacy,'' Serfaty said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Ruth Sinai, who specializes in foreign affairs
for The Associated Press, covered the Toronto summit.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 26</NOTE>
</DOC>
