<DOCNO> AP880622-0286 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 1434EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s w BC-WeeklyFarm Adv26   06-22 0718</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Farm, Adv 26,0736</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, June 26, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>U.S. Farm Trade Negotiators Flexing Muscles After Japanese Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some recently developed muscle was used in
reaching a new agricultural trade agreement with Japan, and U.S.
negotiators are hoping the rest of the world is suitably impressed.
   The pact will open Japan's door to more U.S. beef and citrus
over the next few years, gradually edging away from the restrictive
quota system that has been in effect.
   Fresh from the victory in Tokyo, U.S. Trade Representative
Clayton Yeutter swirled through news conferences last week to
explain what was done and how it was accomplished.
   The United States had demanded that Japan move immediately to
remove all quotas. This brought emotional protests from Japanese
farm groups, including threats to boycott U.S. grain and warnings
to Japanese consumers that American beef could be contaminated by
chemicals.
   But Yeutter said the U.S. pressure for total and immediate
removal of quotas was a negotiating tactic.
   ``It would have been impossible for the (Japanese) government to
make that agreement and survive,'' he said. ``So we had to work out
a way to achieve full market liberalization as quickly as
possible.''
   As it turned out, Japan agreed to phase out quotas on imported
beef and fresh oranges within three years and orange juice in four
years.
   Yeutter said there had been a fundamental change in the attitude
of Japanese leaders who showed a new willingness to reach an
agreement.
   If there was a sudden dawning or enlightenment among Japanese
officials it was helped along by stepped up U.S. pressure for
agricultural trade liberalization.
   ``The pressure came from two sources, in my judgment,'' Yeutter
said. ``The first is a generic one, the fact that we've just been a
lot more aggressive in opening up markets around the world over the
last three years or so than we have in the past.
   ``And the government of Japan finally has concluded that we're
serious about this, and they couldn't stall us off. In other words,
they successfully procrastinated on this for 20 years and finally
concluded that we were coming after them this time.''
   The second source of pressure, he said, resulted from U.S.
decisions to push hard for settlement of trade disputes under the
94-nation General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, which has is
headquarters in Geneva, Switzerland.
   ``We have finally begun to use the GATT, challenging import
restrictions like this that we believe to be inconsistent with the
GATT and illegal internationally,'' Yeutter said.
   Late last year a GATT ruling on a complaint by the United States
held that Japan should ease import restrictions on a dozen
agricultural products, including dairy products, fruit purees,
tomato juice, ketchup, dried peas and beans, sugars and syrups, and
prepared beef and pork products.
   With this victory, Yeutter said Japan was served notice that the
United States was prepared to go again to GATT for relief of the
beef and citrus restrictions.
   Yeutter and others are hopeful that the successful pursuit of
the Japanese agreement on beef and citrus will provide momentum in
dealing with the European Economic Community and negotiations of
new GATT terms for agriculture.
   Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng, as well as Yeutter and
many others, has been a steady critic of EEC policies and has
plugged heavily for reforms of subsidy programs worldwide.
   In September 1986, a GATT meeting in Punta del Este, Uruguay,
agreed to seek new trading rules for agriculture. In July 1987, the
United States formally proposed phasing out all subsidies, direct
or indirect, that affect agricultural trade, and all tariff and
non-tariff barriers, over a 10-year period.
   Lyng continues to be optimistic that ``the process of
negotiations has been moving along'' on the U.S. proposal but
acknowledged last week ``it will take a lot of work'' to convince
other countries during the so-called Uruguay Round of trade
negotiations.
   In Europe, leaders of the 12-nation trading bloc have denounced
the U.S. no-subsidy as unworkable and unrealistic.
   But Yeutter, echoing Lyng's resolve, said the proposal makes
sense and ``ought to be faster'' than the 10 years proposed for the
subsidy phase-out. The EEC and the world would better off if it
were, he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, June 26</NOTE>
