<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON _ The health of the nation's worst savings and loan
institutions worsened during the first three months of the year,
overwhelming modest gains made by solvent thrifts, the government
has reported.
   Losses by the 3,118 federally insured S&Ls were down slightly
from the record set during the last three months of 1987, and Texas
thrifts continued racking up huge losses, the Federal Home Loan
Bank Board reported Tuesday.
   Despite a significant improvement in earnings by thrifts
considered solvent under regulatory rules, economists predicted the
industry as a whole will lose more than $8 billion and set a record
in 1988.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Inflation slowed for the second month in a row
to an annual rate of 4.2 percent in May, with the Farm Belt drought
yet to reach the grocery shelves and consumers balking at paying
more for clothing, according to the Labor Department.
   Retail prices overall rose just 0.3 percent in May as women's
apparel prices fell after two straight months of hefty increases,
the department said Tuesday.
   Despite the slowdown, economists cautioned that inflation could
begin heating up as early as next month as the midwestern drought
forces higher food prices.
</TEXT>
