concluded their annual summit with a debt-relief plan for the
world's poorest countries, proclaiming optimism about the global
economy but spurning President Reagan's plea to abolish farm
subsidies.
   Despite the rebuff on subsidies, Reagan basically got what he
wanted from the summit in terms of tougher action against terrorism
and illegal drug trafficking.
   The three-day summit that ended Tuesday was Reagan's last and
White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the United States was
satisfied with the summit's final product.
