<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0205</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Finish Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rush of buying in gasoline futures contracts
has provided some support for an otherwise bearish energy market.
   The July contracts for crude oil, which were due to expire, came
under immediate pressure when trading began Tuesday and dragged
down the rest of market, observers said.
   But prices recovered late in the day as contracts for wholesale
unleaded gasoline made strong gains.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the July contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, settled 11 cents
lower at $15.89 per barrel. Contracts for delivery in later months
generally were higher.
   July unleaded gasoline gained 0.52 cent to 49.99 cents a gallon,
while home heating oil gained 0.10 cent to 43.28 cents a gallon.
   The buying in gasoline was sparked by traders staking positions
in advance of the release of new supply figures. Traders believe
demand will be high and supplies tight for gasoline during the
summer driving season, analysts said.
   But analysts said the fundamental tone of the market remained
bearish following the lack of new initiatives to contain production
by members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries.
</TEXT>
