<DOCNO> AP880622-0290 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 0332EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Texaco-Icahn Bjt   06-22 0699</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texaco-Icahn, Bjt,0722</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Icahn's Options Keep Texaco, Market Guessing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc.'s management may be turning its
focus back to the oil patch, but corporate raider Carl C. Icahn is
likely to remain a thorn in the oil giant's side for some time.
   He lost a critical proxy battle for five seats on Texaco's
14-member board, but Icahn still owns 14.9 percent of the company's
outstanding shares, a formidable force to reckon with.
   And if a parallel can be drawn to his encounter with USX Corp.,
Icahn may buck popular wisdom and hang onto his Texaco shares.
   When the steelmaker stymied his buyout overtures last year,
experts predicted Icahn would sell out his stake. But he did
nothing of the sort and continues to be USX's largest single
shareholder.
   Right now Icahn is a passive investor in the Pittsburgh-based
steel and energy company. ``But with 10 percent (of the outstanding
shares), there's always the possibility that if he's not satisfied,
he might try to acquire the company,'' said Dennis Sperduto, an
analyst with Argus Research Corp.
   Texaco, Sperduto said, is far more vulnerable to criticism than
USX was at the time, and Icahn's exchanges with Texaco management
have been frosty at best.
   Both sides have swapped barbs, ``and Icahn has been on record as
saying he has no intention of staying with existing management,''
said Paul Ting, an analyst at Oppenheimer & Co.
   After conceding defeat Monday in the proxy contest, Icahn
announced that he was weighing his options, including making a
hostile tender offer, holding his shares or selling them to a third
party.
   Time is not of the essence. If Icahn is to sell his stake, he
must wait until July 20 before pocketing the profits. Under the
``short-swing'' profit rule, a holder of more than 5 percent of a
company's stock must keep those shares for at least six months,
otherwise any profits earned revert back to the company.
   Because a significant amount of stock was voted for Icahn,
Texaco management is under the gun to perform, said Rosario
Ilacqua, vice president of equity research at Nikko Securities Co.
International Inc.
   ``They have to live up to all of the things that the
shareholders who voted for them are expecting,'' he said.
   Icahn is taking at least some credit for the reorganization
Texaco has embarked upon.
   A keystone of the company's plan was a $3 billion payment to
Pennzoil Co. to settle a lawsuit resulting from Texaco's 1984
acquisition of Getty Oil Co. after Pennzoil had made earlier moves
to acquire Getty.
   In addition, Texaco has begun selling off up to $5 billion worth
of marginally profitable assets and says it will distribute $1.7
billion of the proceeds to shareholders.
   A source close to Texaco said that with the restructuring
underway and the proxy battle over, ``some stability is offered
now, and the management can return to the oil patch.''
   Management also is considering a stock buyback program, which,
coupled with the regular quarterly dividend Texaco has resumed
paying, could amount to a handsome return for Icahn if he decides
to hold his stake.
   One thing most experts agree Icahn will not do is dump his
shares on the open market, a move that would have a depressing
effect on Texaco's stock price.
   More likely would be the sale of his shares in a block to a
third party. But selling the stake could pose a problem for Texaco
management, particularly if Icahn lined up another oil company as
the buyer, or even the New York investment firm Kohlberg Kravis
Roberts & Co.
   Kohlberg Kravis ensured Icahn's defeat in the proxy fight by
voting its 12 million shares for Texaco management. While the firm
no longer owns that 4.9 percent stake, it stated it might consider
purchasing shares in the future and that remained ``interested in
the company's progress.''
   In Tuesday trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Texaco jumped
$1.62{ a share to close at $48.50 amid rumors that the company was
about to unveil the buyback program and that Kohlberg Kravis was
purchasing more shares or mulling a leveraged buyout of the oil
company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
