<DOCNO> AP880622-0295 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 0344EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-GMPlant     06-22 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GM Plant,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Analysts Say New GM Plant is Significant, Risky</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KETTERING, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp.'s plans to build a
parts plant aimed at supplying foreign automakers is a big step for
the auto giant, analysts say, but there is some skepticism GM can
make it work.
   GM's Delco Products Division announced Tuesday it would build an
82,000-square-foot plant that would utilize high technology and new
management techniques to make struts for smaller front-wheel-drive
cars in this Dayton suburb.
   Plant manager James A. Bridenbaugh said the low-mass strut
dampers will be aimed at Japanese automakers locating plants in the
United States, although he also expects interest from domestic
automakers.
   Production is scheduled to begin next year with 60 people,
expanding to 150 by 1992, said Delco spokesman Charles W. Kronbach.
The plant will feature flexible manufacturing cells, instead of the
traditional assembly line, and increased responsibilities for
workers.
   ``It is a bit of a surprise. It's a big step for them,'' said
Thomas O'Grady, industry analyst and president of Integrated
Automotive Resources Inc.
   Kronbach said the struts already had been accepted for use on
GM's new Saturn models and on Toyota Camrys to be built in
Georgetown, Ky.
   Delco executives consulted officials of the International Union
of Electronics Workers Local 755, which represents many of the
3,000 Delco employees at Delco's main Kettering plant and
headquarters, Kronbach said.
   Both sides agreed ``that we needed to find a green-field site
like our Japanese competitors here'' with few ties to the main
plant, Kronbach said. ``It gives us a fair shot to try our new
teamwork and technology approach.''
   GM's competitors _ Kayaba, Showa and Tokico _ are building
plants in Ohio, Indiana and Kentucky, close to Japanese auto
assembly plants known as ``transplants,'' he said.
   Kronbach said the new plant would be unionized.
   Maryann Keller, an analyst with Furman Selz Mager Dietz &
Birney, was skeptical, saying she had heard ``a lot of sweeping
statements'' about selling to the Japanese, not only from GM, but
from Chrysler Corp.
   ``I hope they do it. I think working with the transplants will
create a discipline that they probably lack,'' she said.
   ``They sell to the transplants now, they just never put up a
green-fields site with the specific intention of selling to the
transplants,'' Ms. Keller said.
   Kathleen Heaney, an analyst with Nikko Securities International,
warned there may be limits to how often GM can establish a new
plant and new work culture.
   ``They can probably get away with this once. The more that they
try to start building new plants, while they're talking about their
other plants...not being competitive and trying to close those
down, I think they're going to have a hard time,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
