<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AshlandAppeal     06-22 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ashland Appeal,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ashland Oil, Officers Appeal $70 Million Verdict</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COVINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ashland Oil Inc. attorneys have asked a
federal judge to set aside a nearly $70 million civil award to two
former vice presidents, citing trial errors and excessive damages.
   The motions, filed Monday, asks that U.S. District Judge William
O. Bertelsman hold a new trial if he won't overturn the verdict.
   After an eight-week trial, a jury earlier this month awarded
former Ashland Oil vice presidents Bill E. McKay $14.4 million and
Harry Williams $7.7 million in lost earnings and benefits.
   The two claimed they were fired in 1983 for refusing to bribe
foreign officials to obtain crude oil or to help cover up such
illegal payments.
   Lawyers for Ashland and the other defendants _ Chairman John
Hall, Senior Vice President Richard Spears and former Chairman Orin
Atkins _ dispute the verdicts in the documents filed Monday.
   The filing claims Ashland deserves a new trial because the
defendants weren't given time to present their case, Bertelsman
allowed improper evidence to be introduced, and the damages awarded
were beyond what McKay or Williams could have earned with Ashland.
The motions also say Bertelsman gave confusing instructions to the
jury.
   The amount of the awards had been tripled because jurors also
found Ashland had engaged in a pattern of illegal interstate
activity _ paying bribes to foreign officials. The two men were
awarded punitive damages on top of the triple damages.
</TEXT>
