<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru   06-22 0606</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,0624</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inflation Slows Again; Stock Market Gains</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Grafs 1-5 new to UPDATE with durable goods report; picksup
2nd graf pvs: The Dow ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to U.S. factories for ``big ticket'' durable goods
plunged 2.2 percent in May, the steepest dive in nine months, the
government said today.
   The Commerce Department said orders for durables goods, items
expected to last three or more years, totaled a seasonally adjusted
$114.8 billion last month.
   The report, which showed the biggest drop in new orders since
August, surprised economists. The entire May decline can be
accounted for by a precipitous 9 percent decline in orders for
transportation equipment.
   Many experts had predicted a rise of more than 2 percent in
orders on the strength of two big orders late in May to Boeing
Commercial Airplanes Co., one from United Airlines, the other from
American Airlines. But those orders apparently were not recorded in
the Commerce Department's preliminary estimate of durable goods.
   On Tuesday, a government report of lower-than-expected inflation
during May encouraged the stock market, but the good news was
offset by a surge in commodity prices related to the Farm Belt
drought.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials climbed 25.24 points to
2,109.17 on Tuesday. Bond prices were flat and the dollar was
narrowly lower.
   The Labor Department said consumer prices rose a modest 0.3
percent in May.
   But drought fears drove corn futures prices up their daily limit
for the sixth straight day on the Chicago Board of Trade. Soybean
futures also rose sharply while wheat futures retreated.
   The drought will push up food prices this summer, but costlier
food will add only about half a percentage point to the overall
rise in the Consumer Price Index, predicted John Hagens, an
economist for the Wefa Group of Bala Cynwyd, Pa.
   For the first five months of 1988, consumer prices have risen at
an annual rate of 4.4 percent, the same pace as in 1987.
   ``Where is the inflation bear?'' Sandra Shaber, an analyst for
the Futures Group, a Washington consulting firm, said. ``His
footprints are not in much evidence right now.''
   But Ms. Shaber and several other economists warned that
inflation was only hibernating.
   Higher prices for gasoline and medical costs were behind most of
the inflation in May, but they were offset somewhat by a leveling
off of clothing prices.
   In a related report Tuesday, the Labor Department said
Americans' average weekly earnings, after adjusting for inflation,
fell 0.3 percent in May. The decrease follows an increase of 1.0
percent in April and a drop of 0.6 percent in March.
   The changes left American's inflation-adjusted earnings 0.7
percent below a year ago.
   In the commodity markets, analysts said the National Weather
Service's latest six-to-10 day forecast for hot, dry weather in the
Midwest through the end of the month threatened further damage to
corn, oat and soybean crops and inspired new buying of futures
contracts.
   ``With the corn crop, each week that goes by without rain means
another 10 percent is lost,'' said Joel Karlin, an analyst with
Research Department Inc. in Chicago. Some experts estimate anywhere
from 10 to 30 percent of the U.S. corn crop already has been ruined
by lack of rain.
   In a report on the nation's savings and loan industry, the
government said S&Ls overall continued losing huge amounts of money
in the first three months of this year.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board said the 3,118 federally
insured S&Ls lost $3.78 billion, only slightly below the $3.81
billion record set in the last three months of 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
