<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Britain-InterestRates     06-22 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Interest Rates,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commercial Banks Increase Base Rate To 9 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's commercial banks, heeding a signal from
the Bank of England, raised their base lending rate by half a
percentage point Wednesday to 9 percent.
   It was the third increase in the benchmark rate in less than
three weeks and represented a concerted effort by Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher's Conservative government to curb inflationary
pressures and boost the pound.
   The Bank of England signaled the increase by raising a key money
market intervention rate.
   Barclays Bank PLC responded immediately by raising its base rate
from 8.5 percent to 9 percent, effective Thursday. Midland Bank
PLC, National Westminster Bank PLC and Lloyds Bank PLC quickly
followed suit.
   Corporate borrowers can obtain loans from commercial banks at 1
percentage point above the base lending rate.
   There was little reaction in financial markets to the increase.
The pound was slightly higher but dealers said the currency's
response was restricted because the rate hike had already been
discounted.
   Commercial banks increased their base lending rate from 7.5
percent to 8 percent on June 2 and then to 8.5 percent on June 6.
The base rate had been cut from 8 percent to 7.5 percent on May 17
in an attempt to restrain a strong rise in the pound at the time.
   Government figures for inflation, jobs, growth and output have
highlighted the fact that the British economy continues to boom,
despite last October's stock market crash.
</TEXT>
