<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet11am     06-22 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 11am,0250</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices surged this morning in heavy
trading, bolstered by the momentum of a late rally in the previous
session and a strengthened dollar overseas.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks, which advanced
25.24 points late Tuesday, rose another 35.39 points to 2,144.56 by
11 a.m. on Wall Street, putting it at the highest level since the
market crash eight months ago.
   The Commerce Department's report of lower-than-expected durable
goods orders for May also helped ease concerns about inflation and
encouraged some stock buying, brokers said.
   ``Everything just came into play this morning,'' said Philip C.
Puccio, senior vice president and manager of institutional trading
at Dillon Read & Co. in New York.
   Broader market barometers also gained. The New York Stock
Exchange composite index of all listed issues rose 1.97 to 155.26.
On the American Stock Exchange, the market value index rose 1.45 to
308.33.
   Gaining issues outnumbered declines by more than 3-to-1 on the
NYSE, with 1,035 up, 285 down and 424 unchanged. Volume totaled
89.68 million shares after the first 90 minutes of trading.
   IBM led the NYSE's most-active list, jumping 2| to 122~ on
volume of more than 2 million shares Other notable blue-chip
gainers included Alcoa, up 1[ to 53, Boeing, up 1] to 57{, Du Pont,
up 1} to 90[, General Electric, up | to 44[, and Eastman Kodak, up
~ to 46].
