<1ST_LINE>s f BC-Mexico-Economy Adv26   06-22 1114</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Mexico-Economy, Adv 26,1151</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday June 26 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Shock Program Jolts High Inflation Out of Economy Temporarily</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Ramirez de la O correct in 10th graf and thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the millions of people who daily board
the Mexico City subway system, the price of a ticket is sticking at
100 pesos _ less than a nickel _ a ride.
   A stack of tortillas, the mainstay of the Mexican diet, can
still be bought for about a nickel a pound, and the prices of milk,
gasoline and a host of other products haven't changed much.
   The government's ``shock'' program has jolted the worrisome
triple-digit inflation out of the economy _ at least temporarily.
   Government officials are boasting the accomplishments of their
plan, which has frozen the prices of government-regulated goods,
the minimum wage and the exchange rate of the peso currency. It
also calls for federal spending cuts, a tight monetary policy and
opening the economy to more foreign trade.
   So far, the results of the Economic Solidarity Pact have been
impressive. Consumer prices skyrocketed a record 15.5 percent in
January but rose 1.9 percent in May for the slowest gain in 6{
years.
   Still, some analysts say it's too soon to tell whether high
inflation has been permanently chased away.
   ``We're in the honeymoon (stage),'' said Jonathan Heath,
coordinating director of the forecasting firm, Macro Asesoria
Economica.
   ``You cannot say it is successful nor a failure because the pact
has only one objective, that is to reduce inflation permanently,''
said Heath. ``What's been done so far is reduce inflation
temporarily. ... The only real verdict we'll be able to give of the
pact is down the road.''
   Rogelio Ramirez de la O of the Ecanal consulting firm agreed:
``It's too early to say whether there's a permanent reduction in
inflation.''
   To the man on the street, not much seems to have changed.
Construction worker Ismael Carrasco, waiting for a job in the
downtown Zocalo plaza, dismissed the goverment's program as ``a
lie.''
   ``Instead of helping us, they are grinding us down day after
day, more and more. ... Everything is going up,'' he complained.
   Across the street, at Monte de Piedad, the national pawnshop,
dozens of people lined up early on a recent morning to hock their
valuables for a little money to meet expenses.
   ``It is still very difficult,'' said Norberto Godinez, a watch
repairman who pawned a watch to get 35,000 pesos _ about $15.50 _
to buy parts for his work. ``Inflation is the same.''
   President Miguel de la Madrid unveiled the Solidarity Pact in
mid-December after officials became worried that Mexico was on the
verge of spinning into the hyper-inflationary swirls of other Latin
American countries.
   Consumer prices rose a record 159.2 percent last year, well
above the 105.7 percent posted in the previous year. Analysts were
predicting the 1988 pace could well hit the 200 percent mark.
   Moreover, the stock market, once one of the world's top
performers, collapsed. Speculation in the peso currency was
widespread.
   ``It was a wise thing to do something when the situation went
out of control in November 1987,'' said Ramirez de la O. ``It is
probably the only thing that could have been done.''
   Analysts are predicting an inflation rate in the range of 40
percent to 50 percent for 1988, if the government maintains its
tight clamp on wages, prices and the exchange rate through the end
of November when de la Madrid's six-year term ends. The government
has already said the program will run through August.
   De la Madrid is virtually certain to be succeeded by Carlos
Salinas de Gortari, the standard-bearer of the ruling Institutional
Revolutionary Party. Salinas de Gortari has said in campaign
speeches that he intends to press the inflation fight.
   ``We feel that the new administration will continue the
anti-inflation policy to eradicate inflation, hopefully bringing it
below double-digit inflation (in 1989),'' said Abel Beltran del
Rio, executive director of the Mexican forecasting project
Ciemex-Wefa in Bala Cynwyd, Pa.
   ``We feel this is the program that is going to end the inflation
decade-and-a-half of Mexico,'' he said.
   ``Mexico is at the cutting edge in terms of macro-economic
policy of high-debt countries,'' said a knowledgeable analyst, who
spoke on condition of anonymity. Mexico's foreign debt is $100
billion, the second highest in the developing world after Brazil.
   The initial goal of the Solidarity program was to trim the
inflation rate to 2 percent a month by year's end.
   Government officials have said in recent weeks the price pace
should be similar to that of Mexico's trading partners. Inflation
is running just over 4 percent in the United States, Mexico's No.1
trading partner.
   Under the Solidarity Pact, prices on goods and services
regulated by the government have been frozen since March.
Government officials have applied pressure on business leaders to
keep a lid on their prices, resulting in a virtual economy-wide
freeze.
   Before the freeze, the government nearly doubled some official
prices, giving a sharp kick to costs throughout the economy.
   The government also ordered in March a hold on the exchange rate
of the peso currency. It has ranged between 2,240 pesos and 2,280
pesos to the dollar since then. The peso lost about a fifth of its
value in a sharp devaluation in December.
   The minimum wage in Mexico City has been maintained at 8,000
pesos a day _ about $3.50 _ since April. Unskilled workers got
raises of a cumulative 38 percent before the freeze.
   With the wide-ranging holds, analysts say the inflation rate had
to ease.
   But some worry that once the freezes are lifted, prices could
resume their upward climb. Argentina and Brazil, which have used
shock programs in recent years, have still been unable to lick high
inflation.
   Heath suggests that the Mexican government thaw its frozen
prices at the depths of the economic downturn now beginning to be
felt. With low economic activity, there would be little need for
businesses to boost their prices sharply.
   ``We don't expect an explosion of prices,'' Beltran del Rio
said. ``We anticipate increases, sure, but not increases of 30, 40
or 50 percent.''
   Analysts also say the government needs to stick to efforts to
pare its spending.
   ``If the government does not adjust its public finances, we will
see that inflation will pick up again,'' said Ramirez de la O. ``If
the government does adjust, we can take for granted controls can be
removed without inflationary consequences.''
   But, he said, ``it's too early to say the government has taken
the pill of austerity.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday June 26</NOTE>
