<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   06-22 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans opened mixed
today on the Chicago Board of Trade as traders unnerved by rain
forecasts took profits on drought-driven gains.
   Prices on some contracts for future delivery of soybeans dropped
sharply on forecasts for rain today and tomorrow in some parts of
the Farm Belt.
   But the showers were expected to be light and spotty, and
another day of 100-plus-degree temperatures was predicted for many
major grain-producing areas, said Steve Freed, a grain analyst with
Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in Chicago.
   ``Thirty percent of the belt has a chance for 50 percent
coverage of a quarter- to a half-inch'' of rain, Freed said. ``To
me, that's not enough when we're losing half an inch a day.''
   Freed said some price consolidation was healthy in the corn and
soybean markets, which have rocketed to four- and 11-year highs,
respectively, in the past month on fears of crop damage from the
dry weather.
   Wheat futures continued to decline on harvest pressure while
corn was mixed.
   In early trading, wheat was 4 cents lower to 1 cent higher with
July at $3.85{ a bushel; corn was 3 cents lower to 8{ cents higher
with July at $3.43 a bushel; oats were 2 cents to 10{ cents higher
with July at $3.31 a bushel; soybeans were { cent to 22{ cents
lower with July at $10.46 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .62 cent lower to .20 cent higher with August
at 64.10 cents a pound; feeder cattle were 1.25 cents lower to .70
cent higher with August at 71.50 cents a pound; hogs were .07 cent
lower to .23 cent higher with July at 46.30 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were 1.25 cents lower to .70 cent higher with July at
42.75 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures closed mixed on Tuesday.
  
</TEXT>
