<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Brazil-Debt     06-22 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Brazil-Debt,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brazil: Agreement on Foreign Debt Reached with Banks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brazil has reached agreement with
international bankers on its huge foreign debt, the country's
finance minister said.
   ``We have concluded all points of the accord,'' Finance Minister
Mailson Da nobrega said Tuesday. ``Brazil is satisfied with the
agreement. It is the best accord reached so far with bankers.''
   The agreement, which gives Brazil $5.2 billion in new loans, was
not immediately signed but a communique would be issued in New York
and Brazil within the next two days, Da nobrega said.
   Brazil's 700 creditor banks must still work out the exact amount
each would give the country. However, Brazil is not involved in
that part of the agreement, Da nobrega said.
   Brazil's owes its creditors a total of $120 billion, making it
the largest debtor among developing countries.
   Finance Ministry representatives and a committee representing
the creditors have been negotiating for months on an accord that
would satisfy all parties.
   Brazil is to receive $4.6 billion this year and $600 million
during the first three months of 1989. The last installment is
contingent on Brazil's compliance with an economic agreement being
drawn up under International Monetary Fund guidelines, da Nobrega
said.
   There is a 12-year payback period with a five-year grace period
on the new loan.
   In February 1987, Brazil announced a moratorium on interest
payments and said it needed to restructure its debt. At that time,
President Jose Sarney said the country's reserves had fallen to
less than $4 billion and it could not afford to make the payments.
   Under the agreement, the interest owed to private bankers on $70
billion of its overall debt would be paid back over a 20-year
period with an eight-year grace period.
   Brazil also will pay bankers $300 million to $400 mmillion that
was due in March.
   After Brazil announced its moratorium on payments, many large
U.S. banks made large additions to their reserves for bad loans.
The additions resulted in heavy losses for U.S. banking companies
during 1987.
</TEXT>
