<1ST_LINE>r f BC-CannonSettlement     06-22 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Cannon Settlement,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Film Company to Pay $33 Million to Settle Lawsuits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cannon Group tentatively agreed to a $33
million settlement of class-action lawsuits that accused the firm
of inflating its stock price.
   The settlement, announced by the company Tuesday, was $13
million greater than a partial agreement announced in April.
   Cannon said it would be required to pay $9 million of the
settlement, with the rest paid by insurance carriers for directors,
officers and former outside auditors who also were defendants.
   The tentative agreements ``will not constitute any admission of
any liability or wrongdoing,'' the company said, adding that its
board found it in the best interests of Cannon and its shareholders
to settle the suits at this time.
   The suits were filed by shareholders last August after Cannon
disclosed that the Securities and Exchange Commission was
conducting an inquiry into how the firm accounted for its film
costs.
   That inquiry turned into a formal investigation in November when
the SEC filed a fraud complaint.
   Control of the independent production group shifted in April to
a consortium of European stockholders led by Giancarlo Parretti,
who was named chief executive. Former top executvies Menahem Golan
and Yoram Globus, were named to head the firm's movie-making
subsidiary.
   Cannon may be required to change its accounting procedures under
the agreement, the firm said.
</TEXT>
