<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0297</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks surged today in heavy trading and pushed
the Dow Jones average to its highest level since the October crash,
bolstered by the momentum of a late rally in the previous session
and a stronger dollar.
   Brokers said lower-than-expected rises in May consumer prices
and durable-goods orders reported by the government also helped
stock prices by easing fears about inflation.
   The Dow average of 30 industrial stocks, which rose 25.24 points
late Tuesday, gained more than 50 points by early afternoon,
automatically triggering a New York Stock Exchange post-crash ban
on a computerized trading strategy called index arbitrage. The
technique has been blamed for inciting market volatility.
   The Dow index retreated a bit but was still 49.08 points higher
to 2,158.25 by 2 p.m. EDT.
   ``The strength of the dollar this morning was what really got
things going,'' said Leigh Stevens, a strategist at PaineWebber
Inc. in New York. ``Everything just kicked in.''
   The New York Stock Exchange composite index of all listed issues
rose 2.56 to 155.85. On the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index rose 1.91 to 308.79.
   Gaining issues outnumbered declines by more than 4-to-1 on the
NYSE, with 1,249 up, 294 down and 377 unchanged. Volume totaled
169.68 million shares with two hours of trading left.
   IBM led the NYSE's most-active list, jumping 3[ to 123] on
volume of more than 3.2 million shares. Other notable blue-chip
gainers included Alcoa, up 1{ to 53], Boeing, up 1} to 57~, Du
Pont, up 3] to 91}, and McDonalds, up 1\ to 45}.
   Honeywell fell 4[ to 70{. The company said Tuesday it will take
a $23 million second-quarter charge against earnings.
</TEXT>
