<2ND_LINE>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0046,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Close Higher</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later trading; No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices rose sharply Wednesday on the London
Stock Exchange, boosted by a solid Wall Street opening, but
finished slightly below their best levels of the day.
   At the close, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index
was up 19.2 points, or 1.03 percent, at 1,879.3, marginally below
the day's high of 1,879.8.
   Trading volume was a relatively robust 521.6 million shares, up
from Tuesday's 380.2 million shares.
   The London market jumped after Wall Street opened strongly
higher. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 34.32 points
at 2,143.49 by the end of the London trading session.
   In addition, analysts said, the market was reassured after the
Bank of England signaled a hike in British interest rates by
one-half percentage point to 9 percent, with the major commercial
banks following suit around midday.
   Banking shares ended on a strong note on news that Brazil and a
committee of its major creditor banks have reached agreement in
principle to reschedule $62 billion in bank credits and provide
Brazil with $5.2 billion in new loans.
</TEXT>
