<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   06-22 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Close Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans closed mixed
Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade as forecasts for rain
slowed the drought-driven rally.
   Oat futures advanced their daily limit to a new record high of
$3.34 a bushel, and corn for July delivery also closed limit-up.
But soybeans finished mixed and wheat closed mostly lower on hedge
selling as the winter wheat harvest accelerated.
   Forecasts for light, scattered showers in the eastern Corn Belt
prompted a wave of profit-taking in soybean futures, said Dale
Gustafson, an analyst in Chicago with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   But corn prices were strong all day on fears that damage to the
crop was bound to worsen if the Midwest continued to swelter in
hot, dry weather.
   ``There was a little nervousness about the rain but there was
enough commercial buying to offset that,'' Gustafson said. ``Corn
has a much shorter time frame (than soybeans) for it to get some
beneficial rains.''
   Oat futures soared on reports that 50 percent of the U.S. crop
had been lost to the drought.
   At the close, wheat was 4{ cents lower to 8 cents higher with
July at $3.85 a bushel; corn was 4 cents to the limit 10 cents
higher with July at $3.44{ a bushel; oats were 7 cents to 15 cents
higher with July at $3.33 a bushel; soybeans were 11{ cents lower
to 9{ cents higher with July at $10.53 a bushel.
</TEXT>
