<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     06-22 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0234</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks surged today on news of a strengthened
dollar and lower interest rates, boosting the Dow Jones industrial
average to the highest level since the crash eight months ago.
   ``We had a beautiful fire under the stock market today,'' said
Robert O'Toole, head of over-the-counter trading at Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc. ``There's just a lot of cash out there, it's coming
into play.''
   Brokers said the heavy volume and demand for big-name stocks
suggested that large institutional investors and money managers
were buying to enhance their client portfolios before the
second-quarter expires June 30, a phenomenon called ``window
dressing.''
   Lower-than-expected rises in May consumer prices and
durable-goods orders reported by the government also helped stock
prices by easing fears about inflation. That news helped rally bond
prices and pushed yields on the closely watched 30-year Treasury
bill back under 9 percent.
   But the catalyst for the rally appeared to be a surprising surge
in the dollar overseas, caused partly by an impression that leaders
of the seven major industrialized nations, who concluded a summit
Tuesday, would tolerate a higher value for the U.S. currency.
   ``The strength of the dollar this morning was what really got
things going,'' said Leigh Stevens, a strategist at PaineWebber
Inc. in New York. ``Everything just kicked in.''
</TEXT>
