<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Nabisco-China     06-22 0264</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nabisco-China,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nabisco Opens Plant To Make Ritz Crackers In China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nabisco Brands Inc., a major U.S. food
manufacturer, began producing Ritz crackers and other biscuits at a
plant here Wednesday, in a joint venture aimed mainly at the
Chinese market.
   Nabisco Brands Chairman James O. Welch Jr., speaking at the
inauguration of the plant in southwest Beijing, said Nabisco and
its Chinese partner ``have created one of the finest bakeries of
its kind in the world.''
   Welch said the bakery was built at a cost of $9 million, with
RJR Nabisco Inc., the parent of Nabisco Brands, providing 51
percent and Beijing Yili Food Co. the rest.
   The plant is designed to produce 40 million packages of Ritz,
Premium, Escort and Maria biscuits and crackers a year, with a
retail value of $20 million. It will employ 150 people.
   Nabisco provided the equipment and technology while Yili, a
Chinese food manufacturer with an 80-year history, supplied the
land, building and utilities, Welch said.
   Ralph Donner of RJR Nabisco China said the company will try to
export about 15 percent of its product, mainly to other Asian
countries.
   Two other RJR Nabisco companies, Del Monte and R.J. Reynolds
Tobacco, also have ventures in China.
   Del Monte has a pilot project near Shanghai where sweet corn is
grown, canned as creamed corn and exported, primarily to Asian
markets. R.J. Reynolds plans to open a joint venture plant in the
southeast China city of Xiamen later this year to manufacture RJR
and jointly-owned brands of cigarettes for sale in China and abroad.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
