<DOCNO> AP880622-0326 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 1815EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Zenith     06-22 0403</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zenith,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Partnership Acquires State in Zenith</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Delaware partnership said Wednesday it has
acquired a 7.1 percent stake in Zenith Electronics Corp. and may
seek to acquire the computer and television maker.
   In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission,
Brookhurst Partners Limited Partnership said it believes its
holding of 1.85 million Zenith shares makes it the company's
largest single shareholder.
   Brookhurst said in a statement that it ``does not consider
itself a passive investor and intends to encourage management to
enhance stockholder values.'' To that end, the partnership said it
was considering purchasing more Zenith shares and ``making a
proposal with respect to a business combination with Zenith.''
   A spokesman for Glenview, Ill.-based Zenith had no comment. On
Wall Street, the company's stock rose 87{ cents to close at $29.25
a share.
   Brookhurst began accumulating Zenith shares on April 25 for
about $19 a share. The partnership steadily continued its purchases
until late June, when the shares were trading in the $28 range,
according to documents provided by the partnership.
   Zenith had revenue of $2.36 billion in 1987, but reported a loss
of $19.1 million, its third consecutive annual loss. The company
attributed the shortfall to sharply reduced operating results in
its consumer electronics division as well as the ``slow and
costly'' introduction of new picture tube technology.
   Earlier this month Zenith announced it was ``continuing to
examine all options to restore overall corporate profitability to a
satisfactory level.'' Among the options the company hinted at was
the sale of the consumer electronics operations, which generated
about $1.1 billion in revenue last year.
   The consumer electronics division makes television sets,
videocassette recorders and cable products. The company's other
main business is in personal computers and computer components.
   Analysts note that Zenith is highly debt-ridden and has little
cash on hand, making it not a particularly attractive takeover
candidate.
   Zenith strengthened its shareholder-rights provision in April,
saying the takeover defense was intended to ``guard against abusive
tactics such as the gradual accumulation of shares and partial
tender offers.''
   Brookhurst said it was formed expressly to acquire Zenith
shares. The group is headed by Herbert Abelow, a former managing
director of the investment firm First Boston Corp., and Nicholas
Ihasz, who from 1976 to 1980 directed the floor trading operations
of Ivan F. Boesky & Co. The two now head Abelow Ihasz & Co. of New
York.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
