<1ST_LINE>u f AM-USAir-Union     06-22 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-USAir-Union,0543</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USAir: Flight Attendants Union Violated Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TARA BRADLEY-STECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USAir Group Inc. officials told a federal
judge Wednesday that the Association of Flight Attendants persuaded
its members to refuse overtime during the Memorial Day holiday in
violation of federal labor law.
   ``It was their position that this is what the union wanted them
to do,'' USAir's Pittsburgh flight attendant supervisor, Robert
Fuhr, said of his futile attempts to call employees to work over
the three-day holiday.
   Airline managers told U.S. District Judge Robert Standish in a
courtroom overflowing with flight attendants that notices were
posted in crew lounges encouraging the overtime boycott.
   The airline, with executives based in Washington and operations
based in Pittsburgh, is asking Standish to award $2 million in
damages and to bar the union from instigating a repeat of the
disruption during the Independence Day holiday period.
   USAir said it lost at least $1 million in revenue when it was
forced to cancel 180 flights and paid at least $100,000 to
accommodate displaced holiday passengers.
   Officials of the flight attendants union deny any wrongdoing.
They have complained about a proposed lower pay scale for flight
attendants entering USAir through its merger with Pacific Southwest
Airlines.
   ``We didn't promote this action at all. We were shocked this
happened,'' Dee Maki, an AFA spokeswoman, said during a break in
the hearing.
   The hearing is expected to continue Thursday.
   The Railway Labor Act makes it illegal for a union to organize
disruptive job actions during contract negotiations, USAir
spokesman David Shipley said. Talks between USAir and
AFA-represented flight attendants at PSA got underway before
Memorial Day, he said.
   The airline has proposed bringing PSA flight attendants into the
USAir system at a 10 percent salary disadvantage that would
disappear as their pay rises over three years, Ms. Maki said.
   ``They deserve the same money,'' she said. ``They work the same
as anybody else.''
   USAir has a two-tier pay system for its flight attendants, and
the proposal for PSA workers would create two additional tiers, Ms.
Maki said.
   Shipley declined comment on the issue.
   USAir has about 3,000 flight attendants whose base salary is
$40,000 after 10 years on the job. PSA has about 1,000 flight
attendants, Shipley said.
   The union spokeswoman also said USAir does not have enough
flight attendants, and those it has are frequently called in from
off-hours and holidays. They haven't had a pay raise since 1985.
   However, in its complaint, USAir said more than a third of its
flight attendants choose to work beyond 85 hours per month, the
maximum they can be required to work by the airline. They may
volunteer to work an additional 10 hours at straight pay, but their
contract, a two-year pact expiring in August 1989, prohibits
further hours.
   ``Without the regular and predictable willingness of flight
attendants to fly over 85 hours per month, USAir would have to hire
an additional 150 flight attendants,'' Fuhr said in a deposition.
   The Federal Aviation Administration requires a minimum number of
flight attendants on board each plane, depending on the number of
passengers and other factors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
