<1ST_LINE>u f AM-AdvancedTelevisions     06-22 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Advanced Televisions,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Televisions Should Be Compatible With Old, Group Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S.-based organization that includes Japanese
television makers has agreed that a coming generation of improved
televisions should be compatible with the existing broadcast
system, it was announced Wednesday.
   The agreement reached by a committee of the Electronic
Industries Association, while leaving many questions unanswered,
helps resolve a key point of conflict between Japanese TV makers
and the U.S. broadcasting and equipment industry.
   The committee agreed that any system which is finally adopted
should be compatible with the existing broadcast system, and that
``there should be no discernible degradation in the NTSC signal
finally received by the home viewer.''
   NTSC stands for the National Television System Committee and
refers to the existing broadcasting format, which will eventually
be replaced or relegated to a secondary role.
   The committee also agreed that there should be a smooth
transition to the new standard for high-definition television to
protect both the consumers' and broadcasters' investments.
   Japanese television makers have created a version of
high-definition television that is incompatible with the existing
U.S. broadcast system. Since Japanese TV makers are represented on
the committee of the Electronic Industries Association that met
Wednesday in Atlanta, the agreement seems to indicate their
willingness to compromise.
   Sidney Topol, chairman of Atlanta-based Scientific-Atlanta Inc.,
who is chairman of the committee on advanced television, was
scheduled to testify before a congressional committee on the issue
Thursday.
</TEXT>
