<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Hertz-Volvo     06-22 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hertz-Volvo,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Volvo Buying 20 Percent Of Hertz</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Tomas in 6th graf is cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ROCKLEIGH, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Volvo North America Corp. announced
Wednesday it is buying 20 percent of Hertz Corp., the world's
largest car rental company, for $100 million.
   The U.S. branch of the Swedish car manufacturer Volvo said it is
buying the stake from Ford Motor Co., which had held 80 percent of
Park Ridge Corp., the holding company for Hertz. The purchase is to
be completed by July 31.
   Ford now holds 60 percent of Hertz, based in Park Ridge, and the
remaining 20 percent is owned by Hertz executives.
   A Volvo statement said the purchase would allow the company,
based in Rockleigh, to increase its share in the Hertz fleet of
400,000 rental cars. A Volvo subsidiary already runs the Hertz
business in Sweden.
   Hertz has 30,000 employees in 120 countries and last year rented
20 million cars. It has about 33 percent of the U.S. car rental
market.
   Tomas Ericson, a Volvo spokesman, said Hertz's U.S. fleet now
includes between 2,000 and 2,500 Volvos. He said a ``supply
agreement'' would increase the number in the United States and
Europe but declined to disclose the figures.
   ``We felt it was a good investment in a good company,'' Ericson
said.
   ``A spinoff is that more people will experience driving Volvo
cars,'' he said. ``But we're not looking to be the major supplier.
Ford will keep that.''
   Ford and the Hertz employees formed Park Ridge Corp. and bought
the car rental company from Allegis Corp. in December 1987.
Allegis, the parent of United Air Lines, since has changed its name
to UAL Corp.
   Volvo North America was in the picture at the time of that
transaction and kept talks alive until it reached an agreement to
buy part of Ford's stake, Ericson said.
   When Ford bought into Hertz, it said it ultimately planned to
reduce its investment and become a minority owner.
   Ford officials could not be reached for comment Wednesday. Calls
to the company's Detroit office were not returned.
   Joe Russo, a spokesman for Hertz, said Ford wanted to ``bring in
others that would be acceptable to both Ford and Hertz.''
   He said Volvo was attractive because it is part of the car
industry, manufactures a high-quality product and already has cars
in the Hertz rental fleet.
   Ford autos make up more than half of the company's U.S. fleet
and are featured in its advertising, Russo said. The fleet includes
cars by other makers but for competitive reasons Hertz does not
disclose figures, he said.
</TEXT>
