<DOCNO> AP880622-0334 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 1932EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-OptionsProbe     06-22 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Options Probe,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Philadelphia Stock Exchange Investigating Possible Improper
Dealings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The executive vice president of the
Philadelphia Stock Exchange said Wednesday the exchange is
investigating whether deadline rules were violated last week in
stock options traded for Farmers Group Inc.
   In a statement, Richard T. Chase said the investigation focuses
on possible improper dealings in stock options, which may have been
exercised after a 5:30 p.m. deadline last Friday.
   The Wall Street Journal reported in Wednesday's editions that
traders may have made up to $4 million in profits.
   The story said by exercising the stock options after the
deadline traders profited from an unexpected decision by
California's Insurance Commissioner concerning BAT Industries PLC's
$4.5 billion hostile takeover bid for Farmers. The commissioner's
decision was announced about 7 p.m. EDT.
   Commissioner Roxani M. Gillespie ruled that London-based BAT is
barred from acquiring a California insurer such as Farmers because
slightly more than 10 percent of BAT's shares are owned by
government entities, including British local-government pension
funds, according to the newspaper.
   Mrs. Gillespie said in an interview that she delayed the
announcement of her decisions to make sure that Farmers securities
were no longer trading on any exchanges.
   On Monday, Farmers stock plunged $5.25 to $56.75 a share,
creating sizable profits for holders of certain options to sell
Farmers stock, the newspaper story said.
   Chase's statement said the exchange issued a special memo
Friday, ``in response to numerous inquiries,'' that rules required
customers to tell their brokers whether they wanted to exercise the
June Farmers options by 5:30 p.m. Friday.
   ``At this point the exchange believes it has identified all
member firms who exercised options,'' Chase's statement said.
   The exchange is now examining specific transactions, he said.
   The statement said that violators could face ``sanctions, which
include fines, censure or suspension.''
   The June Farmers puts were the most active stock option on the
Philadelphia Exchange on Friday, trading 7,253 contracts, according
to the report. Each contract represents 100 shares.
   William Uchimoto, the acting general counsel for the exchange,
told the newspaper the exchange is investigating dealings in about
10,000 put options, or about one million Farmers shares.
</TEXT>
