<1ST_LINE>u f BC-LTV-Chronology     06-22 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-LTV-Chronology,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-LTV Pensions, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a brief chronology of developments in the dispute
between financially troubled LTV Corp. and the Pension Benefit
Guaranty Corp., the federal agency charged with insuring 30 million
U.S. workers' pensions:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>1986</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   July 17 _ Dallas-based LTV Corp., a giant steel, aerospace and
energy concern files for Chapter 11 Bankruptcy Code reorganization
in New York.
   Dec. 16 _ LTV's steel subsidiary, Cleveland-based LTV Steel Co.,
tells the federal Pension Benefit Guaranty Corp. that it will no
longer contribute to three steel industry pension plans.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1987</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Jan. 12 _ The PBGC, saying the three plans are underfunded by
some $2 billion, terminates them and takes over as trustee of the
pensions for some 77,000 retirees.
   The PBGC, LTV's largest creditor by virtue of the pension plan
takeover, also eliminates benefits that are not covered by its
guarantees, trimming monthly benefits for about 7,000 LTV
pensioners by as much as $400 a month.
   Jan. 16 _ The United Steelworkers of America sues in bankruptcy
court to restore the cut benefits, claiming they have placed severe
hardships on retirees and their families.
   April _ With bankruptcy court approval, LTV Steel makes a single
hardship payment to each retiree, totaling $6.7 million.
   June 25 _ Steelworker local presidents approve a collective
bargaining agreement with LTV Steel, replacing most of the benefits
lost when the PBGC took over the plans. LTV says the pact is
necessary to avoid a crippling strike.
   July 30 _ Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland approves the
LTV-union pact, over the objections of the PBGC which claimed the
company was taking unfair advantage of federal funds to cut costs
and gain labor peace.
   September _ The PBGC shifts responsibility for the pension plans
back to LTV. LTV, claiming the action violates the automatic stay
against actions against debtor companies in reorganization, gets a
bankruptcy court order compelling the PBGC to show why it shouldn't
be held in contempt. The PBGC, in turn, moves to have the issue
heard on the higher, district court level.
   Nov. 24 _ U.S. District Judge Robert Sweet rules the dispute
should be heard in district court level because of ``issues of
national importance ...''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1988</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   June 22 _ Sweet throws out the PBGC decision to turn
responsibility for the pension plans. He says the agency can't
force LTV to reassume the pension obligations based on the evidence
it presented, but says it might be able to establish, at a trial,
LTV's ability to handle the pension funds.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
