<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SuzukiSuit     06-22 0202</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Suzuki Suit,0211</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suit Over Suzuki Samurai Filed In Federal Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New Jersey man has filed a class-action
suit against the maker of the Suzuki Samurai, which has been the
subject of claims that it can roll over when steered sharply to
avoid an accident.
   Paul Asarian said in his federal court suit that American Suzuki
Motor Corp. of Brea, Calif., knew of a design defect as far back as
1985 but didn't tell the public.
   The defect can't be fixed, and even if it could, the value of
his Englewood-bought Samurai would be diminished, Asarian charged.
He is seeking to represent other Samurai owners as a class, damages
and a requirement that the company buy back the vehicles.
   He said 150,000 of the four-wheel drive vehicles have been sold
in the past three years.
   Consumers Union, publisher of Consumer Reports, gave the model
an ``unacceptable'' rating.
   Other suits against Suzuki have been filed in Philadelphia and
Chicago.
   The company could not be reached for comment Wednesday. It
referred calls to its public relations firm, and no one returned a
message from the firm, Rogers & Associates of Los Angeles.
   Suzuki says the vehicle is safe.
</TEXT>
