<1ST_LINE>u f AM-LTV-Miners     06-22 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-LTV-Miners,0574</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retired Miners Picket UMW Offices Over Benefits</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-LTV Pensions, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 200 retired miners fearing the loss of
their health care benefits next month in the bankruptcy court
reorganization of LTV Corp. picketed the offices of the United Mine
Workers Health and Retirement Fund here Wednesday.
   The miners, some accompanied by their wives, complained that the
UMW fund has not yet promised to pick up their health care coverage
when a bankruptcy court-ordered mandate for LTV to continue it
expires July 15.
   However, UMW officials said the company and the union reached an
agreement last week for LTV to continue financing the coverage
until the issue of who is responsible is resolved in either the
bankruptcy or other courts.
   The agreement still has to be approved by a bankruptcy court in
New York, where LTV is being reorganized while seeking protection
from its creditors under Chapter 11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code.
   Wearing placards protesting ``Why do we have to beg for our
health cards?'' some of the miners directed their ire at UMW
President Richard Trumka, while others met with officials at the
union's headquarters five blocks away.
   ``Mr. Trumka sold us down the river on this,'' complained
Raymond Rush, a retired miner from Carmichels, Pa. ``We don't know
whether they are going to pick up our coverage or not.''
   The demonstration was planned before the union was able to
notify the affected UMW-covered LTV retirees and their spouses,
according to John Duray, a union spokesman.
   In a letter dated Tuesday, Trumka told the retirees, ``I have
every reason to believe your medical benefits will continue
uninterrupted and indefinitely.''
   Affected are 1,485 retired UMW members, and their spouses, who
formerly worked at 11 mines in Pennsylvania, Kentucky and West
Virginia that were owned at one time by the giant steel, aerospace
and energy company.
   LTV has left the coal business entirely since filing its
bankruptcy court petition in July 1986. But it has agreed to
continue the benefits forever to about 600 of the miners and their
spouses who worked at five mines sold to other companies.
   LTV, however, maintains that the UMW Health and Retirement Fund
has the obligation under the union's contract with the coal
industry to pick up the health care costs for retirees at five
mines that the company has retained ownership of but closed in the
past two years.
   ``While several legal issues are involved, the bottom line is
simple,'' Trumka said.
   ``Unlike other companies which have refused to pay those
benefits while the issue is being decided in court, LTV will ask
the bankruptcy court to allow the company to continue those
benefits until the issue of responsibility is ultimately resolved.''
   Courts in the past have shifted the obligation for continuing
lifetime health coverage provided under UMW contracts to a benefit
trust established by the union in 1974 as a ``safety net'' to
handle cases where companies go out of business. The industry now
pays 8 cents for every hour worked by a miner into that fund, Drury
said.
   Robert Waime of Nemacolin, Pa., one of the picketing retirees,
said their fear was that they may be without any health coverage
``for weeks'' between the time LTV stopped the benefits and the UMW
fund picks them up.
</TEXT>
