<1ST_LINE>u f AM-ICC-Railroad     06-22 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ICC-Railroad,0524</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ICC Directs Regional Railroad to Take Over D&H Service</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Interstate Commerce Commission moved
Wednesday to assure that shippers on the Delaware & Hudson Railroad
will continue to have rail service after the ailing railroad shuts
down.
   The Delaware and Hudson filed for protection from creditors
under the federal bankruptcy laws earlier this week and had given
notice that it would stop service within days.
   ICC Chairman Heather Gradison said the railroad planned to stop
service at 11:59 p.m. Wednesday.
   As a result, she said, the commission directed in an emergency
order that the New York, Susquehanna & Western Railway, another
regional rail line in the Northeast, assume the service of the D&H.
   The D&H, a subsidiary of Guilford Railroad Co., provides service
over nearly 1,700 miles of track in Vermont, New York,
Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Maryland and Virginia.
   In Cooperstown, N.Y., David Soule, executive vice president of
Delaware & Otsego Corp., parent of the New York, Susquehanna &
Western, said the railroad would take over the D&H operations
whenever it officially stops operations.
   ``At that time we are all set to begin operating on D&H
tracks,'' he said.
   The New York State Department of Transportation had asked the
ICC to take the emergency action, saying the shutdown of the D&H
``will create a transportation crisis in the Northeast.''
   The New York department said in a petition to the ICC that
continued operation of services over the D&H rail network was
essential for the economic well-being of New York State and the
surrounding region.
   The ICC ordered the New York, Susquehanna and Western to provide
the service without compensation for 45 days, during which the
commission would determine what essential services should be
further continued on an emergency basis.
   Both railroads had offered to provide the service without
compensation, as had Conrail. But the ICC said it selected the New
York, Susquehanna and Western over Conrail because the selection
``would raise fewer potential competitive issues during the interim
period.''
   The D&H said last Friday that it planned to file for protection
under Chapter 11 of the federal Bankruptcy Act and did so on
Monday. The railroad cited the collapse of efforts to win labor
concessions as a key reason for the filing, saying that under
current labor contracts it could not run the railroad profitably.
   Guilford officials claimed that the D&H lost $8.1 million last
year and at least $8 million so far this year. Guilford, based in
North Billerica, Mass., bought the railroad in 1984.
   The D&H listed assets of $75.9 million and liabilities of $108.4
million.
   Dennis Watson, an ICC spokesman, said the commission is inviting
offers from other railway lines to take over the D&H lines after
the term of the temporary operation has expired.
   ``The ICC will be conducting an analysis of the D&H lines for
essential service and at least the temporary continuation of
service to critical shipping points that do not receive other
railroad service,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880622-0344 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 2152EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Farmers-Batus     06-22 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farmers-Batus,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Batus Sues California Insurance Regulators Over Rejection of
Takeover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Batus Inc. sued the California Insurance
Department Wednesday, seeking to reverse the department's ruling
that Batus cannot take over Farmers Insurance Group Inc.
   The suit, filed in Los Angeles Superior Court, alleges that
state Insurance Commissioner Roxani Gillespie misinterpreted the
law in denying Batus permission to operate a California insurance
company.
   Ms. Gillespie found the Louisville, Ky., company unfit because a
significant amount of the stock of its parent, BAT Industries PLC
of Britain, is held by government entities.
   The suit also alleged that if Ms. Gillespie's interpretation of
the law were correct, the law would be unconstitutional.
   California is one of nine states where Batus' hostile $4.5
billion takeover effort must be approved by insurance regulators.
Arizona, the only other state to rule, has approved the takeover.
   A spokeswoman said Ms. Gillespie was unavailable to comment on
the suit.
   On Friday, after she issued her ruling, Ms. Gillespie said the
ruling on government ownership was in keeping with previous
commission decisions.
   Farmers' management is resisting a merger with Batus, which is
offering stockholders $63 a share for Farmers stock.
   About 13 percent of BAT stock is owned by more than 100
government and government-related entities, including city councils
and government pension funds in Britain, Batus said.
   Batus noted the commissioner's report didn't find any indication
the government shareholders ever had attempted to influence
business decisions of BAT or Batus.
   The commissioner found Batus met other criteria for ownership of
a California insurer. The commissioner ruled a takeover would not
substantially lessen competition in the industry and that Batus did
notintend to sell Farmers' assets or make substantial management
changes.
   The commissioner discounted arguments that Batus, a tobacco
company, might discontinue non-smoker discounts at Farmers and that
cigarette product liability suits might drain its resources.
   Batus owns paper, tobacco and retailing operations, Saks Fifth
Avenue stores and the maker of Kool cigarettes.
   Farmers is the nations third-largest home and auto insurer and
seventh-largest property and casualty insurer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
