<DOCNO> AP880622-0345 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 2313EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f AM-FCC-Murdoch     06-22 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FCC-Murdoch,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Murdoch Modifies Propsal To Put Station In Trust</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Publisher Rupert Murdoch modified his proposal
to put his Boston television station in an independent trust after
concerns were raised by a public interest law firm.
   Murdoch's News America Publishing Inc. last week proposed the
trust agreement to comply with Federal Communications Commission
rules barring single ownership of a TV station and a daily
newspaper in the same city.
   Under those rules, Murdoch faces a June 30 deadline to dispose
of WFXT-TV, a Boston UHF station, or the Boston Herald newspaper.
   Under terms of the trust agreement, Murdoch would relinquish
control of the station to former Sen. Edward Brooke of
Massachusetts and former New York Gov. Hugh Carey. The station
could be sold for more than $35 million if Murdoch agrees to the
financial terms.
   Murdoch's lawyers amended the proposal this week to add that the
trust managers ``shall use their best efforts'' to sell the station
for a price Murdoch considers reasonable. Additionaly, it adds the
purpose of the trust is not only to comply with the cross-ownership
rules, but also to permit continued operation of the station while
the trust managers find a buyer.
   Andrew Schwartzman, executive director of the Media Access
Project, a Washington, D.C.-based public interest law firm, had
raised concerns that the initial proposal lacked emphasis on the
trust managers' efforts to sell the station.
   Schwarztman, in a filing with the FCC Wednesday on behalf of the
Committee for Media Diversity, a coalition formed to support
retention of the cross-ownership rules, said the group is satisfied
that Murdoch's amended proposal meets the terms of the FCC's policy
on trusts. But the group still questions the ``wisdom and
legality'' of the policy, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
