<1ST_LINE>r f AM-OilSuit     06-22 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Suit,0340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Companies May Get Partial Court Costs in Price-Fixing Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four states that accused the oil industry of
conspiring to create the gasoline shortage of the mid-1970s may
have to pay eight oil companies $1.3 million in court costs
stemming from an adverse court ruling, attorneys said Wednesday.
   The states and the companies agreed to the $1.3 million amount
in a settlement approved here by U.S. District Judge William P.
Gray, who dismissed the states' price-fixing suit in November 1986.
At the time, Gray awarded the companies court costs, but there was
protracted wrangling over the amount.
   However, the states of California, Arizona, Oregon and
Washington have appealed the dismissal of the suit to the 9th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals.
   Gray's order approving the payment of court costs doesn't take
effect unless the companies prevail on appeal, said Mary Elizabeth
Alden, the assistant California attorney general handling the case.
   The $1.3 million award, announced Wednesday by defendant Mobil
Corp. of New York, would be split among Mobil; Atlantic Richfield
Co. of Los Angeles; Chevron Corp. of San Francisco; Gulf Oil Corp.,
now a part of Chevron; Exxon Corp of New York; Shell Oil Co. of
Houston; Texaco Inc. of White Plains, N.Y.; and Unocal Corp. of Los
Angeles.
   The settlement didn't specify how much each state would pay, Ms.
Alden said.
   The states, in suits filed separately between 1973 and 1977,
accused all 16 major U.S. oil companies of conspiring to fix prices
by creating the oil crisis of the mid-1970s. The states sought
unspecified damages that attorneys believed would have totaled
billions of dollars.
   The suits were consolidated before Gray, who ruled in dismissing
the suit that the states hadn't presented any evidence of a
conspiracy.
   The state of Florida originally was a party to the case but
withdrew. Eight of the oil companies settled out of court.
   The appeal is scheduled for a July 15 hearing in Pasadena.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
