<1ST_LINE>r f AM-PSNHBankruptcy     06-22 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PSNH Bankruptcy,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Utility Gets Bankruptcy Plan Extension</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Public Service Company of New Hampshire
on Wednesday received a seven-month extension during which it will
have the exclusive right to offer a bankruptcy reorganization plan.
   Financial problems stemming from its investment in the stalled
Seabrook nuclear power plant prompted company to seek federal
bankruptcy reorganization protection earlier this year.
   The company's period of exclusivity was extended until Dec. 27,
a month less than the utility sought. The original 120-day period
of exclusivity expired May 27.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Court Judge James Yacos also ruled that the
state will have full intervenor standing in the case. He allowed
limited standing to the state's consumer advocate and the Business
and Industry Association on certain issues.
   ``The intended result of this ruling is to grant the state ...
an unquestioned place at the bargaining table,'' Yacos said.
   Standing was denied to the state of Connecticut, Seacoast
Anti-Pollution League, Campaign for Ratepayers' Rights and Citizens
Within a 10-mile Radius, an anti-Seabrook group.
   Nicholas Ashooh, a company spokesman, said the utility was
satisfied with the extension.
   ``We have a lot of work to do between now and then. We'll do our
very best'' to meet the new deadline, he said.
   Yacos said the company has until Feb. 28 to get its
reorganization plan accepted by other parties and creditors.
   The complexities of the finances, regulatory questions and the
uncertain fate of the $5.4 billion Seabrook plant _ completed but
held up in regulatory challenges _ made the extra time essential,
Yacos said.
   He said the case, apparently the fourth-largest in terms of
assets and liabilities, which exceed $2 billion, was unprecedented.
   The utility employs 2,700 people and has annual revenue of more
than $50 million. The utility serves nearly 75 percent of New
Hampshire's population of more than 1 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
