<1ST_LINE>r f AM-FortHoward     06-22 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fort Howard,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Papermaker Gets Buyout Overture From Executives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fort Howard Corp. said Wednesday some of
its executives have indicated they want to purchase the
paper-making company, sending its stock price sharply higher.
   A company statement disclosing the overture did not identify the
people seeking to develop a leveraged buyout proposal, and
indicated no formal offer had been submitted.
   The managers considering a buyout may get backing from interests
outside the corporation, and there was no guarantee the company
would endorse the move, the statement read.
   Fort Howard's stock leaped $8.12{ a share to close at $48.37{ on
the New York Stock Exchange, on the heels of a $1.12{ a share rise
on Tuesday amid buyout speculation.
   Based on Wednesday's closing stock price and Fort Howard's
approximately 67.4 million common shares outstanding, the company
has a market value of about $3.3 billion.
   Fort Howard went public in 1970. Company directors and
executives hold an estimated 7 million of its outstanding common
shares, about 10.4 percent.
   The Green Bay-based company employs 17,000 people worldwide,
including about 3,200 in Wisconsin. It reports annual sales
exceeding $1.5 billion.
</TEXT>
