<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Pillsbury     06-22 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Pillsbury,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pillsbury's Restaurant Head Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of Pillsbury Co.'s full service
restaurant subsidiary has resigned, the company announced Wednesday.
   The resignation of Kyle T. Craig, chairman and chief executive
officer of S&A Restaurant Corp., comes amid a major management
shakeup and follows Pillsbury's loss of a significant market share
in key consumer food businesses to General Mills Inc. and others in
recent months.
   Craig joined Pillsbury's Burger King Corp. in 1978 and has had
responsibility for Pillsbury's full service restaurants, which
include the Steak and Ale and Bennigan's chains, since August 1985.
   Pillsbury Chairman William Spoor recently abolished Pillsbury's
restaurant group superstructure and shuffled executives, who now
report directly to him.
   On Monday, Pillsbury said J. Jeffrey Campbell had resigned as
chairman and chief executive of its restaurant group, which he had
headed since May 1987.
   In a statement on Wednesday, Spoor said Craig had made
significant contributions to the full-service restaurant group and
the company was ``grateful'' to him.
   In recent months, Pillsbury experienced declining sales at
Burger King and its other restaurants.
   In response, the Minneapolis-based food and restaurant business
has closed weak stores, deposed its former chairman, eliminated
more than 200 white-collar employees and taken $141 million in
after-tax charges to restructure around its cornerstone businesses.
   Spoor had reiterated on Tuesday that the company would not sell
Burger King and would resist any takeover attempts. Pillsbury has
been the subject of takeover rumors since last winter, partly
because of its financial performance.
   Next week, the company will report drastically lower net
earnings of about $70 million for fiscal 1988 and slightly improved
sales of $6.2 billion. Operating profits, before writeoffs, will be
up slightly from fiscal 1987.
   Pillsbury plans to invest heavily in its remaining, core
businesses: Burger King; Bennigan's; Distron, its troubled fast
food distribution service; Green Giant; refrigerated dough; frozen
pizza; dessert mix; fish and ice cream.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
