<FILEID>AP-NR-06-22-88 0046EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-TexasS&Ls     06-22 0196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Texas S&Ls,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Large Sale of Savings Units Expected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A large Phoenix savings institution may be
allowed to buy a number of insolvent Texas savings and loan
associations, according to savings industry officials quoted in a
report published Wednesday.
   The New York Times reported that the Federal Home Loan Bank
Board is close to completing a deal that would eventually let
Merabank F.S.B. of Phoenix, a $6.5 billion savings institution,
acquire Texas associations with assets totalling several billion
dollars.
   Merabank plans to enter into an initial agreement to acquire a
few insolvent Texas institutions now, and more soon if the initial
transactions are successful, The Times quoted industry sources as
saying.
   The sources said the first part of the transaction is expected
to be announced soon, as early as Wednesday. It would be the third
in a series of deals announced by the bank board to sell off more
than 150 insolvent thrifts in Texas, Oklahoma and Louisiana with
assets of $50 billion, which have been suffering huge losses due to
depressed real estate prices.
   Officials of both the bank board and Merabank declined comment
on the negotiations, The Times said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
